urther on any specifics relating to the lawsuit.\" Macy's signed a customer bill of rights earlier this month. Civil rights leaders met with retail chain representatives and agreed to create the document. The one-page document is to be posted to the department store websites, which will include Macy's, Barneys New York, Bloomingdales, Lord & Taylor and Saks Fifth Avenue. \"Profiling is an unacceptable practice and will not be tolerated,\" the document states, drafted by the Retail Council of New York State, along with National Action Network and the Rev. Al Sharpton. \"Employees who violate the company's prohibition on profiling will be subject to disciplinary action, up to and including termination of employment,\" the document says. CNN's Rande Iaboni contributed to this report.", "answer": "Halim Sharif, a New York City club promoter, has accused Macy's flagship store in Herald Square of racial profiling after he purchased a $2,400 Louis Vuitton bag on April 19, 2013. According to his lawyer, Kareem Vessup, Sharif was stopped and his purchase was unnecessarily searched by a loss-prevention employee, despite providing a receipt. Sharif claims the employee was dismissive and mishandled his purchase. Vessup also noted that other shoppers who set off the security alarm were not stopped, and none were African-American or Hispanic. Sharif has filed a complaint with Macy's, but has received no response.\n\nThis incident is the third involving Macy's and the fifth overall in New York City this year, where individuals have accused department stores of racial profiling. Vessup also represents Kayla Phillips, who was allegedly stopped by NYPD plainclothes officers after leaving Barneys New York in February.\n\nMacy's has stated that they take such claims seriously and will investigate Sharif's allegation rigorously. The store has a zero-tolerance policy for discrimination and will take immediate action if their policies are found to be violated. Earlier this month, Macy's and other major retailers signed a customer"}
