{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_899308", "question": "Sanlam, the country's second largest life assurer, is planning to undertake a share repurchase totalling some R4-billion as part of its major capital restructuring plans, the company said on Monday.\nAs part of the share repurchase, the group will offer shareholders 12.00 rand per share in a specific pro-rata offering for ten percent of their shares, while also undertaking a voluntary offer to shareholders holding less than 300 Sanlam shares. This will be followed by a share repurchase in the open market.\nSanlam's share price closed on Friday at 11.52 rand, and was last quoted on the JSE at 11.69 rand, up 1.5 percent or 17 cents, in very brisk volumes of some 13.2 million shares so far on the day.\nNews of the share repurchase programme follows formal approval from Sanlam shareholders to sell at least 60 percent of its R124-million shares (21.3 percent interest) in banking group Absa to UK banking group Barclays plc.\nSanlam CEO Johan van Zyl had said at the presentation of the company's year-end results in March this year that it would undertake a major capital restructuring exercise this year, part of which was likely to include a share repurchase scheme. At the time, it estimated it would have excess capital of some R6-billion.\nOn Monday Sanlam said it estimated its excess capital at R7-billion, based on an extensive modeling exercise to determine its future capital requirements.\nAfrican Life to be bought out?\nMarket watchers have speculated that the remaining R3-billion is destined to be used to buy out fellow life insurer African Life (Aflife, in which it has already bought up a substantial stake in the past few months. Aflife has been trading under a cautionary since February 14.\nSanlam said on Monday that the remaining R3-billion had been earmarked for \"profitable structural growth opportunities\" to support the group's strategy of being a diversified financial service provider.\n\"A number of initiatives are being investigated,\" it said. \"If suitable opportunities are not available to be realised within a reasonable time frame and on terms that will add value to Sanlam, the remaining excess will also be returned to shareholders.\"\nIn the proposed offer to shareholders with less than 300 shares, Sanlam will offer a price equal to the volume weighted average market value of the shares traded on the JSE for the five business days immediately preceding Friday, September 16, 2005, plus a 20-cents-per-share premium. Sanlam will have about 650 000 shareholders falling into this category following its pro-rata offer.\nThe proposed schemes are subject to a number of conditions precedent, including 75 percent shareholder approval, as well as that of the High Court.\nJohannesburg - Healthcare companies such as Network Healthcare Holdings must be at least 35 percent owned by black people by 2010, according to a draft charter released by the health ministry yesterday.\n\"Equity ownership should increase to 51 percent by 2014,\" health minister Manto Tshabalala-Msimang said.\nAt least 60 percent of all goods and services procured by health companies \"should be from black-owned firms or black persons by 2010\", rising to 80 percent by 2014, she added.\nNetwork Healthcare, South Africa's biggest hospital owner, agreed to sell a 10 percent stake to black people for about R1 billion in April.\nAt least 60 percent of all healthcare workers should be black, 50 percent of whom must be women by 2010, increasing to 70 percent and 60 percent respectively by 2014, the health minister said.\nBetween 75 percent and 80 percent of South Africans had limited or no access to health services, Tshabalala-Msimang said.\nThe charter aimed to transform the health sector to \"remedy the wrongs of the past\" by improving access, equity and quality in healthcare, and improving levels of black economic empowerment.\nShe said the costs of a recent shoulder operation had showed her how expensive it was becoming to get rid of pain.\n\"I could not believe it. It is just incredible how unaffordable healthcare has become.\n\"If I can tell you how much I paid for that shoulder operation, you will be shocked. It just finished my medical aid - something is wrong.\"\nTshabalala-Msimang said healthcare needed to be developed in the context of \"us being Africans. Surely we can't act as though we are Americans.\"\nAccording to the draft, healthcare expenditure in South Africa was approximately R107 billion in 2003/04, equivalent to 8.7 percent of the annual gross domestic product.\nThe key challenge was not necessarily inadequate resources, but inequitable and inefficient application of resources, the document read.\nIn 2003/04, medical schemes spent about R8 800 per beneficiary, while in the public sector it was R1 050 for people who were not members of medical schemes.\nInequity was also skewed in favour of the urban and private sector: R33.2 billion in the public sector served 37.9 million people, whereas in the private sector R43 billion was available for 6.9 million people.\nBarry Swartzberg, the managing director of Discovery Health Medical Aid, said similar inequities existed in almost every industry.\n\"People in the private sector spend money from their own pocket - it is their choice.\"\nThe department's director-general, Thami Mseleku, countered: \"Government is obliged to ensure that those citizens are also protected, otherwise it is a laissez-faire situation.\"\nThe charter proposes contracting private firms to the state.\nThe deadline for comment is August 15. Thereafter, the charter will be finalised and submitted to the cabinet.\nJohannesburg and Durban - A crippling strike by about 190 000 employees planned for today was averted in the steel and engineering sector after they accepted a 6.8 percent wage offer for the lowest grades and 5.2 percent for higher categories, Dumisa Ntuli, the spokesperson for the National Union of Metalworkers of SA (Numsa), said yesterday.\nHe was speaking after weekend meetings to brief union members about the industry's latest offer. \"Because our bargaining strategy has achieved the desired results, we have called off the strike and will be signing a two-year wage agreement with the Steel Engineering Industries Federation of SA [Seifsa] today,\" Ntuli said.\nThe agreement will be backdated to July 1 and will be extended to those not belonging to Numsa. The deal brings to an end delicate and fragile talks following the initial rejection of union demands by Seifsa.\nThe employers' group said most Seifsa sectors were fighting for survival against external competition, and erosion of local and international markets. This had largely been driven by the strong rand.\nNtuli said the parties had agreed to hold further talks around labour broker arrangements, retirement gratuity pay, shift allowances, leave enhancement pay and severance pay.\nIn another development, the pulp and paper industry has averted a strike that would have involved about 5 000 workers following intensive negotiations over the weekend, resulting in a 6.25 percent across-the-board wage increase with effect from July 1.\nThe agreement between the Employers' Association for the Pulp and Paper Industry, the United Association of SA, which represents artisans in the industry, and the Chemical, Energy, Paper, Printing and Wood Allied Workers' Union (Ceppwawu) put the last-minute brakes on industrial action at Sappi and Mondi mills countrywide.\nMark Albon, Sappi's public relations manager for KwaZulu-Natal, said all Sappi staff had reported for duty as normal yesterday. \"Sappi mills have indicated that their production has not been affected in any way by the threat of action prior to the agreement.\"\nKeith Jacobs, Ceppwawu's deputy general secretary, said all conditions of employment other than the wage increase had remained the same.\n\"In a last-minute bid to avert a strike, we settled at 6.25 percent after the unions and employers' association had deadlocked at 7 percent and 6 percent,\" he said.\nThe bargaining process started at the beginning of May with unions demanding 18 percent and employers offering 2.5 percent.\nMeanwhile, Bloomberg reported that a pay strike by local glass workers affecting Consol and other manufacturers entered a fourth day and the Solidarity union said the action would continue \"indefinitely\" until an agreement was reached.\nMost plants across the country remained closed after workers downed tools on Friday, according to Jaco Marais, a spokesperson for Solidarity.\nMet 'n nuwe fokus op bemarking en die onsekerheid en wisselvalligheid kenmerkend aan gedereguleerde bemarking, het die Nasionale Landboubemarkingsraad groter bestaansreg as ooit tevore, meen die nuwe voorsitter van dié raad.\nSuid-Afrikaanse boere sal nie maklik vergeet wat bemarkingsrade jare lank gedoen het nie: Pryse vasgestel, landbouprodukte gekoop, poele bestuur, agterskotte betaal, markte verwring en oorskotte verwyder. Tot 1996, toe 'n nuwe bemarkingswet alle vorme van beheer en regulering weggeneem het om plek te maak vir 'n vryemarkstelsel.\nNou \"besluit\" die mark wat 'n ton mielies kos, waar dit lonend is om 'n slagplaas te bou en wie al die koring sal koop. Daar ver, in Pretoria, is steeds 'n landboubemarkingsraad met boerelede en ekonome.\nToe 'n parlementslid nou die dag op 'n vergadering van die Portefeuljekomitee oor Landbou en Grondsake vra of die Nasionale Landboubemarkingsraad (NLBR) nog bestaansreg het, was daar nie 'n kort antwoord nie, sê mnr. Mohammad Karaan, senior lektor in landbou-ekonomie aan die Universiteit van Stellenbosch, wat pas as voorsitter van dié raad aangewys is.\nDie lang antwoord, ná 'n uitgerekte onderhoud, was dat die bevordering van bemarking en handel en die insameling van bruikbare inligting om die regte, tydige bemarkingsbesluite te neem, nog nooit méér noodsaaklik vir die voortbestaan van die landbou was nie. \"Ons kan nie die raad toemaak solank daar nog vir hom 'n rol is nie, maar ons moet strategiese aanpas-sings maak.\"\nAnders as sy voorganger, mnr. Godfrey Rathogwa, is Karaan 'n nie-uitvoerende voorsitter. Mnr. Peter Dall, prof. Johan Kirsten en mee. Dora Ndaba en Lilibeth Moolman is weer as lede aangewys. Die nuwe lede is mnre. Zolile Duze, Abe Japhta en Frank Lawrence en mee. Celiwe Maku en Lina Keyter. Hulle hoop om teen 1 Mei 'n hoof uitvoerende beampte met sterk bestuursvaardighede aan te stel.\nDidiza het ook oor die Bemarkingswet 'n duidelike opdrag gegee. Hulle moet die wet bestudeer en verbeter. \"Afskaffing van die wet is nie ter sprake nie.\"\nDie raad het die afgelope paar jaar baie werk oor statutêre heffings gedoen, maar Karaan wil groter klem op bemarking en handel lê. \"Ons moet die fokus skuif na 'n organisasie wat bemarking en handel bevorder. Ons moet wegkom van produksie en beweeg na die markte; dan gaan produksie vanself regkom.\"\nDis nie asof hulle iets nuuts gaan doen nie. Die uitbreiding van markte, promosies en bemarking doen die verskillende maatskappye en bedryfsliggame reeds, maar hulle het meer ondersteuning nodig, meen Karaan.\n\"Eintlik moet die bemarkingsraad 'n forum word vir gesprek oor bemarkingskwessies tussen die Regering en die verskillende bedrywe.\n\"Dit moet 'n bemiddelingsrol speel. Enige bedryf wat 'n bemarkingskwessie aan die Regering wil voorlê, kan saam met die raad 'n voorlegging of plan opstel, wat die raad na die Regering kan neem.\"\nEen van die grootste uitdagings vir die raad is om die bemarkingsfokus van produksie na die verbruiker te verskuif. \"As bemarking nie daaroor gaan om aan verbruikersbehoeftes te voldoen nie, sit ons die pot mis. Die landbou moet produseer wat verbruikers wil hê. Dít is waarby die landbou moet aanpas.\n\"Ons verkoop steeds kommoditeite, maar ons moet wegkom daarvan. Ons moet die nutwaarde sien wat ons produkte bemarkbaar maak en dit aanwakker deur slim promosies en bestuur in die mark. \"Ons moet handel slimmer bevorder. Ons moet innoverend ons produkaanbod verander en markte meer aggressief uitbrei. Maar die staat sal 'n bydrae moet lewer. Dis onregverdig dat maatskappye dit alles self moet doen.\"\nKaraan meen die bemarkingsraad het 'n kritieke rol te speel ten opsigte van onderhandelinge by die Wêreldhandelsorganisasie (WHO). \"Die raad sal sterker leiding moet neem met die samewerking van die bedryf. Daar moet byvoorbeeld 'n sterker bedryfsbetrokkenheid in voorleggings aan die WHO wees. Daar kan nooit te veel navorsing gedoen word ter voorbereiding vir gesprekke daar nie.\"\nDie bemarkingsraad moet ook monitor wat gebeur in die res van die wêreld, waar is oorskotte aan die ontwikkel en navorsing doen na die moontlike uitwerking daarvan op plaaslike markte en pryse. Saam met die bedrywe moet die gevolglike markrisiko's bestuur word.\nEn dis juis waar hy meen een van die bemarkingsraad se belangrikste funksies lê, naamlik om wisselvalligheid in prys, hoeveelheid en wisselkoers beter te help bestuur. \"Ons kan die skommelings nie wegwens nie. Ons moet meer voorkomend optree en meer gesofistikeerde toekomsmarkte en instrumente kry. Nege uit die tien keer is die probleme in die landbou bemarkingsprobleme.\"\nKaraan, wat deeltyds in die Hemel-en-Aardevallei boer, beskryf homself as 'n kapitalis met 'n sosiale verantwoordelikheid. Sy toewyding tot die vrye mark is egter nie so absoluut dat hy glo die mark kan alles regstel nie. \"Die mark is inherent onregverdig en raak meer só gegewe die onregverdige globale speelveld met groter monopolieë, groter en slimmer subsidies en die feit dat dié wat voor is, voor bly.\n\"Die inherente onregverdighede moet beter bestuur word. Die Regering moet toetree, want die mark gaan misluk, maar wanneer hy toetree, gaan dit tydelik wees.\"\nVir steun aan die landbou kan hy regverdiging vind. Hy meen die Regering en die landboubedrywe moet die rol van die landbou in die ekonomie \"herontdek\". En hoewel hy erken dat die landbou se bydrae tot die ekonomie afneem, is daar vele bewyse dat 'n sterk landbou goed is vir ekonomiese groei. Die landbou se rol in landelike ekonomieë word dikwels onderskat, en daarom is dit belangrik dat 'n groter waardering vir die rol van die landbou by die Regering gekweek word.\nKaraan sê die landbou het meer funksies as blote voedselproduksie. Dit is multifunksioneel. Dit bied toerisme-moontlikhede en 'n verantwoordelikheid teenoor die omgewing, veral ten opsigte van bewaring en voogdyskap. \"Die samelewing kry meer uit die landbou as net dít wat hulle op die winkelrakke sien, en juis dít verskaf in 'n mate regverdiging vir oordragte na die landbou.\"\nDie ryk nywerheidslande besef die ekonomies-politieke rol van die landbou terdeë, nie omdat daar veel meer stemme uit die landbou te werf is nie. Vir Karaan beteken steun aan die boere beslis nie dat verbruikers die boere moet betaal nie. \"Steun behoort tot die minimum beperk te word. Ons wil dit slim doen - op 'n manier wat nie die mark sal verwring nie.\"\nHy is versigtig om van beskerming aan boere te praat; hulle moet veel eerder gehelp word om die onregverdighede in die mark te bestuur. \"Onregverdigheid kan in boere se guns werk en kan hulle selfs doeltreffender maak as boere wat subsidies kry. Boere moet besef omdat hulle min ondersteuning kry, maak dit hulle juis besonder mededingend.\n\"Daar sal geen regstreekse subsidies wees nie. Ons kan nie die foute wat in Amerika, Japan en Europa gemaak word, hier dupliseer nie. Dit gaan oor die aard van die ondersteuning - oor inligting eerder as rand en sent - oor onregstreekse ondersteuning in die vorm van geld vir navorsing en promosie.\"\nKaraan ondersteun hoër tariewe om tydelik verligting te bring teen die prysverlagende uitwerking van gesubsidieerde invoerprodukte, maar meen die Suid-Afrikaanse landbou fokus te veel op die bedreiging van subsidies in ryk lande. \"Ons moet ook meeding teen goedkoop arbeid in Derdewêreldlande, soos China en Indonesië. Dis 'n probleem wat nie gaan verdwyn nie.\"\nEweneens gaan die probleme van die Suid-Afrikaanse landbou nie verdwyn as uitvoersubsidies in ander lande afgeskaf word nie.\nDie raad het baie spesifieke ondersteuningsmeganismes vir swart boere in gedagte - nie bloot beter inligtingstelsels of doeltreffender markte nie, maar \"sterker meganismes\" soos minimum pryse, die staat as laaste-uitweg-koper, afset deur staatsinstellings, meganismes om voorraad te dra, of voor- of agterskotte. Aan al die meganismes moet 'n tydsraamwerk gekoppel word en die bedrywe en die Regering moet nou saamwerk. Hierdie aspek en die gepaardgaande integrasie van staatsondersteuning (bv. Casp, Mafisa en grondhervorming) is een van die grootste uitdagings.\nKaraan meen Suid-Afrika het net nie genoeg markinligting om 'n wêreldspeler te word nie. \"Te veel van die regte inligting is in private besit. Ons moet 'n beter openbare inligtingstelsel kry. Ons stel nie belang in statistiek of data nie. Die uitdaging is om data om te skakel in bestuursinligting en bedryfsintelligensie wat in die openbare domein is.\"\nHy meen daar word te min geld bestee aan behoorlike inligtingstelsels en voortydige navorsing oor ekonomie en bemarking. Die graanbedryf is 'n goeie voorbeeld daarvan. \"In die afwesigheid van 'n goeie inligtingstelsel wat probleme betyds bespeur, word die ondersoek nou eers gedoen nadat die probleem ontstaan het.\n\"Ons moet leer uit die graanbedryf se probleme. 'n Mens wil nie onsimpatiek wees nie, maar dit het óók te doen met boere se voorkeur vir produksie en dikwels te min aandag aan bemarking, swak bestuur, te veel geleende geld en omdat baie boere nie spaar wanneer dit goed gaan nie.\"\nKaraan erken dat die sowat R13 miljoen wat vanjaar vir die raad se werksaamhede begroot is, \"nie naastenby\" genoeg is om die uitdagings wat die bemarking van die Suid-Afrikaanse landbou bied, aan te pak nie. \"Selfs saam met die geld uit heffings is dit nie genoeg nie. As ons meer ondersteuning wil gee en markbevordering en waardetoevoeging wil doen, handel en markte wil uitbrei, het ons meer hulpbronne nodig. Vanjaar sal die begroting nog genoeg wees om die rekeninge te betaal, maar in die toekoms sal die raad beslis meer geld moet kry.\"\nSynde 'n landbou-ekonoom en akademikus met 'n groot betrokkenheid by swart bemagtigingsinisiatiewe, meen mnr. Mohammad Karaan, nuwe voorsitter van die Nasionale Landboubemarkingsraad, dat die verskillende bedrywe groter inisiatief moet neem om bemagtiging en grondhervorming te bestuur en te beheer, maar dat aansporing van regeringskant moet kom.\n\"Kanaliseer van die grondhervormingsgeld na die bedrywe, sodat hulle 'n groter verantwoordelikheid aanvaar vir hervorming wat bedryfsin maak. Dit sal groeigeleenthede bring en die samelewing sal meer vertroue in hulle hê.\"\nHy sê Suid-Afrika is nie werklik 'n landbouland nie, tog is die meeste kommersiële boere produktief in toestande wat sub-optimaal is. As toestande beter is, kan hulle floreer. Karaan sê dié boere moet nuttig gemaak word vir die toekoms. Swart boere gaan die ondersteuning en kundigheid van wit boere nodig hê. \"Daardie kundigheid is waarskynlik ons bes-te bron van mededingendheid in die toekoms.\"\nKaraan sê daar is nog te veel wantroue en spanning in die verhouding tussen die landbou en die Regering. 'n Groot deel van dié wantroue kom van die bedryf se kant. Dit het moontlik gelei tot die ingesteldheid van die Regering om sy eie ding te wil doen, sonder die wit boere. Karaan sê dit verteenwoordig nie 'n beweging na 'n hoër moraliteit en groter wysheid nie. \"Skakeling tussen die bedryf en die staat moet nie op spanning, wantroue, ras of die geskiedenis gegrond wees nie, eerder op ekonomiese insig, wysheid, sosiale kapitaal en die toekoms.\"\nOok in dié opsig glo hy kan die bemarkingsraad help om 'n beter benadering te vestig. Hy sou ook wou sien dat die voorste bedryfsleiers en die Regering meer gereeld vergader en praat oor handel, pryse, verbruik, invoer, produksie, neigings - al die veranderlikes wat nodig is om verskillende strategieë, taktiek en scenario's op te stel.\nVir die Suid-Afrikaanse landbou is daar 'n beter toekoms as wat mense soms dink. \"Ons moet ons nie blind staar teen die probleme en krisisse nie, want dit krimp ons horisonne. Ons moet produksie en markte uitbrei anderkant ons landsgrense. As ons die landbou wil red, moet ons dit hanteer soos enige ander besigheid, met hoër doeltreffendheid, groter visie en meer sensitiwiteit teenoor wêreldneigings.\"\nLede van die Landboubemarkingsraad (LBR) se nuwe raad moes weer die kwessie rondom sy toepaslikheid tydens die voorlegging van sy begroting aan die parlement se portefeuljekomitee oor landbou in die gesig gestaar.\nHoewel mnr. Neo Masithela, voorsitter van die portefeuljekomitee, lede versoek het om liefs nie nou hierdie debat aan te raak nie, het dr. Kraai van Niekerk, die DA se woordvoerder oor landbou, gesê dit is 'n belangrike vraag of die LBR nog in die toekomstige Suid-Afrika tersaaklik gaan wees en of daar nie tans heelwat duplisering van funksies in hierdie liggaam bestaan nie.\nHy sê die sowat R1,8 miljoen wat deur die staat vir dié funksies begroot word, kan doeltreffender benut word deur die bemarkingsraad se werk na die ekonomiese afdeling van die Departement van Landbou oor te dra. \"Die aksieplanne van die LBR in die nuwe jaar is toenemend gemik op terreine wat reeds deur ander organisasies en departemente uitgevoer word,\" het hy gesê.\nDie DA vra dat die Bemarkingsraad so gou moontlik afgeskaf en sy funksies aan bestaande departemente oorgedra word.\nMnr. Peter Dall, 'n lid van die raad, sê die oorblywende bemarkingsrade is amper uitgefaseer. Hy sê hoewel hierdie rade nie meer funksioneer nie, is hulle steeds in die statute vervat en dat daar huidig 'n memorandum aan me. Thoko Didiza, die Minister van landbou, voorgelê is. Hy verwag dat die rade binnekort heeltemal afgeskaf sal wees.\nMasithela is bekommerd dat daar die afgelope vier jaar lank nog geen bemarking in die Vrystaat, Noord-Kaap of Mpumalanga plaasgevind het nie. \"Daar kan nie net op die Wes-Kaap gefokus word nie,\" het hy gesê.\nMe. Dora Ndaba, die ondervoorsitter en waarnemende hoof uitvoerende beampte, en mnr. Mohammad Karaan, nuwe voorsitter van die LBR, was by die voorlegging teenwoordig.\nBlue Ear Disease broke out last year in the Western Cape and we had an eradication program in place but in April this year, another lot of infected pigs were picked up and we’ve been searching all the farms around.\nWe have got about 116 farms that have been infected, i.e. farms and smallholdings. At this stage, we slaughtered out in the region of 10 706 pigs. Financial loss is very difficult to estimate, but it will be running into the millions, mainly because there are a lot of small farmers; emerging farmers who tweak out a living with a few pigs; and then the commercial farmers have been affected pretty bad as well.\nThe vetinary department, state department-Western Cape have introduced a permit system, that all pigs in the Western Cape or Boland area can only be moved under permit. This permit system will carry on right up to December, and we will still search to see if we find more infected pigs in that period.\nThe farms that have been put under quarantine will remain under quarantine for 8 weeks after the last pigs have been slaughtered and then they will be allowed to introduce pigs again. All those farms will have to be disinfected and cleaned, and they have to stand dormant for at least 8 weeks.\nDuring our negotiations with the Minister of Agriculture in the Western Cape, Mr Kobus Dowrie, we told him that we would slaughter at our own cost as commercial farmers, as long as he made money available to slaughter all the emerging farmer’s pigs, which he agreed to.\nThe assurance that I can give consumers is that pork is a 100% safe to eat, it has no effect on humans whatsoever, this virus only affects pig and only affects their lungs and reproductive system, and it doesn’t affect any other animals.\nAt this stage we have had very good cooperation from all our emerging farmers and our big commercial farmers. We have a few small farmers who seem to be flaunting the regulations that have been put in place and we plead to them not to flaunt it, it just puts the whole industry in danger.\nDie landbou in Suid-Afrika sal nié die verwagte styging in die brandstofprys kan akkommodeer sonder dat die bedryf self skade ly nie, sê mnr. P.A. von Wielligh, voorsitter van die TLU SA se energiekomitee.\n\"Vanuit 'n landbouperspektief word vraagtekens geplaas op die doeltreffendheid in die metode van vasstelling van brandstofpryse (wat juis tydens ons voorbereiding vir en tydens planttyd self, 'n hoogtepunt skyn te bereik), die belastingimplikasie en die wyse waarop die Regering dit saamstel asook Sasol se rol in hierdie proses,\" sê hy.\nVerdere ongelukkigheid spruit voort uit die hardnekkige gerugte rakende die verspreiding van brandstof vanaf Suid-Afrika na buurlande wat hierdie selfde brandstof verkoop teen baie goedkoper as waarvoor dit in Suid-Afrika beskikbaar is.\nAangesien Suid-Afrika tans ongeveer 40 % van sy eie brandstof vervaardig en slegs die res invoer, behoort daar ook 'n besparing te wees wat na die verbruiker deur gegee kan word.\nMnr. Von Wielligh sê die TLU SA stel voor dat die Regering weens die golwende effek binne die oliebedryf meer goedkoop voorrade moet bekom en dit opberg om die finansiële impak van stygende pryse op die verbruiker te beperk. Die egalisasiefonds kan gebruik word om hierdie doel te bereik.\nFuel accounts for ± 10% of direct agricultural costs in SA. This percentage equates to R3,8 billion per year. Using this figure as basis, one can determine the effect of a 1 cent/litre change in the fuel price, which is around R10m a year. The wholesale price of diesel has risen by 35% from July 2004 to July 2005.\nWhat practical effect does this have?\nA fuel-intensive industry, e.g. maize production, requires 80-100 litres of fuel per ha. The effect of the price hike is to increase costs by R133/ha. This is a direct effect attributable simply and solely to the increase.\nIn 2000 we negotiated with Government to be paid back that portion of the fuel price, which goes toward fuel tax and the Road Accident Fund. Though it insisted on certain conditions, Government approved the rebate and farmers are currently paid back an amount of 71,5c/l.\nI think the time has come to ask Government to readjust this amount. Farmers still pay fuel tax of 60c per litre, and this is where we intend asking Government for relief.\nThe way in which prices are set is reasonably transparent. Shipping, evaporation and international factors can cause these price fluctuations, so we’re not asking for an investigation into the changes. We’re asking Government to adjust the rebate to accommodate short-term crises, specifically in the grain industry.\nIt’s not a subsidy; it’s a rebate on a tax payment that seriously jeopardises our ability to compete internationally. Unfortunately the news isn’t good. Chances are that the diesel price will rise again next month – by more than 60c.\nWhat can farmers do about it?\nObviously they can start stocking up on the diesel they’ll need later on, but I think they should negotiate with diesel wholesalers as well. There’s a 40c margin on wholesale diesel. I think even suppliers realize that farmers’ livelihoods are under threat. From this starting point I think negotiations to decrease that margin, even if it is only on the short-term, may prove fruitful. It is quite possible.\nThe National Agricultural Land Forum consists of land owners who have been affected by land claims. In every area where land claims have been gazetted, landowners’ organisations are formed. This is coordinated at a provincial level.\nThe National Agricultural Land Forum is made up of these provincial structures. Where the upcoming National Land Summit will focus more on political issues and land reform as a whole, we focus on the economic implications of land claims. We look at the road ahead. What are the nuts and bolts of the situation? How will local economies, especially those in rural towns, be maintained?\nThis conference is only one of the ways in which we communicate with Government. Earlier today we were told by international investors that they can’t move money here while there is still uncertainty; they need a firmer base.\nThe result is very little development in this area over the last few years. It’s a problem that must receive urgent attention. There’s no alternative for agriculture in this province. Agriculture can’t be separated from land.\nWe’re asking Government.. to discuss the relationship between agriculture and land with us. Together, we can make plans to maintain this relationship.\nThere is a path open to us. SA has an excellent Restitution Act; the people who wrote it really knew what they were doing. The problem lies in its implementation.\nThe Act allows for every claim to be negotiated. We’re asking that this option be exercised more. If we can create forums involving all the relevant role players, e.g. local businessmen, landowners, claimants, organised agri, NAFU, Agri SA and the Transvaal Agricultural Union.\nSolutions can be found that way. The reason everything looks so bleak is because one body (The Land Claims Commission) has taken everything onto itself and is serving its own agenda, even outside provincial structures.\nWe’re aware that the Expropriation Act is being rewritten. We don’t know what it will look like in future, but the current Expropriation Act is almost an improvement on our current situation.\nIt the Expropriation Act is used, farmers must be paid the full value of their land. They must also be paid for improvements made, for any business conducted on the property, and even for the relocation of his assets. This isn’t what’s happening at the moment. Farmers are being offered 50-75% of what their land has been valued at.\nWe as landowners are incredibly frustrated by the workings of the Land Claims Commissioner’s office. Firstly, it is unable to handle claims effectively – there’s a definite lack of administrative ability. Some gazetted claims are erroneous or incomplete, making it necessary to correct them.\nResearch is also of a poor quality: conflicting claims have been allowed on one property, bringing the whole process to a halt. We have to pay for expensive research to investigate the validity of claims. If a case goes to the Land Claims Court, we have to pay legal fees as well. All this is a tremendous frustration – on top of which there is a lack of communication from the Commissioner with us landowners.\nWe’ve contacted the new DG of the Department of Agriculture. His office was more sympathetic than that of the Land Claims Commissioner. All we heard from there is that he was upset by our criticism of the process.\nNandi Mandela, the Durban-based chairperson of Class A Cables, an electrical supply company that won a contract to supply the council with materials, has lashed out at allegations that she won the work because of her name.\n\"In my entire work experience I have never asked for any favours, nor do I believe I have received favours because of my surname,\" she said on Monday.\nMandela, granddaughter of Nelson Mandela, was reacting to allegations by Durban businessman T P Ndlazi that the eThekwini municipality was only awarding lucrative tenders to those with political connections.\nHe cited as an example how Class A Cables won a share of a multimillion-rand contract to supply electrical cable to the city, claiming his prices were cheaper and that Class A was sourcing the cabling from India.\nAlthough Ndlazi TP Electrical scored a portion of what he said was a R45-million-a-month contract, he claimed he had only been contracted to supply the least popular cable, while Class A would supply the most popular. He appealed in December.\nThe council said it had rescinded the award to Class A, but neither Ndlazi nor Mandela had officially been informed.\nSeveral people contacted The Mercury making similar claims.\nMandela said Class A was established five years ago and was a \"true black economic empowerment\" company that was in negotiations with its Indian-based supplier around establishing a R50-million cable manufacturing plant in Durban.\nClass A Cables is not in the telephone directory and, according to the department of trade and industry's register, the company was formed last July.\nThe directors are Raju Chetty, Raj Chetty, Rajgopal Chetty, Thembinkosi Madikane, Vaughan Charles, Nandi Mandela and Sipho Magwaza.\nThe tender in dispute was advertised in November 2003, with promises of an award in January 2004, according to Ndlazi. However, it was finally awarded a year later.\nIn response to questions, Mandela could not explain how the company had tendered for the work when it did not exist at the time. She said Class A Cables had been previously registered as \"Transcreations\".\nShe said the Chetty family were involved in the day-to-day running of the business. \"As chairperson I share expertise in respect of strategic direction.\"\nMandela said Class A was sourcing its cable from an Indian company, \"the second largest global manufacturer\" of electrical cables. To source cables locally would mean securing material from competitors.\nThe bid to establish the plant in Durban, using Indian \"help... and expertise\", was aimed at breaking the \"monopoly in the cable manufacturing industry, which is still white dominated\".\nMandela's statement reads: \"The company (Class A Cables) will set up the first black-owned electric manufacturing plant which will be worth more than R50-million within two years of receiving the first order from the municipality.\"\nMandela was \"dismayed\" to read that her company's contract had been rescinded.\nDerek Naidoo, deputy municipal manager, Procurement and Infrastructure, was quoted as saying the council had done a rethink on the award to Class A Cables \"and now it has zero\". That portion of the tender would be readvertised.\nMandela described Ndlazi's suggestion that Class A Cables got the contract because of her name as \"grossly insulting\".\nThe African Christian Democratic Party called for a review of the tender process. Echoing this was the Black Contractors' Forum, whose Jabulani Ngcobo said the tender process needed to be investigated and an impartial body established to consider appeals against the process.\nMunicipal Manager Michael Sutcliffe, who heads the tender appeal process, promised to respond.\nA Limpopo motorist has been charged with faking a hijacking to avoid getting into trouble with his father.\nThe 23-year-old man is expected to appear in the Mokopane magistrate's court soon on a charge of perjury.\n\"He allegedly claimed that two armed robbers hijacked him while he was driving his father's minibus taxi, but it appears he was trying to cover up after being involved in an accident,\" said Waterberg police spokesperson Captain Gabashane Moseki on Monday.\nThe man was driving along the road between Mawhelereng and Roedtan at about 4pm on Saturday when he apparently lost control of the vehicle and hit a tree.\nHe was not injured, but the minibus was badly damaged. He was alone in the vehicle.\nThe man then went home and told his father that the minibus had been hijacked.\nThey reported the case at Mawhelereng police station. \"The suspect even cried loudly, claiming that he nearly lost his life after the hijackers pointed firearms at him. We felt pity for him,\" said Moseki.\nPolice mobilised several units, including the crime prevention and the serious and violent crime units, and found the minibus at the accident scene.\nPolice initially thought the robbers had crashed it, but upon further investigation they found the hijacking was a hoax.\nMoseki warned the public against making false reports and wasting the police's time and resources.\n\"It is expensive to follow up a hijacking case or any other case that requires manpower, vehicles, telephones and time,\" she said.\nMoseki said the maximum sentence for perjury was three years in jail, with or without the option of a fine.\nSenior Pretoria police officers will begin an investigation on Monday into the conduct of the Garsfontein police station commissioner and his staff after the resignation from that station of 22 police reservists.\nThe reservists resigned last week after they were allegedly ordered to patrol the station's jurisdiction without bulletproof vests, firearms, torches or handcuffs - which is against standing police orders.\nThe reservists have transferred to Brooklyn and Lyttelton police stations, and the flying squad.\nThe investigation will look at eight grievances laid against Garsfontein police station commissioner Senior Superintendent Frans Manyaka and the station's crime prevention unit commander.\nThe investigation is to be conducted by Pretoria's deputy police area commissioner, Director Nic Sithole, and Senior Superintendent Johan Brits.\nA list of grievances, a copy of which was made available to the Pretoria News, reveals that the day before the police station's reservists were to conduct operations, over the weekend of June 24 to 26, all their equipment, including firearms and bulletproof vests, was confiscated.\nThe station commissioner allegedly told the reservists that if they did not like the situation they should work elsewhere.\nOther grievances include the failure of Garsfontein police station's senior staff to communicate with reservists about meetings, operations and other important issues relating to day-to-day policing.\nA reservist said another major grievance was that the station commissioner accused reservists of failing to perform their duties despite 150 wanted criminals being arrested by them in the first five months of the year.\n\"What is happening here is ridiculous.\n\"We all volunteer our time to protect our suburb yet we are being deliberately prevented from doing so by the station commissioner,\" said the reservist.\n\"On the weekend that our equipment, including vehicles, was taken away, we were still ordered to conduct special operations.\n\"We refused to work, even though we were told that we would be charged with misconduct,\" the reservist said.\n\"The station commissioner is completely incompetent and should be removed from his position immediately.\n\"Unless something is done soon there are going to be no staff left at the police station,\" he said.\nGarsfontein Community Policing Forum chairman Nic Pascoe said the reservists definitely had grounds for their grievances.\n\"We are extremely alarmed by the situation as our community cannot afford to loose any of these reservists.\n\"In fact, we are desperate for reservists at Garsfontein police station, where they make up more than 50 percent of the station's operational members,\" Pascoe said.\nPolice spokesperson Superintendent Morné van Wyk confirmed that the reservists had transferred to other stations as a result of internal conflict but denied they made up 50 percent of the station's operational members.\n\"These reservists are not an integral part of the station,\" he said.\n\"An internal investigation into the grievances is being conducted.\"\n\nWhat drastic action did the Garsfontein police station commissioner take the day before reservists were to conduct weekend operations that led to the reservists' resignation?", "answer": "Based on the details in the article, the day before the Garsfontein police station reservists were to conduct weekend operations, the police station commissioner confiscated all their equipment, including firearms and bulletproof vests. Specifically:\n\n\"The list of grievances, a copy of which was made available to the Pretoria News, reveals that the day before the police station's reservists were to conduct operations, over the weekend of June 24 to 