{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_116302", "question": "Write a Python function `at_least_two_true` that receives two binary predicates (functions that return boolean values) as arguments and returns a new predicate that returns True if at least two of the original predicates return True. If either predicate returns False, the new predicate should return False. If both predicates return False, the new predicate should return False, but if both predicates return True, the new predicate should return True.\n\nThe provided predicates should have the same signature and accept the same arguments. The new predicate must accept the same arguments as the original predicates. The function must validate that both predicates are boolean predicates.", "answer": "Here's how you can do it in Python:\n\n```python\ndef at_least_two_true(pred1, pred2):\n    assert callable(pred1) and callable(pred2), \"Both predicates must be functions\"\n    \n    def new_predicate(*args):\n        return pred1(*args) and pred2(*args)\n    return new_predicate\n```\n\nThe `assert` statement checks that both predicates are functions. The `new_predicate` function uses the `*args` syntax to accept the same arguments as the original predicates. It then returns True if both predicates return True, and False otherwise."}
