{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_185706", "question": "The length of time between arrivals of vehicles at an intersection follows an exponential distribution with a mean of 10 seconds. What is the probability that the time between arrivals will be 15 seconds or less, and what is the probability that the time between arrivals will be between 10 and 15 seconds?", "answer": "To find the probability that the time between arrivals will be 15 seconds or less, we can use the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the exponential distribution. The CDF of an exponential distribution is given by:\n\nF(x) = 1 - e^(-x/λ)\n\nwhere λ is the mean of the distribution, and x is the value of interest. In this case, λ = 10 and x = 15.\n\nF(15) = 1 - e^(-15/10) \n       = 1 - e^(-1.5) \n       ≈ 1 - 0.2231 \n       ≈ 0.7769\n\nSo, the probability that the time between arrivals will be 15 seconds or less is approximately 0.7769, or 77.69%.\n\nTo find the probability that the time between arrivals will be between 10 and 15 seconds, we can use the probability density function (PDF) of the exponential distribution and integrate over the range of interest. Alternatively, we can subtract the cumulative probability up to 10 seconds from the cumulative probability up to 15 seconds:\n\nF(15) - F(10) = (1 - e^(-15/10)) - (1 - e^(-10/10))\n               ≈ 0.7769 - (1 - e^(-1))\n               ≈ 0.7769 - (1 - 0.3679)\n               ≈ 0.7769 - 0.6321\n               ≈ 0.1448\n\nSo, the probability that the time between arrivals will be between 10 and 15 seconds is approximately 0.1448, or 14.48%."}
