{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_110598", "question": "Write an engaging first scene for a young adult novel about life in a future where memories can be implanted, edited, and even stolen.", "answer": "As she lay in bed, 17-year-old Maya stared up at the ceiling, the soft glow of her comms device casting an ethereal light on her face. Her eyes fluttered closed, and the familiar hum of the memory sync program whirred to life in her mind. The download began, and fragments of a summer vacation she'd never actually experienced began to unfurl like a home movie. She felt the warmth of sun-kissed skin, the taste of saltwater taffy, and the sound of seagulls wheeling overhead.\n\nBut something was off. The memories felt...grafted on, like a hasty addition to a patchwork quilt. Maya's eyes snapped open, and she sat up, her heart racing. She'd always known her parents had gifted her these manufactured memories, hoping to fill the gaps in her own fractured past. Yet, tonight, the artificial recollections seemed hollow, even false.\n\nMaya tossed aside her covers and swung her legs over the side of the bed. Her gaze drifted to the shelf where a single, antique photograph sat framed – a faded snapshot of her as a toddler, standing beside her mother on a windswept beach. This was the only genuine memory she possessed, one that predated the accident that had ravaged her mind and necessitated the implants.\n\nA sudden urge seized her, and Maya carefully removed the frame from the shelf. She turned it over, running her thumb along the intricate patterns etched into the silver backing. A small inscription, hidden from view, was engraved there: \"Remember me.\" A shiver ran down her spine as she realized the words were new – or, at least, new to her. Who had written this, and what did they mean? For the first time, Maya wondered if her memories – false and true alike – were more than just recollections. Were they also clues?"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_865693", "question": "A dataset of exam scores has a mean of 80 and a standard deviation of 10. If each score in the dataset is increased by 5 points, what is the new mean and standard deviation of the dataset?", "answer": "When each score in the dataset is increased by 5 points, the mean will also increase by 5 points. This is because the mean is the average of all scores, and adding a constant value to each score shifts the entire distribution upward by that same value. Therefore, the new mean of the dataset is 80 + 5 = 85.\n\nAs for the standard deviation, it remains unchanged at 10. The standard deviation measures the spread or dispersion of scores from the mean. Since adding a constant value to each score shifts all scores equally, the relative distances between scores and the mean remain the same. As a result, the spread of scores, and thus the standard deviation, remains unchanged."}
