{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_319415", "question": "If the annual increase in the population of a town is 10% and the present number of people is unknown, the population will be 15730 in 2 years. What is the present population of the town?", "answer": "Let's denote the present population of the town as P.\n\nAccording to the given information, the population increases by 10% each year. Therefore, after one year, the population will be P + 10% of P, which can be written as:\n\nP + 0.10P = 1.10P\n\nAfter two years, the population will increase by another 10%, so we will take the population after one year (1.10P) and increase it by 10%:\n\n1.10P + 0.10 * 1.10P = 1.10 * 1.10P = 1.21P\n\nWe are given that after two years, the population will be 15730. Therefore, we can set up the equation:\n\n1.21P = 15730\n\nNow, we can solve for P:\n\nP = 15730 / 1.21\nP = 13000\n\nSo, the present population of the town is $\\boxed{13,000}$  people."}
