{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_376581", "question": "How to know if a number is a power of two\n```python\ndef is_power_of_two(n):\n    \"\"\"Returns True if n is a power of two, False otherwise\"\"\"\n    return n != 0 and (n & (n - 1)) == 0\n```\nHow does that function work?", "answer": "The function works by utilizing a property of binary numbers. In binary, powers of two have exactly one bit set to 1, while all other bits are 0. For example:\n\n- 8 (2^3) is 1000 in binary\n- 16 (2^4) is 10000 in binary\n- 32 (2^5) is 100000 in binary\n\nWhen you subtract 1 from a power of two, you get a number that has all the bits set to the right of the leftmost 1 in the original number. For example:\n\n- 8 (1000) minus 1 is 7 (0111)\n- 16 (10000) minus 1 is 15 (01111)\n- 32 (100000) minus 1 is 31 (011111)\n\nUsing the bitwise AND operator (&) on these two numbers will result in 0, because there are no bits that are set in both numbers.\n\n- 8 (1000) & 7 (0111) is 0 (0000)\n- 16 (10000) & 15 (01111) is 0 (00000)\n- 32 (100000) & 31 (011111) is 0 (000000)\n\nTherefore, if `n` is a power of two, `n & (n - 1)` will be 0.\n\nThe `n != 0` check is necessary to handle the case where `n` is 0, which is not a power of two.\n\nThis function is a concise and efficient way to check if a number is a power of two, as it only requires a single bitwise operation and a comparison."}
