{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_722507", "question": "Write a Python function `split_and_join` that takes a string as an argument and performs the following operations:\n\n1. split the string on a space delimiter and return the result as a list of words\n2. join the words using a hyphen delimiter and return the result as a single string\n\nUse Python's built-in functions and methods to achieve the desired functionality.\n\nYour code should pass the following assertion:\n```python\nassert split_and_join(\"this is a string\") == \"this-is-a-string\"\n```", "answer": "Here is a Python function that implements this logic:\n\n```python\ndef split_and_join(string):\n    \"\"\"\n    Splits the input string on a space delimiter, joins the resulting words\n    using a hyphen delimiter, and returns the resulting string.\n    \"\"\"\n    words = string.split()  # split on space delimiter\n    return \"-\".join(words)  # join using hyphen delimiter\n```"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_496779", "question": "A snail is at the bottom of a 20-foot well. Each day, it climbs up 3 feet, but at night, it slips back 2 feet. How many days will it take for the snail to reach the top of the well?", "answer": "Let's break down the snail's movement pattern. It climbs 3 feet during the day and slips back 2 feet at night, so the net distance it covers each day is 1 foot. However, when the snail is close enough to the top, it will climb out of the well and not slip back. \n\nIf we subtract the 3-foot climb from the 20-foot well depth, we can see that on the 18th day, the snail will climb to the top and escape. To explain, the snail will climb 3 feet from the 17-foot depth it reached after slipping back the previous night (17 + 3 = 20). On that final day, it won't slip back because it has already escaped the well.\n\nSo, it will take the snail 18 days to reach the top of the well."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_46104", "question": "In the positive arithmetic sequence $\\{a_n\\}$, the equation $\\frac{a_{41}+a_{42}+...+a_{60}}{20}=\\frac{a_{1}+a_{2}+...+a_{100}}{100}$ holds. Determine the similar conclusion in the positive geometric sequence $\\{b_n\\}$.", "answer": "[Analysis]\nThis question examines the property of arithmetic sequences to derive the property of geometric sequences. It is a moderate difficulty problem.\n\n[Answer]\nCombining the properties of arithmetic and geometric sequences, we can draw a parallel to the given conclusion:\nIn the positive geometric sequence $\\{b_n\\}$, the similar conclusion is $\\boxed{\\sqrt[20]{b_{41}b_{42}b_{43}...b_{60}} =\\sqrt[100]{b_{1}b_{2}b_{3}...b_{100}}}$."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_351779", "question": "Heat kernels on cone of $AdS_2$ and $k$-wound\ncircular Wilson loop in $AdS_5 \\times S^5$ superstring\n\nR. Bergamin\nDipartimento di Fisica e Astronomia “Galileo Galilei\"\nUniversità degli studi di Padova, Via Marzolo 8, 35131 Padova, Italy\nA. A. Tseytlin1\nThe Blackett Laboratory, Imperial College, London SW7 2AZ, U.K.\n\n– Submission Data Authors: R. Bergamin and A. A. Tseytlin Report No.: Imperial-TP-AT-2015-07 Title: Comments: pages. Abstract:\n\nIntroduction and summary\n\nIn this paper, which is a sequel to Appendix B in, we shall consider the computation of the disc partition function for the $AdS_5 \\times S^5\\ $superstring $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{0} Z= e^{- {\\Gamma}} \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\qquad {\\Gamma}= {\\Gamma}_0 + {\\Gamma}_1 +... \\end{aligned}$$ for the euclidean minimal surface of ending on $k$-wound circle at the boundary. Here the expansion is in inverse powers of the string tension $T= { {\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\ \\over 2\\pi}$ and we will be interested in first subleading (1-loop) correction ${\\Gamma}_1$.\n\nThe string partition function should be representing the expectation value $\\langle W \\rangle$ of the circular Wilson loop in $k$-fundamental $SU(N)$ representation in dual ${\\cal N}=4$ SYM theory taken in the limit $N\\to \\infty$ and then expanded in large ‘t Hooft coupling $\\lambda$ for fixed $k$. The well-known exact expression for $\\langle W \\rangle$ in the planar approximation gives $$\\begin{aligned} && \\langle W \\rangle ={ 2 \\over k {\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\ } {I}_1 ( k {\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\ )= e^{- {\\hat \\Gamma}} \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\qquad {\\hat \\Gamma}= {\\hat \\Gamma}_0 + {\\hat \\Gamma}_1 +... \\, \\label{1} \\\\ && {\\hat \\Gamma}_0 = - k {\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\ \\, \\qquad \\qquad \\textstyle{\\hat \\Gamma}_1 = {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} \\ln { \\pi \\over 2} + { 3 \\over 2} \\ln k + { 3 \\over 2} \\ln {\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\ \\. \\label{b3} \\end{aligned}$$ Assuming that the planar $k$-fundamental circular Wilson loop is indeed represented by the open string path integral in $AdS_5 \\times S^5\\ $with the boundary condition that the disc-like world sheet ends on $k$-wound circle at the boundary the corresponding minimal surface in, e.g., $AdS_3$ with the metric $ds^2 = z^{-2} ( dr^2 + r^2 d \\phi^2 + dz^2 )$ is described by $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{2} \\phi = k \\tau\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ z= \\tanh k \\sigma\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ r= \\cosh^2 k \\sigma\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ z= \\sqrt{1- r^2} \\, \\end{aligned}$$ where $\\tau \\in (0, 2 \\pi)\\, \\ \\sigma\\in (0, \\infty)$. Then the induced metric is $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{3} ds^2 = { k^2 \\over\\sinh^2 k\\sigma} ( d\\tau^2 + d \\sigma^2) = d \\xi^2 + k^2 \\sinh^2 \\xi\\, d \\tau^2 \\, \\qquad \\qquad \\textstyle\\xi =\\ln \\tanh {k\\sigma\\over 2}\\. \\end{aligned}$$ For $k=1$ this is the usual $AdS_2$ metric but for $k=2, 3, 4,...,$ it has a conical singularity at $\\xi=0$ with negative deficit $\\delta= 2 \\pi (1-k)$, i.e. this is a cone of $AdS_2$. The corresponding classical action is proportional to the regularized $AdS_2$ volume. To recall, the euclidean ${\\widetilde{AdS}_2}$ space in Poincare coordinates $ds^2 = z^{-2} ( dx^2 + dz^2 )$ with boundary being a line $R$ is not equivalent to $H_2= AdS_2$ in angular coordinates $ds^2= d \\xi^2 + \\sinh^2 \\xi\\, d \\varphi^2$ with boundary $S^1$; in particular, their regularized volumes are different $$\\begin{aligned} V_{{\\widetilde{AdS}_2} }= { \\ell \\over\\epsilon} \\to\\ 0 \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ V_{{{AdS}_2} }=2 \\pi ( { 1 \\over\\epsilon} - 1) \\to \\ - 2 \\pi \\. \\label{o}\\end{aligned}$$ Here we set the $AdS_2$ scale to 1, $\\ell \\to \\infty$ is the length of the boundary of ${{\\widetilde{AdS}_2} }$ and $\\epsilon\\to 0$ is a radial IR cutoff. As a result, the renormalized classical string action for ([3]) is ${\\Gamma}_0= - k{\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\ $ which matches the value of ${\\hat \\Gamma}_0$ in ([b3]). This suggests that the prescription to use the regularized volume of $AdS_2$ is a required part of definition of string theory partition function in the context of AdS/CFT.\n\nThe starting point to compute ${\\Gamma}_1$ is the general form of the $AdS_5 \\times S^5\\ $superstring one-loop correction 2 $$\\begin{aligned} {\\Gamma}_{1}= {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} \\ln \\frac{[{\\rm det} (-\\nabla^2_0 )]^5 \\, [{\\rm det} (-\\nabla^2_0 +2 )]^3 \\ }{[{\\rm det} (-\\nabla^2_{{1\\over 2}} +\\frac{1}{4}R +1) ]^8}\\,. \\label{b1}\\end{aligned}$$ In the simplest cases of minimal surfaces with symmetric-space induced metric (like $AdS_2$ spaces of straight line and circular loop) it is natural to preserve this symmetry in the loop computation till very end, i.e. not to introduce radial cutoff directly on contributions of individual modes. Then, as standard for determinants on a symmetric spaces they can be computed using heat kernel technique (utilizing in an essential way the unbroken global symmetry) and the final expression will be proportional to the space volume factor for which we should use its renormalized value in ([o]). For example, in the straight line case the classical action and loop corrections will be proportional to the volume of $\\widetilde{AdS}_2$ with boundary $R$ which has zero renormalized value in ([o]) and should thus be assumed to vanish, in agreement with $\\langle W \\rangle =1$ on the gauge theory side.\n\nSuch heat kernel based computation of ([b1]) in the $k=1$ circular loop case gives (using that the renormalized $V_{{{AdS}_2} }= - 2 \\pi$) $$\\begin{aligned} {\\Gamma}_{1} (1) = {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} \\ln (2 \\pi) \\. \\label{4} \\end{aligned}$$ The same expression was found in using a different (Gelfand-Yaglom) method to compute the determinants with the radial IR cutoff implemented explicitly on modes and all power divergences dropped in the final expression. The same method applied to the $k>1$ case led to the following generalization of ([4]) $$\\begin{aligned} {\\Gamma}_{ 1\\, {\\rm KT} } (k) = {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} \\ln (2 \\pi) + ( 2 k + {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} ) \\ln k - \\ln k! \\. \\label{b2} \\end{aligned}$$ This expression does not match the gauge theory result ${\\hat \\Gamma}_1$ in ([b3]). The third $\\ln {\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\ $ term in ${\\hat \\Gamma}_1$ may be attributed to the presence of the string tension normalization factor for the three (Mobius-symmetry) ghost zero modes on the disc, which was not included in ([b1]) and thus should be absent in ([4]),([b2]).3 The remaining difference may be coming from a numerical factor in normalization of the disc zero modes or from the ratio of the ghost and the two longitudinal mode determinants (assumed to be equal to one in ([b1])) once they are computed with proper boundary conditions (cf. ).\n\nBelow we shall ignore these open issues and aim at just deriving the analog of ([b2]) in the heat kernel approach of. Explicitly, we will find that $$\\begin{aligned} {\\Gamma}_1 (k) = {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} k \\ln (2 \\pi) + {\\rm I}(k) \\, \\ \\ \\ \\qquad \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ {\\rm I}(1) =0 \\, \\qquad \\qquad \\ \\ \\label{55} \\\\ \\label{5} {\\rm I}(k) = - \\frac{1}{4} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} { dy\\over y \\, \\sinh y} \\Big[ ( 5 e^{-y} + 3 e^{-3y} ) \\big( \\coth \\frac{y}{k}-k\\coth y \\big) + 16 e^{-2y} \\big( { 1 \\over\\sinh { y \\over k} } - { k \\over\\sinh y} \\big) \\Big] \\end{aligned}$$ Here the terms with $e^{-y}$ and $e^{-3y}$ are the contributions of the scalar factors under log in ([b1]) and the term with $e^{-2y}$ – the contribution of the spinor factor. For large $k$ the integral $I(k)$ is well approximated by a straight line, ${\\rm I}(k) = c\\, k +..., \\ c=1.077$. This result for ${\\Gamma}_1$ with $k >1$ is thus different from ([b2]) of and also different from the simple gauge-theory expression $\\sim \\ln k$ in ([b3]).\n\nHere we will not attempt to understand the difference with ([b2]), concentrating on developing technical tools required for derivation of ([5]) that may have other potential applications. The main issue is to find scalar and fermion heat kernels on the cone of $AdS_2$ in ([3]). Let us mention also that another possible application of the above partition function is to computation of Rényi entropy on $AdS_2$ (see ).\n\nIt will be useful to replace $k$ in ([3]) by an arbitrary real number $\\kappa$ and set $\\kappa=k$ only at the end. Then if we take $\\kappa$ to be equal to $1/n$ with an integer $n$ the metric ([3]) becomes that of an orbifold $AdS_2/Z_n$ (with a conical singularity of positive deficit) and the corresponding scalar or fermion heat kernel can be found as a sum over images. This special case of $\\kappa= 1/n$ will thus allow us to check the general $\\kappa$ expressions for heat kernels.\n\nIn the case of a cone of a 2-plane $ds^2 = d \\xi^2 + \\kappa^2 \\xi^2 d \\tau^2$ with a general $\\kappa$ the scalar Laplacian heat kernel can be found using “re-periodisation\" trick (or Sommerfeld formula) and the same idea applies also to the construction of heat kernel on the cone of $AdS_2$ with generic $\\kappa$. We shall present a detailed derivation of the expression of for the scalar heat kernel in section 2.\n\nThe analogous construction for the spinor heat kernel can be given using the result for the regular $AdS_2$ and generalizing the examples of cones of 2-plane and 2-sphere in. We shall present it in section 3. This will be our main new technical result. As a check, we shall match the small $t$ expansion of the spinor kernel with the general form of asymptotic expansion of spinor heat kernel on a conical singularity in and also show that in the special case of $\\kappa=1/n$ corresponding to $AdS_2/Z_n$ orbifold it agrees with the result in.\n\nIn section 4 we shall use the results for the scalar and spinor heat kernels to compute the determinants in ([b1]) deriving ([5]) and comparing it to ([b2]).\n\nIn Appendix A we shall review the derivation of the Sommerfeld formula for heat kernels of 2d scalar and spinor Laplacians on a manifold with a conical singularity. In Appendix B we shall present the derivation of the phase factor matrix $U$ in the $AdS_2$ spinor heat kernel in ([31]).\n\nScalar heat kernel on cone of $AdS_2$\n\nIn order to compute the $1$-loop partition function ([0]),([b1]) we need to know the traces of heat kernels of the scalar and spinor Laplacians on the cone of $AdS_2$ with an arbitrary deficit $\\delta= 2 \\pi (1-\\kappa)$ (we shall denote this space as $AdS_{2\\kappa}$). In the regular $AdS_2$ case we have $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{ab1} \\ln \\det \\Delta = - \\int_\\epsilon^\\infty { dt \\over t} \\ {\\rm K}(t) \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ {\\rm K}(t) = \\int d^2 x \\sqrt g \\ K(x,x;t) \\, \\ \\ \\ K(x,x';t) = \\big\\langle x| e^{-t \\Delta} | x'\\big\\rangle \\ \\ \\ \\\\ {\\rm K}(t) = V_{{AdS_{2}}} K(t) \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ K(t) = K(x,x; t) \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ V_{{AdS_{2}}} = - 2\\pi \\. \\label{vvo}\\end{aligned}$$ Here ${\\rm K}$ is the trace of heat kernel which on symmetric space is a product of (regularized) volume and heat kernel at coinciding points.\n\nIn this section we will review the computation of the heat kernel ${\\rm K}$ of the scalar Laplacian $\\Delta_0= - \\nabla^2_0 + m^2$ on $AdS_{2\\kappa}$ using the Sommerfeld formula, rederiving the expression for it given in. We shall check the consistency of the result in the special case when $\\kappa= 1/n$ with integer $n$ by comparing it with the scalar heat kernel on the orbifold $AdS_{2}/Z_{n}$.\n\nThe generalization of the scalar heat kernel on regular $AdS_{2}$ to the case of $AdS_{2\\kappa}\\ $ can be constructed using the Sommerfeld formula as reviewed in Appendix A. The starting point is the expression for the untraced heat kernel of the scalar Laplacian on the regular $AdS_{2}$ $$K_{AdS_{2}}(x,x^{\\prime};t)= \\frac{\\sqrt{2}\\, e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{3}/{2}}} \\int_{d(x,x^{\\prime})}^{\\infty} \\frac{dy \\ y \\ e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}}{\\sqrt{\\cosh y-\\cosh d(x,x^{\\prime})}}\\. \\label{21}$$ Here $d(x,x')$ is the geodesic distance between the two points $x=(\\xi,\\phi)$ and $x'=(\\xi', \\phi')$ of $AdS_2$ in polar coordinates $$\\begin{aligned} && ds^2 = d \\xi^2 + \\sinh^2 \\xi \\, d \\phi^2 \\, \\label{aa}\\\\ && \\cosh d(x,x') = \\cosh \\xi\\, \\cosh \\xi'- \\sinh \\xi\\, \\sinh \\xi'\\, \\cos(\\phi-\\phi') \\. \\label{aaa} \\end{aligned}$$ According to the Sommerfeld formula, the traced heat kernel in presence of a conical singularity when $\\phi \\in (0, 2 \\pi \\kappa)$ is given by4 $$\\begin{aligned} && \\label{S}{\\rm K}_{AdS_{2\\kappa}}(t) \\equiv {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= K(0; t ) + \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz \\, \\cot \\frac{z}{2\\kappa}\\ K(z;t)\\, \\\\ && K(z;t)\\equiv \\int_{0}^{2\\pi \\kappa}d\\phi \\int_{0}^{\\infty}d\\xi \\ \\sinh \\xi \\ K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi+z;t)\\,\\label{ss} \\\\ && K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi+z;t)=\\frac{\\sqrt{2}e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t}}{(4\\pi t)^{3/2}} \\int_{d(\\xi,z)}^{\\infty} \\frac{dy\\, y \\, e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}}{\\sqrt{\\cosh y-\\cosh d(\\xi,z)}}\\, \\label{sss}\\\\ && K(0;t)= \\int_{0}^{2\\pi \\kappa}d\\phi \\int_{0}^{\\infty}d\\xi\\ \\sinh \\xi \\ K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi;t)= \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}} (t) \\, \\label{ses}\\\\ && {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}} (t) = V_{{AdS_{2}}} \\, K_0(t)\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ K_0(t) = \\frac{e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{3}/{2}}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} {dy \\, y\\, {1 \\over\\sinh {y\\over 2}} \\, e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}} \\. \\label{sis} \\ \\ \\end{aligned}$$ Here $K(z;t)$ is the integrated heat kernel with points separated by $z$ along angular direction only. The contour $\\Gamma$ on the complex plane is made of two vertical lines going from $-\\pi +i \\infty$ to $-\\pi - i \\infty$ and from $\\pi -i \\infty$ to $\\pi +i \\infty$ (see Appendix A). The geodesic distance $d(\\xi,z)$ between the points $(\\xi,\\phi)$ and $(\\xi,\\phi+z)$ is given by $\\sinh d(\\xi,z)= | \\sinh \\xi\\ \\sin \\frac{z}{2}|$.\n\nIn ([sis]) we used that for regular symmetric $AdS_2$ space the heat kernel does not depend on coordinates at coinciding points. Note that the IR divergence regularized by $V_{{AdS_{2}}} \\to - 2 \\pi$ will be present only in the first “$AdS_2$\" term $K(0;t)$ in ([S]), while the second integral term will be finite.\n\nTo compute $K(z;t)$ we introduce $v= \\sinh \\xi, % \\ d(u,z)=2 \\mathrm{arcsinh} ( u\\sin \\frac{z}{2})\\, \\ \\cosh d(v,z) =1+2v^{2}\\sin^{2}\\frac{z}{2}$ to get $$\\begin{aligned} K(z;t) %&\\frac{\\k e^{-(m^{2}+\\fo)t}}{2(4\\pi)^{{1}/{2}}t^{3/2}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} %\\frac{dv\\ v}{\\sqrt{1+v^{2}}} \\int_{d(v,z)}^{\\infty} %\\frac{y e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}dy}{\\sqrt{\\sinh^{2}(\\frac{y}{2})- %x^{2}\\sin^{2}(\\frac{z}{2})}} \\\\ = \\frac{\\kappa\\ e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t}}{2(4\\pi)^{{1}/{2}}\\ t^{3/2}\\ \\sin {z\\over 2}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} \\frac{dv\\ v }{\\sqrt{1+v^{2}}} \\int_{d(v,z)}^{\\infty} {dy \\ y\\ e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}} \\over\\gamma^2(y,z)-v^{2} }\\,\\label{22} \\, \\ \\qquad \\gamma(y,z)\\equiv \\frac{\\sinh{\\frac{y}{2}}}{\\sin{\\frac{z}{2}}} % \\frac{\\sinh y/2}{\\sin {z\\ov 2}} \\.\\label{23}\\end{aligned}$$ Now we interchange the integration limits $\\int_{0}^{\\infty}dv \\int_{d(v,z)}^{\\infty} dy = \\int_{0}^{\\infty}dy \\int_{0}^{d^{-1}(y,z) }dv, \\ \\ %=A(y,z)$ and integrate over $v$ using $\\int_{0}^{\\gamma(y,z)} \\frac{dv\\ v}{\\sqrt{1+v^{2}} \\sqrt{\\gamma^{2}(y,z)-v^{2}}}= \\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\arctan \\gamma^{-1} (y, z)$. Then integrating by parts one finds that $$\\label{24} K(z;t)= \\frac{\\kappa}{(4\\pi t)^{{1}/{2}}\\sin {z \\over 2} } \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dy\\ e^{-{y^{2}\\over 4t}} \\ \\frac{\\cosh {y\\over 2} \\ \\sin {z\\over 2} }{ \\cosh y-\\cos z} \\.$$ Changing the variable $y\\rightarrow 2y$ we finally get $$\\label{25} K(z;t)= \\frac{\\kappa\\ e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{1}/{2}}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dy \\ e^{-{ y^2 \\over t} } \\ \\frac{\\cosh y}{\\sinh^{2} y + \\sin^{2} { z \\over 2} } \\.$$ According to ([S]), the scalar heat kernel on cone of $AdS_{2}$ is thus given by $$\\begin{aligned} && {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}}(t) + \\frac{\\kappa\\ e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{1}/{2}}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dy\\ \\cosh y\\ e^{-{y^{2}\\over t} } \\ \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\ F(z;y,\\kappa)\\, \\label{26} \\\\ && F(z;y,\\kappa)=\\frac{1}{\\sinh ^{2} y+\\sin ^{2}{z \\over 2} }\\ \\cot \\frac{z}{2 \\kappa}\\. \\label{27} \\end{aligned}$$ For $\\kappa=1$ the function $F(z,y;\\kappa)$ becomes $2 \\pi$ periodic in $z$, and due to the structure of the contour $\\Gamma$, this leads to the vanishing of the integral contribution.\n\nTo evaluate the contour integral we use the residue theorem. The two vertical lines $(-\\pi +i \\infty,-\\pi - i \\infty)$ and $(\\pi -i \\infty,\\pi +i \\infty)$ surround one pole of $\\cot \\frac{z}{2\\kappa}$ at $z=0$ with the residue $\\mathrm{Res} \\ F(z=0;y,\\kappa)= \\frac{2\\kappa}{\\sinh^{2} y}$. Setting $y=-iu$ we get $F(z;u,\\kappa)= \\frac{\\cot \\frac{z}{2 \\kappa}}{ (\\sin \\frac{z}{2 } +\\sin u)(\\sin \\frac{z}{2}-\\sin u)}$ with two poles on the imaginary axis at $z= \\pm 2u$. Using the limit $$\\lim_{z\\rightarrow \\pm 2u} \\frac{\\sin \\frac{z}{2} \\pm \\sin u}{z \\pm 2u}= {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} \\cos u$$ we find $$\\mathrm{Res}\\ F(z= \\pm 2u;u,\\kappa)=\\frac{\\cot \\frac{u}{\\kappa}}{\\sin u \\cos u}= -\\frac{\\coth \\frac{y}{\\kappa}}{\\sinh y \\cosh y}.$$ Therefore $$\\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\, F(z;y,\\kappa)=2 \\pi i \\ \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\Big( \\frac{2\\kappa}{\\sinh^{2}y} -\\frac{2 \\coth \\frac{y}{\\kappa}}{\\sinh y \\ \\cosh y}\\Big) = \\frac{1}{\\sinh^{2}y}\\Big( \\frac{\\tanh y}{\\kappa\\tanh \\frac{y}{\\kappa}}-1\\Big) \\. \\label{277}$$ Finally, the scalar heat kernel on $AdS_{2\\kappa}$ is given by $$\\label{28} {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}} (t) + \\frac{ e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t} }{(4\\pi t)^{{1}/{2}}}\\int _{0}^{\\infty} dy \\ e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{t}}\\frac{1}{\\sinh y} \\big( \\coth \\frac{y}{\\kappa}-\\kappa\\, \\coth y \\big) \\,$$ which is the same expression as given in.\n\nThe integral vanishes for $\\kappa=1$, i.e. ${\\rm K}_{\\kappa=1}(t)= {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}}(t)$. It is obviously convergent at $y \\to \\infty$ and also at $y\\rightarrow 0$ since $\\frac{ \\coth \\frac{y}{\\kappa} -\\kappa\\coth y }{\\sinh y} \\big|_{y\\to 0} \\to %\\frac{1}{y}\\big[ \\big( \\frac{1}{y}+\\frac{y}{3 \\k^{2}}\\big) -\\big( \\frac{1}{y}+\\frac{y}{3}\\big) \\big] = \\frac{1}{3} ({\\kappa}^{-1} - \\kappa) + O(y)$.\n\nThe special case of $\\kappa= 1/n$ corresponds to the $Z_{n}$ orbifold of $AdS_{2}$ which is obtained by identification $\\phi = \\phi + \\frac{2 \\pi}{n}$. The analog of the Sommerfeld formula for orbifolds is equivalent to the summation over images expression discussed in. There it was found that the small $t$ expansion of the heat kernel for a massless scalar Laplacian on $AdS_{2}/Z_{n}$ is given by $$\\label{30} {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}/Z_{n}}(t)=\\textstyle\\frac{1}{n} {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}}(t)+ \\frac{n^{2}-1}{12n} - \\frac{(n^{2}+11)(n^{2}-1)}{360n}\\, t +O(t^{2}) \\.$$ To compare to the general expression ([28]) we need first to set there $m=0$ and expand for small $t$. Changing the variable $y\\rightarrow \\sqrt{t}\\, u$ we get for $t\\to 0$ $$\\label{31a} \\begin{split} {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= & \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}}(t) + \\frac{\\kappa( 1-\\frac{t}{4})}{(4\\pi)^{{1/2}}} \\int _{0}^{\\infty} du\\ e^{-u^{2}} \\ \\textstyle\\big[ \\frac{1}{3} \\big(\\frac{1}{\\kappa^{2}}-1\\big) + \\frac{7\\kappa^{4}-5 \\kappa^{2}-2}{90 \\kappa^{4}} \\, t \\, u^{2} \\big] + O(t^{2})\\\\ =& \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}}(t)+ \\textstyle\\frac{1}{12}\\big(\\kappa^{-1} - \\kappa\\big) - \\frac{1+10\\kappa^{2}-11\\kappa^{4}}{360 \\kappa^{3}}\\, t + O(t^{2})\\. \\end{split}$$ Setting here $\\kappa= 1/n$ we indeed match the orbifold expansion ([30]).\n\nSpinor heat kernel on cone of $AdS_2$\n\nLet us now turn to the spinor case. The fermions in ([b1]) are real (Majorana) so that log of their determinant or trace of heat kernel should be understood with extra ${\\textstyle{1\\over 2}}$ included (so that on a trivial background the contribution of one 2d Majorana fermion is minus that of one real scalar). The starting point is the heat kernel for the (Majorana) spinor Laplacian $\\Delta_{1\\over 2}= - \\nabla^2_{1\\over 2}+ {1 \\over 4} R + m^2$ on $AdS_{2}$ $$\\label{31} K(x,x^{\\prime};t)= U(x,x^{\\prime})\\, \\frac{%\\sqrt{2}\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{\\sqrt 2 \\, (4\\pi t)^{3/2}} { 1 \\over\\cosh {d(x,x^{\\prime})\\over 2} } \\int_{d(x,x^{\\prime})}^{\\infty} \\frac{dy\\, y\\, \\cosh \\frac{y}{2} \\, e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}}{\\sqrt{\\cosh y-\\cosh d(x,x^{\\prime})}}\\.$$ Here $U(x,x^{\\prime})$ is a $2\\times 2$ matrix acting on the $AdS_{2}$ spinor bundle and satisfying the equation of the parallel transport along the geodesic connecting the two points $(x,x^{\\prime})$: $$\\label{32} n^{\\mu}(x,x^{\\prime})\\nabla_{\\mu} U(x,x^{\\prime})=0 \\, \\qquad U(x,x)= I \\, \\qquad n_{\\mu}(x,x^{\\prime})=\\nabla_{\\mu}\\, d(x,x^{\\prime})= \\partial_{\\mu}\\, d(x,x^{\\prime}) \\.$$ Here the derivatives are taken with respect to the point $x$ and $n_{\\mu}(x,x^{\\prime})$ is the tangent vector to the geodesic. The general structure of $U(x,x')$ on hyperbolic spaces was not spelled out in the literature. As we show in Appendix B in the present case of $AdS_2$ in polar coordinates ([aa]) it is given by ($\\sigma_3$ is the Pauli matrix) $$\\label{4u} U(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})= \\exp\\Big( i \\sigma_{3}\\, \\arctan \\frac{\\cosh \\frac{\\xi+\\xi^{\\prime}}{2}\\, \\tan\\frac{\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}}{2}}{\\cosh \\frac{\\xi-\\xi^{\\prime}}{2}} \\Big)\\.$$ We can now apply the fermionic version of the Sommerfeld formula (see Appendix A) to obtain the heat kernel of the spinor Laplacian on the cone of $AdS_{2}$ (cf. ([S]),([ss])) $$\\begin{aligned} &&\\label{F} {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\mathrm{Tr\\, }K(0;t )+ \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\ \\frac{1}{\\sin \\frac{z}{2\\kappa}}\\ \\mathrm{Tr\\, } K(z;t)\\,\\\\ && \\label{ff} \\mathrm{Tr\\, } K(z;t)\\equiv \\int_{0}^{2\\pi \\kappa}d\\phi \\int_{0}^{\\infty}d\\xi\\, \\sinh \\xi \\ \\mathrm{Tr\\, }K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi+z;t)\\, \\\\ && \\mathrm{Tr\\, }K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi+z;t)= \\mathrm{Tr\\, }U(\\xi,z)\\, \\frac{%\\sqrt{2}\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{\\sqrt 2\\, (4\\pi t)^{3/2}}{ 1 \\over\\cosh {d(\\xi,z)\\over 2}} \\int_{d(\\xi,z)}^{\\infty} \\frac{dy\\, y\\, \\cosh \\frac{y}{2} \\, e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}}{\\sqrt{\\cosh y-\\cosh d(\\xi,z)}} \\nonumber\\\\ && U(\\xi,z)= \\exp \\Big[ i \\sigma_{3} \\arctan \\big( \\cosh \\xi \\tan\\frac{z}{2}\\big) \\big]\\, \\qquad \\ \\mathrm{Tr\\, }U(\\xi,z)=\\frac{2}{\\sqrt{1+\\cosh ^{2} \\xi\\ \\tan ^{2} {z\\over 2} }}\\, \\label{fff}\\\\ &&\\label{FA} \\mathrm{Tr\\, }K(0;t)= \\mathrm{Tr\\, }K(x,x;t) = \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_2} (t) \\, \\ \\ \\qquad {\\rm K}_{AdS_2} (t) = V_{AdS_2} K_{_{1\\over 2}}(t) \\, \\\\ && \\label{Fv} K_{_{1\\over 2}}(t) = \\frac{%2 \\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{(4\\pi t)^{3/2}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} {dy\\, y\\, \\coth \\frac{y}{2} \\, e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}} \\.\\end{aligned}$$ Here $K(x,x';t)=K(\\xi,\\xi',\\phi,\\phi';t)$ is the fermionic kernel in the regular $AdS_2$ case in ([31]).5 The contour $\\Gamma$ is the same as in the scalar case in ([S]) (see Appendix A).\n\nTo compute $\\mathrm{Tr\\, }K(z;t)$ in ([ff]) we integrate over the angle and after a change of variables ($v = \\sinh \\xi, \\ \\ % d(v,z)=2 \\mathrm{arcsinh}( v\\sin \\frac{z}{2}), \\ \\ \\cosh d=1+2v^{2}\\sin^{2}\\frac{z}{2}$) we find $$\\label{33} \\mathrm{Tr\\, }K(z;t)=\\frac{\\kappa\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{(4\\pi)^{{1}/{2}}\\, t^{3/2}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} \\frac{dv\\, v }{\\sqrt{1+v^{2}}} \\frac{\\cos {z\\over 2}}{1+v^{2}\\sin^{2} {z\\over 2} }\\int_{d(v,z)}^{\\infty} \\frac{dy\\, y\\, \\cosh \\frac{y}{2}\\, e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{4t}}}{\\sqrt{\\sinh^{2} \\frac{y}{2}- v^{2}\\sin^{2} \\frac{z}{2}}}.$$ Interchanging the integration limits as explained below ([23]) we get $$\\begin{split} \\label{355} &\\mathrm{Tr}\\, K(z;t)=\\frac{\\kappa\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{(4\\pi)^{{1}/{2}}\\, t^{3/2} \\sin {z\\over 2} } \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dy\\, y\\, \\cosh \\frac{y}{2}\\, e^{-{y^{2}\\over 4t} } \\ G(y,z), \\\\ & G(y,z)\\equiv \\int_{0}^{\\gamma(y,z)}{ dv\\over\\sqrt{1+v^{2}}} \\, \\frac{v \\ \\cos {z\\over 2}}{ \\sqrt{\\gamma^{2}(y,z) -v^{2}}\\ (1+v^{2}\\sin^{2}{z\\over 2} )}\\, \\end{split}$$ where $\\gamma(y,z)={ \\sinh \\frac{y}{2}\\over\\sin \\frac{z}{2}}$ as in ([23]). As a result $$\\label{34} G(y,z)= %&\\frac{\\cos {z\\ov 2}}{2} \\int_{0}^{a(y,z)} \\frac{dt}{\\sqrt{1+t}\\sqrt{a(y,z)-t} ( 1+tb(z) )} %\\\\=&\\frac{ \\arctan\\big[ \\frac{\\sqrt{1+ab}\\sqrt{1+t}}{\\sqrt{1-b}\\sqrt{a-t}}\\big] \\cos {z\\ov 2}}{ \\sqrt{1-b}\\sqrt{1+ab}} \\vert ^{t=a(y,z)}_{t=0} \\\\=&\\frac{\\cos \\frac{z}{2}}{\\sqrt{1-b}\\sqrt{1+ab}}\\big( \\pi /2 -\\arctan \\big[ \\frac{\\sqrt{1+ab}}{\\sqrt{1-b}\\sqrt{a}}\\big] \\big) \\\\= & \\frac{1}{\\cosh{ y\\over 2} } \\big( {\\pi \\over 2} -\\arctan \\frac{\\tan {z\\over 2} }{\\tanh {y \\over 2} }\\big) \\.$$ Integrating by parts in the remaining integral over $y$ in ([355]) one can put it into the form $$\\begin{aligned} \\mathrm{Tr}\\, K(z;t) %&=& \\frac{2\\k\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{1/2}}\\sin{z\\ov 2}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} %dy \\ e^{-{y^{2}\\ov 4t}} \\ \\partial_{y}\\big( {\\pi \\ov 2} -\\arctan \\frac{\\tan {z\\ov 2} }{\\tanh {y \\ov 2} } \\big)\\no \\\\ = \\frac{\\kappa\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{1/2}}\\sin{z\\over 2}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dy \\ e^{-{y^{2}\\over 4t}}\\ \\frac{\\sin z}{ \\cosh y-\\cos z }\\. \\label{36} \\end{aligned}$$ Changing the variable $y\\rightarrow 2y$ gives $$\\label{37} \\mathrm{Tr}\\, K(z;t)= \\frac{2\\kappa\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{1/2}}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dy\\ e^{-{y^{2}\\over t}} \\ \\frac{\\cos {z\\over 2}}{ \\sinh^{2} y + \\sin^{2} {z\\over 2}} \\,$$ so that ([F]) takes the form (cf. ([26])) $$\\begin{aligned} && {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_2}(t) + \\frac{2\\kappa\\, e^{-m^{2}t}}{(4\\pi t)^{{1/2}}} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dy\\, e^{-{y^{2}\\over t}} \\ \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\ F_{_{1\\over 2}}(z;y,\\kappa)\\, \\label{38} \\\\ && F_{_{1\\over 2}}(z;y,\\kappa)=\\ \\frac{1}{ \\sinh ^{2}y+\\sin ^{2} {z\\over 2}}\\ \\frac{\\cos \\frac{z}{2}}{\\sin {z\\over 2\\kappa}} \\. \\label{39} \\end{aligned}$$ For $\\kappa=1$ the function $F_{_{1\\over 2}}(z,y;\\kappa)$ becomes the same as $F(z,y;\\kappa)$ in ([27]) in the scalar case, so that the second integral term vanishes because of the structure of the contour $\\Gamma$.\n\nIt remains to evaluate the contour integral using the residue theorem. As in the scalar case, the contour $\\Gamma$ contains one pole of $\\frac{1}{\\sin {z\\over 2\\kappa}}$ at $z=0$ and two imaginary poles $z= \\pm 2iy$ of $\\frac{1}{\\sinh ^{2}y+\\sin ^{2} {z\\over 2}}$, i.e. (cf. ([277])) $$\\begin{aligned} %\\la{40}\\mathrm{Res}\\, \\FF(z=0;y,\\k)= \\frac{2\\k}{\\sinh^{2} y } \\, \\qquad % \\mathrm{Res}\\, \\FF(z= \\pm 2iy;y,\\k)= -\\frac{1}{\\sinh y\\, \\sinh \\frac{y}{\\k} \\ }\\ \\ \\ \\\\ \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\ F_{_{1\\over 2}}(z;y,\\kappa)= %2\\pi i \\ \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\k} \\big( \\frac{2\\k}{\\sinh^{2}y} -\\frac{2}{\\sinh y\\, \\sinh\\frac{y}{\\k}}\\big) %\\no \\\\ - \\frac{1}{\\sinh y}\\big(\\frac{1}{\\kappa\\sinh \\frac{y}{\\kappa}}-\\frac{1}{\\sinh y}\\big) \\. \\label{41} \\end{aligned}$$ Finally, the spinor heat kernel the $AdS_{2\\kappa}$ is given by $${\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_2} (t) {-} \\frac{2\\, e^{-m^{2}t} }{(4\\pi t)^{{1/2}}}\\int _{0}^{\\infty} dy\\ e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{t}}\\ \\frac{1}{\\sinh y }\\, \\big(\\frac{1}{ \\sinh \\frac{y}{\\kappa}}-\\frac{\\kappa}{\\sinh y}\\big) \\. \\label{42}$$ The integral term here vanishes at $\\kappa=1$ and is convergent at both $y\\to \\infty$ and $y \\to 0$ where $\\frac{1}{\\sinh y} \\big(\\frac{1}{\\kappa\\sinh \\frac{y}{\\kappa}}-\\frac{1}{\\sinh y}\\big) \\to \\frac{1}{y}\\big[ \\big( \\frac{1}{y}-\\frac{y}{6 \\kappa^{2}}\\big) -\\big( \\frac{1}{y}-\\frac{y}{6}\\big) \\big] =\\frac{1}{6} \\big( 1-\\frac{1}{\\kappa^{2}}\\big).$\n\nTo check ([42]) we may compare its small $t$ expansion with the asymptotic expansion of spinor heat kernel in the case of a general curved manifold with a conical singularity derived in. Setting $m=0$ in ([42]) and changing $y\\rightarrow \\sqrt{t}\\, u$ we get $$\\label{44} {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_2}(t) {-} \\frac{2 \\kappa}{(4\\pi)^{{1/2}}}\\int _{0}^{\\infty} du \\ e^{-u^{2}}\\ \\frac{1}{\\sinh( \\sqrt{t}\\, u)}\\ \\big[\\frac{1}{\\kappa\\sinh(\\frac{\\sqrt{t}\\, u}{\\kappa})}-\\frac{1}{\\sinh(\\sqrt{t}\\, u)}\\big] \\,$$ so that expanding in small $t$ gives $$\\label{45} {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\kappa\\, {\\rm K}_{AdS_2} (t) \\textstyle+ \\frac{1}{12} ({\\kappa^{-1}}-\\kappa) + \\frac{17\\kappa^{4}-10\\kappa^{2}-7}{1440 \\kappa^{3}}\\, t+O(t^{2}) \\,$$ in agreement with general expressions in. As in the scalar case, we may also match ([45]) with the small $t$ expansion of the the massless spinor heat kernel on $AdS_{2}/Z_{n}$ in corresponding to the special case of $\\kappa= {1\\over n}$ (cf. ([30])) $$\\label{43} {\\rm K}_{AdS_{2}/Z_{n}}(t)= \\textstyle\\frac{1}{n}{\\rm K}_{AdS_2} (t) + \\frac{n^{2}-1}{12n} - \\frac{(7n^{2}+17)(n^{2}-1)}{1440n}\\, t +O(t^{2}) \\.$$\n\nOne-loop partition function\n\nLet us now apply the above results for heat kernels ([28]) and ([42]) to compute the $AdS_5 \\times S^5\\ $string partition function ([0]),([b1]) on the cone $AdS_{2\\kappa}$. Using the explicit values of masses ($m^2_0= 0, 2$ and $m^2_{1\\over 2}=1$) in ([b1]) and ([ab1]) we get $$\\begin{aligned} &&\\label{51} {\\Gamma}_{1} (\\kappa) = \\kappa\\, {\\Gamma}_1(1) + {\\rm I}(\\kappa) \\, \\qquad \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ {\\Gamma}_1(1) = {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} \\ln (2 \\pi) \\,\\ \\\\ && {\\rm I}(\\kappa) = - {\\textstyle{1\\over 2}} \\int^\\infty_\\varepsilon { dt \\over t} \\int _{0}^{\\infty} {dy} \\ { e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{t}} \\over(4\\pi t)^{{1}/{2}} }\\ H(t,y; \\kappa) \\, \\label{522} \\\\ && \\label{52} H(t,y; \\kappa)= {1\\over\\sinh y} \\Big[ ( 5 e^{- { 1\\over 4} t } + 3 e^{- {9 \\over 4}t }) \\big( \\coth \\frac{y}{\\kappa}-\\kappa\\, \\coth y \\big) + 16 e^{- { t} } \\big(\\frac{1}{ \\sinh \\frac{y}{\\kappa}}-\\frac{\\kappa}{\\sinh y}\\big) \\Big] \\. \\ \\ \\ \\ \\end{aligned}$$ Here we isolated the contribution $\\kappa\\, {\\Gamma}_1(1)$ of the first ($AdS_2$) terms in ([28]) and ([42]) where ${\\Gamma}_1(1)$ given by ([4]) was already computed in. The first term in the bracket in $H$ is the combined contribution of 5+3 scalars and the second term is the contribution of 8 fermions (taken with the minus sign as required in ([b1])). Both vanish for $\\kappa=1$, i.e. $H(t,y;1)= 0$.\n\nThe proper time integral is actually convergent at $t\\to 0$ as one can see from the small $t$ expansion of the heat kernels in ([31a]) and ([45]) or directly from ([522]),([52]) after setting $y \\to y= \\sqrt t\\, u$ to get $\\int _{0}^{\\infty} {dy} \\ { e^{-\\frac{y^{2}}{t}} \\over(4\\pi t)^{{1}/{2}} } \\to \\int _{0}^{\\infty} {du} \\ { e^{- u^2} \\over(4\\pi)^{{1}/{2}} }$: $$\\begin{aligned} % \\bh{old} \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ H(t, \\sqrt t \\, u; \\kappa)\\Big|_{t\\to 0} = - {\\textstyle{2\\over 15}}( \\kappa- \\kappa^{-3}) u^2 \\, t + O(t^2) \\. \\label{53} \\end{aligned}$$ The resulting cancellation of 2d UV divergences in ([522]) is an important check of the consistency of this result as the (non-trivial part of the) 1-loop correction in $AdS_5 \\times S^5\\ $superstring should be finite on generic 2d background.\n\nWe can thus remove the proper-time (UV) cutoff $\\varepsilon$ in ([522]) and compute the finite integral over $t$ (keeping $t$ and $y$ as integration variables and using that $\\int _{0}^{\\infty}\\frac{dt}{t^{3/2}} e^{-( \\mu^2 t+\\frac{y^{2}}{t})}= \\frac{\\sqrt{\\pi}}{y} e^{-2\\mu y}$) $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{54} {\\rm I}(\\kappa) = - \\frac{1}{4} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} { dy\\over y \\, \\sinh y} \\Big[ ( 5 e^{-y} + 3 e^{-3y} ) \\big( \\coth \\frac{y}{\\kappa}-\\kappa\\coth y \\big) + 16 e^{-2y} \\big( { 1 \\over\\sinh { y \\over\\kappa} } - { \\kappa\\over\\sinh y} \\big) \\Big] \\. \\end{aligned}$$ This integral is convergent at both $y\\to \\infty$ and $y\\to 0$ as for small $y$ the integrand goes as ${1\\over 6} ( \\kappa- \\kappa^{-1}) + O(y)$.\n\nIt is not clear how to compute the integral ([54]) analytically. For some integer values of $\\kappa$ it is given by a combination of values of the Riemann $\\zeta$-function and polygamma functions, but we could not find an interpolating expression. It is of course straightforward to evaluate it numerically and conclude that for $\\kappa=k\\not=1$ it is different from the earlier result ([b2]) of and also from the gauge-theory ${ 3\\over 2} \\ln k$ behaviour in ([b3]). We illustrate the difference between ${\\Gamma}_{1} (k)$ in ([51]) and ${\\Gamma}_{1, \\rm KT} (k)$ in ([b2]) in Figure 1. For large $\\kappa$ we find that ${\\Gamma}_{1}$ grows linearly, ${\\Gamma}_{1}(\\kappa\\gg 1 )\\to 1.077 \\kappa$, while for small $\\kappa$ we get ${\\Gamma}_{1}(\\kappa\\to 0 ) \\to - 0.15 \\kappa^{-1}$.\n\nComparison between ${\\Gamma}_{1}(k)$ in ([51]) (black dots) and ${\\Gamma}_{1\\, \\rm KT} (k)$ in ([b2]) (blue line)\n\nAcknowledgments\n\nA.A.T. thanks E. Buchbinder for a collaboration at an initial stage and useful discussions. He also acknowledges discussions with V. Forini, D. Fursaev, M. Kruczenski, S. Solodukhin and A. Tirziu. The work of A.A.T. is supported by the ERC Advanced grant No.290456, the STFC grant ST/J0003533/1 and by the Russian Science Foundation grant 14-42-00047 associated with Lebedev Institute.\n\nHeat kernels of Laplacians on 2d cone\n\nLet us consider a $2$-dimensional space with a radial coordinate $\\xi$ and a polar angle $\\phi$ of period $\\beta =2\\pi\\kappa$ with metric near $\\xi=0$ being $ds^2 = d \\xi^2 + \\xi^2 d \\phi^2$ so that there is a conical singularity with angular deficit $\\delta= 2\\pi-\\beta= 2\\pi (1-\\kappa)$. Given the expression for the heat kernel of a scalar or spinor Laplacian on a regular manifold ($\\kappa=1$) it is possible to derive its counterpart on the space with $\\kappa\\not=1$ using so called Sommerfeld formula. We shall review this construction below.\n\nScalar case\n\nLet us consider first the case of flat 2d cone $$\\label{a1} ds^{2}= d\\xi^{2} + \\xi^{2}d\\phi^{2} \\,\\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\phi +2\\pi \\kappa\\equiv \\phi \\.$$ To construct the heat kernel for $\\Delta =- \\partial^\\mu\\partial_\\mu$ on this cone it is sufficient to consider the two points $x(\\phi )= (\\xi,\\phi)$ and $x(0)=(\\xi,0)$ separated only in the angular direction by angle $\\phi$. The starting point is the heat kernel for $\\kappa=1$, i.e. on a regular $R^2$ plane, where we have for $K(x,x'; t) = \\big\\langle x| e^{- t\\Delta } | x' \\big\\rangle$ $$\\label{a2} K(x(\\phi),x(0);t)\\equiv K_0 ( \\xi, \\phi,\\ \\xi,0;t ) = \\frac{1}{4\\pi t}\\, e^{ - { 1 \\over 4t} { |x(\\phi) - x(0) |^2 } } = \\frac{1}{4\\pi t} \\, e^{-{1 \\over 2t}(1-\\cos \\phi){ \\xi^2 }}\\.$$ Since this is a smooth function of $\\phi$, we can rewrite it using the Cauchy representation: $$\\label{a22} K(x(\\phi),x(0);t)= \\frac{1}{2\\pi i}\\oint_{C} \\frac{dz}{z-\\phi}K(x(z),x(0);t)\\,$$ where $C$ is a contour in the complex plane which encircles the point $z=\\phi$. Now let us deform $C$ to a family of contours $A_{n},\\ n=0, \\pm1,\\pm2,....$, where $A_{n}$ goes from $(2n+1)\\pi-\\epsilon + i\\infty$ to $(2n-1)\\pi + \\epsilon + i \\infty$ in the higher half plane and from $(2n-1)\\pi + \\epsilon - i\\infty$ to $(2n+1)\\pi - \\epsilon - i \\infty$ in the lower half plane one. Then the heat kernel can be expressed as the “sum over images\" $$\\begin{aligned} K(x(\\phi),x(0);t) = \\frac{1}{2\\pi i}\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\int_{A_{n}}\\frac{dz}{z-\\phi}K(x(z),x(0);t) \\nonumber\\qquad \\qquad \\\\ = \\frac{1}{2\\pi i} \\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\int_{A_{0}}\\frac{dz}{z-\\phi -2\\pi n}K(x(z),x(0);t) =\\frac{1}{4\\pi i} \\int_{A_{0}} dz\\, \\cot \\frac{z-\\phi}{2} \\ K(x(z),x(0);t)\\. \\label{a3} \\end{aligned}$$ Here we used the periodicity of the kernel in ([a2]) and the identity $\\sum _{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{z-n q}=\\frac{\\pi}{q} \\cot \\frac{\\pi z}{q}\\.$\n\nWe can now repeat the same procedure changing the period of the angle from $2\\pi$ to $2 \\pi\\kappa$ to get the heat kernel on the cone ([a1]) $$\\label{a4} K_{\\kappa}(x(\\phi),x(0);t) =\\frac{1}{4\\pi i \\kappa} \\int_{A_{0}} dz\\, \\cot \\frac{z-\\phi}{2\\kappa} \\ K (x(\\phi),x(0);t) \\,$$ or after shifting $z\\rightarrow z +\\phi$ $$\\label{a5} K_{\\kappa}(x(\\phi),x(0);t)= \\frac{1}{4\\pi i \\kappa} \\int_{A_{0}^{\\prime}} dz\\, \\cot \\frac{ z}{2\\kappa}\\, K(x(z+\\phi),x(0);t)\\.$$ The contour $A_{0}^{\\prime}$ is obtained from $A_{0}$ by a shift by $\\phi$ and consists of two pieces: one in the upper half plane running from $\\pi + \\phi+ i\\infty$ to $-\\pi +\\phi +i\\infty$ and one in the lower half plane going from $-\\pi +\\phi -i\\infty$ to $\\pi+\\phi-i\\infty$. We may then deform $A_{0}^{\\prime}$ into a small circle around $z=0$ and another contour $\\Gamma^{\\prime}$ made of two vertical lines: one going from $-\\pi + \\phi -i \\infty$ to $-\\pi +\\phi+ i \\infty$ and one from $\\pi +\\phi +i \\infty$ to $\\pi +\\phi -i \\infty$. Near $z=0$ the integrand has a pole of $\\cot\\frac{ z}{2 \\kappa}\\sim \\frac{2 \\kappa}{ z}$ with residue being the regular plane kernel $K(x(z+\\phi),x(0);t)$. Then denoting $\\Gamma= -\\mathrm{\\Gamma^{\\prime}}$ we finish with $$\\label{a6} K_{\\kappa}(x(\\phi),x(0);t)=K(x(\\phi),x(0);t) + \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\, \\cot \\frac{z}{2 \\kappa}\\ K(x(z+\\phi),x(0);t) \\.$$ This is the Sommerfeld formula for the heat kernel of the scalar Laplacian on the cone ([a1]) in terms of the heat kernel on the regular 2-plane.\n\nThe same procedure can be applied to the case of an arbitrary space $\\mathcal{M}$ where the heat kernel depends only on the angular distance between two points. Denoting $x=(\\xi,\\phi)$, $x'=(\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime})$ the coordinates of two points on the corresponding cone $\\mathcal{M}_{\\kappa}$ of $\\mathcal{M}$, the Sommerfeld formula for the heat kernel of the scalar Laplacian reads $$\\label{a7} K_{\\kappa}(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime};t)= K(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime};t) + \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\, \\cot \\frac{z}{2 \\kappa}\\ K(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi +z,\\phi^{\\prime} ;t).$$ Here the angular distance is $z=\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}$ and the contour $\\Gamma$ is formed by two vertical lines from $-\\pi + (\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}) +i \\infty$ to $-\\pi +(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime})- i \\infty$ and from $\\pi +(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}) -i \\infty$ to $\\pi +(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}) +i \\infty$. Taking the coincident points limit we get $$\\label{a8} K_{\\kappa}(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi=\\phi^{\\prime};t)= K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi=\\phi^{\\prime};t)+\\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\, \\cot \\frac{z}{2 \\kappa} \\ K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi+z;t)\\.$$ Defining the integrated heat kernel $$\\label{a88} K(z;t)= \\int_{M_{\\kappa}}d\\phi \\, d\\xi \\, \\sqrt{g} \\ K(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi+z;t)\\,$$ we finally get the expression for the trace of heat kernel $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{a9} {\\rm K}_\\kappa(t)=\\int_{M_\\kappa} d^2 x\\, \\sqrt g \\, \\big\\langle x| e^{- t\\Delta } | x \\big\\rangle= K(0; t) + \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} dz\\, \\cot \\frac{z}{2\\kappa}\\ K(z;t)\\. \\end{aligned}$$ Since in ([a9]) $\\phi=\\phi'$, here the contour $\\Gamma$ reduces to two vertical lines going from $-\\pi -i \\infty$ to $-\\pi + i \\infty$ and from $\\pi - i\\infty$ to $\\pi +i \\infty$.\n\nThus in addition to the expected term $K(0; t)$ “inherited\" from the regular space case there is a correction given by a contour integral on the complex plane. For $\\kappa=1$ this second term vanishes as expected: the integrand becomes $2\\pi$ periodic in $z$ and the contributions coming from the integration along the two vertical lines at $-\\pi$ and $\\pi$ cancel each other.\n\nSpinor case\n\nLet us start again with a flat space cone. On $R^2$ in Cartesian coordinates the spin connection is trivial and the fermionic Laplace operator $\\Delta_{{1\\over 2}}= -{\\nabla}^{2}+\\frac{1}{4}{R}$ reduces to the scalar Laplacian $\\Delta_0 = -\\partial^{\\mu}\\partial_{\\mu}$. Thus solution to the heat kernel equation is the same as for the scalar ([a2]) up to $2\\times 2$ identity matrix $I$: $$\\label{a10} \\tilde K\\left(x,x';t\\right)= K_{0}(x,x';t)\\, I \\.$$ In polar coordinates $( \\xi, \\phi )$ the spinor covariant derivative is $\\nabla_{\\mu} = \\partial_{\\mu} + \\omega_{\\mu}$ with $\\omega_{\\mu}dx^{\\mu}= -\\frac{i}{2}\\sigma_{3}d\\phi$. Thus $$\\label{a11} \\nabla_{\\mu} = {\\rm V}\\partial_{\\mu} V^{-1} \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\Delta_{1\\over 2}= {\\rm V}\\Delta_0 {\\rm V}^{-1} \\, \\qquad \\qquad {\\rm V}=e^{ \\frac{i}{2}\\sigma_{3}\\phi} \\.$$ Then the solution to the spinor heat kernel equation in polar coordinates may be written as $$\\label{a12} K(x,x';t) = {\\rm V}(\\phi)\\, \\tilde K(x,x';t) \\,$$ with $\\tilde K$ given by ([a10]). Due to the presence of the spin factor ${\\rm V}$ the spinor heat kernel is antiperiodic in $\\phi$.\n\nTo get spinor heat kernel on a cone of $R^2$ we follow the same route as in the scalar case: we choose $x(\\phi) =(\\xi,\\phi)$, $x(0) =(\\xi,0)$ and first rewrite $K(x,x';t)$ in ([a12]) using the method of the images as in ([a22]),([a3]): $$\\begin{aligned} \\nonumber\\label{a13} &&K (x(\\phi),x(0);t)= \\frac{1}{2\\pi i}\\oint_C { \\frac{dz}{z-\\phi}\\, {\\rm V}(z)\\, K(x(z),x(0);t)} \\nonumber\\\\ &&\\qquad\\qquad\\qquad \\quad = \\frac{1}{2\\pi i}\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\int_{A_{n}}\\frac{dz}{z-\\phi}\\ {\\rm V}(z)\\, K(x(z),x(0);t) \\nonumber\\\\ &&\\qquad\\qquad\\qquad \\quad= \\frac{1}{2\\pi i} \\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\int_{A_{0}}\\frac{dz\\, (-1)^{n}}{z-\\phi -2\\pi n}\\, {\\rm V}(z)\\, K(x(z),x(0);t)\\nonumber\\\\ &&\\qquad\\qquad\\qquad \\quad=\\frac{1}{4\\pi i} \\int_{A_{0}} \\, dz \\, \\frac{1}{\\sin \\frac{z-\\phi}{2} }\\, {\\rm V}(z) \\, K(x(z),x(0);t) \\. \\label{a15}\\end{aligned}$$ Here we used the antiperiodicity of ${\\rm V}$ and $\\sum _{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} \\frac{(-1)^{n}}{z-q n }=\\frac{\\pi}{q} \\frac{1}{\\sin\\frac{\\pi z}{q}}$. We can now change the periodicity of $\\phi$ from $2\\pi$ to $2\\pi \\kappa$ and to get the expression for the spinor heat kernel on the cone of $R^2$ $$\\begin{aligned} K_{ \\kappa}(x(\\phi),x(0);t)&=& \\frac{1}{4\\pi i \\kappa} \\int_{A_{0}} \\,dz\\ \\frac{1}{\\sin\\frac{z-\\phi}{2 \\kappa}}\\, K(x(z),x(0);t)\\nonumber\\\\ &=& \\frac{1}{4\\pi i \\kappa} \\int_{A_{0}^{\\prime}}\\, dz \\ \\frac{1}{\\sin\\frac{z}{2\\kappa}}\\, K(x(z+\\phi),x(0);t)\\, \\label{a14}\\end{aligned}$$ where $A_{0}^{\\prime}$ is again given by two lines in the upper and lower half plane: one running from $\\pi + \\phi+ i\\infty$ to $-\\pi +\\phi +i\\infty$ and the other from $-\\pi +\\phi -i\\infty$ to $\\pi+\\phi-i\\infty$. Next, we deform $A_{0}^{\\prime}$ into a small circle around $z=0$ and a contour $\\Gamma^{\\prime}$ made of two vertical lines that run from $-\\pi + \\phi -i \\infty$ to $-\\pi +\\phi+ i \\infty$ and from $\\pi +\\phi +i \\infty$ to $\\pi +\\phi -i \\infty$. Setting $\\Gamma= -\\Gamma^{\\prime}$ we obtain $$\\label{a16} K_{\\kappa}(x(\\phi),x(0);t)= K(x(\\phi),x(0);t)+ \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_\\Gamma\\, dz \\ \\frac{1}{\\sin\\frac{z}{2 \\kappa} }\\, K(x(z+\\phi),x(0);t) \\.$$ This expression can be generalized to the case of a cone of curved 2d space where the heat kernel depends on the angular distance between two points $x=(\\xi,\\phi)$ and $x'=(\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime})$ $$K_{\\kappa}(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime};t)=K(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime};t) + \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma} \\, dz \\frac{1}{\\sin \\frac{z}{2\\kappa} }\\, K(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi+z,\\phi^{\\prime};t)\\. \\label{a17}$$ Here, as in the scalar case in ([a7]), $\\Gamma$ is modified by $\\phi \\rightarrow \\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}$. Defining the integrated kernel as in ([a88]) we then get the final expression for the traced spinor heat kernel: $$\\label{a20} {\\rm K}_{\\kappa}(t)= \\mathrm{Tr}\\, K (0;t) + \\frac{i}{4\\pi \\kappa} \\int_{\\Gamma}\\, dz \\ \\frac{1}{\\sin\\frac{z}{2\\kappa}} \\, \\mathrm{Tr}\\, K(z;t)\\.$$ Here $\\mathrm{Tr\\, }$ is over the spinor indices and the integration contour reduces for $\\phi=\\phi^{\\prime}$ to the two vertical lines going from $-\\pi -i \\infty$ to $-\\pi + i \\infty$ and from $\\pi - i\\infty$ to $\\pi +i \\infty$. For $\\kappa=1$ the integrand becomes periodic (as the product of two antiperiodic functions in $z$) and thus the integral contribution vanishes.\n\nMatrix $U$ in spinor heat kernel on $AdS_2$\n\nHere we solve the equation ([32]) for the matrix $U$ in the $AdS_2$ metric ([aa]) written in polar coordinates. The corresponding zweibein and tangent space and spinor connections are ($\\mu=( \\xi,\\phi )$) $$\\begin{aligned} %g_{\\mu \\nu}= \\begin{pmatrix} %1 & 0 \\\\ %0 & \\sinh^{2} \\xi % \\end{pmatrix}, \\hspace{1cm} && e^{1}_{\\mu}=(1,0)\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ e^{2}_{\\mu}=(0,\\sinh \\xi)\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\omega_{\\xi}^{\\alpha \\beta}=0\\, \\ \\ %\\omega_{\\phi}^{00}=\\omega_{\\phi}^{11}=0, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\omega_{\\phi}^{12}=-\\omega_{\\phi}^{21}=-\\cosh \\xi \\, \\label{33a}\\\\ && \\omega_\\mu= { 1 \\over 2} \\omega_{\\mu}^{\\alpha \\beta} \\Sigma_{\\alpha \\beta} =(0,-\\frac{i}{2}\\cosh \\xi\\ \\sigma_{3})\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\Sigma_{\\alpha \\beta} = {1\\over 4} [ \\gamma_\\alpha, \\gamma_\\beta] \\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ % \\Sigma_{\\k \\beta}= \\frac{1}{4}[\\gamma_{\\k},\\gamma_{\\beta}]= \\frac{i}{2} \\sigma_{3} \\epsilon_{\\k \\beta}, \\gamma^{\\alpha }=( \\sigma_{1},\\sigma_2) \\. \\label{3322} \\end{aligned}$$ In it was shown that ([32]) is equivalent to the requirement that the spinor covariant derivative acts on $U(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})$ in the following way $$\\label{34b}\\textstyle \\nabla_{\\mu}U= \\partial_{\\mu}U +\\omega_{\\mu}\\, U= A\\, \\Sigma_{\\alpha \\beta}\\, n^{\\beta}\\, U\\, \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ A\\equiv \\tanh\\frac{d(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})}{2}\\,$$ where the geodesic distance between the two points $(\\xi,\\phi)\\, (\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi^{\\prime})$ is given in ([aaa]). This equation for $U$ can be rewritten as $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{35b} \\partial_{\\xi}U=\\frac{i}{2}{ \\tanh {d\\over 2 } \\over{\\sinh\\xi }\\, } {\\partial_{\\phi}d}\\, \\sigma_{3}U\\, \\qquad { \\partial_{\\phi}U}=\\frac{i}{2}{\\sinh\\xi} \\big( \\coth\\xi-\\tanh \\frac{d}{2}\\, \\partial_{\\xi}d\\big) \\, \\sigma_{3} U \\. % \\\\& U(\\xi^{\\prime}=\\xi,\\phi^{\\prime}=\\phi)=I.\\end{aligned}$$ The first equation in ([35b]) has solution $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{36b} && U(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})= \\exp \\big[ \\frac{i}{2}\\sigma_{3}B(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})\\big] \\, C(\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime}) \\,\\\\ && B(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})= \\int {d\\xi \\over\\sinh \\xi}\\ \\partial_{ \\phi} \\log \\big[ 1 + \\cosh d(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})\\big] \\. \\label{37a}\\end{aligned}$$ Using ([aaa]) we find $$\\begin{aligned} B&=& \\int { d\\xi \\over\\sinh\\xi}\\ \\frac{\\sinh\\xi\\sinh\\xi^{\\prime}\\sin(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime})}{1+\\cosh\\xi\\cosh\\xi^{\\prime}-\\sinh\\xi\\sinh\\xi^{\\prime}\\cos(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime})} \\nonumber %= \\\\& \\int d\\xi\\ \\frac{\\sinh\\xi^{\\prime}\\sin(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime})}{(1+ \\cosh\\xi\\cosh\\xi^{\\prime}-\\sinh\\xi\\sinh\\xi^{\\prime}\\cos(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}))} \\\\=& -2 \\arctan\\big[ \\frac{\\cosh (\\frac{\\xi-\\xi^{\\prime}}{2})\\cot(\\frac{\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}}{2})}{\\cosh (\\frac{\\xi+\\xi^{\\prime}}{2})}\\big] \\\\ \\\\ &=& 2 \\arctan \\frac{\\cosh \\frac{\\xi+\\xi^{\\prime}}{2}\\ \\tan\\frac{\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}}{2}}{\\cosh \\frac{\\xi-\\xi^{\\prime}}{2}} -{\\pi} \\. \\label{3888}\\end{aligned}$$ The matrix $C(\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})$ can be determined from the second equation in ([35b]) $$\\begin{aligned} \\label{39b} %\\begin{split} \\partial_{\\phi}C= \\frac{i}{2}\\sigma_{3} \\big( \\cosh\\xi-\\sinh \\xi \\tanh \\frac{d}{2} \\, \\partial_{\\xi} d-\\partial_{\\phi}B \\big) C =0 \\, % \\\\ =&\\frac{i}{2}\\sigma_{3} \\big( \\cosh\\xi-\\frac{\\sinh\\xi}{1+\\cosh d}\\partial_{\\xi}\\cosh d -\\partial_{\\phi}B\\big) C \\\\= & \\frac{i}{2}\\sigma_{3} \\big( \\cosh\\xi - %\\frac{\\sinh \\xi \\big( \\sinh \\xi\\cosh \\xi^{\\prime}-\\cosh \\xi \\sinh \\xi^{\\prime}\\cos(\\phi -\\phi^{\\prime}) \\big) }{1+\\cosh \\xi \\cosh \\xi^{\\prime}-\\sinh \\xi \\sinh \\xi^{\\prime}\\cos(\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime})} - \\partial _{\\phi}B \\big) C. %\\end{split}\\end{aligned}$$ where we used ([aaa]) and ([3888]). Thus $C$ is constant and is fixed by the initial condition $U(\\xi=\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi=\\phi^{\\prime})=I$ $$\\label{40b} C(\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})= e^{ \\frac{i}{2}\\pi \\sigma_{3} } = i \\sigma_3 \\.$$ As a result, $$U(\\xi,\\xi^{\\prime},\\phi,\\phi^{\\prime})= \\exp\\Big( i \\sigma_{3}\\, \\arctan \\frac{\\cosh \\frac{\\xi+\\xi^{\\prime}}{2}\\, \\tan\\frac{\\phi-\\phi^{\\prime}}{2}}{\\cosh \\frac{\\xi-\\xi^{\\prime}}{2}} \\Big)\\. \\label{uub}$$\n\n 1. Also at Lebedev Institute, Moscow. tseytlin@imperial.ac.uk↩\n\n 2. Here $\\nabla^2_0$ and $\\nabla^2_{1\\over 2}$ are 2d Laplacians defined on scalars and spinors respectively. $R$ is the curvature of 2d metric equal to $-2$ in the case of $AdS_2$ of unit radius.↩\n\n 3. Note that this contribution should be absent in the straight line case as the induced metric volume enters also the normalization of the zero modes but the renormalized $V_{\\widetilde{AdS}_2}=0$ according to ([o]).↩\n\n 4. The $AdS_2$ scalar heat kernel has also an alternative representation\n\n    $K_0 (t) = \\frac{e^{-(m^{2}+{1\\over 4})t}}{2\\pi} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dv \\, v\\, \\tanh( \\pi v) \\, e^{- t v^2}.$↩\n\n 5. The trace of the $AdS_2$ Majorana spinor heat kernel has also an alternative representation\n\n    $K_{_{1\\over 2}}(t) = \\frac{e^{- m^{2}t}}{2\\pi} \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dv \\, v\\, \\coth( \\pi v) \\, e^{- t v^2}.$\n\n    Note that in contrast to here we do not include the fermionic statistics minus sign in the definition of the fermionic heat kernel, accounting for this sign explicitly when combining the bosonic and fermionic contributions below.↩\n\n\n\nWhat is the main goal of computing the heat kernels on the cone of $AdS_2$?", "answer": "Based on the abstract and introduction, the main goal of computing the heat kernels on the cone of $AdS_2$ is to calculate the one-loop correction to the string partition function for a circular Wilson loop with winding number $k$ in $AdS_5 \\times S^5$. The heat kernels allow computing the determinants that enter the one-loop partition function. Specifically, the authors aim to derive an expression for the one-loop correction $\\Gamma_1(k)$ and compare it to previous results."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_3300", "question": "Each of the five numbers 1, 4, 7, 10, and 13 is placed in one of the five squares so that the sum of the three numbers in the horizontal row equals the sum of the three numbers in the vertical column. The largest possible value for the horizontal or vertical sum is\n[asy] draw((0,0)--(3,0)--(3,1)--(0,1)--cycle); draw((1,-1)--(2,-1)--(2,2)--(1,2)--cycle); [/asy]\n$\\text{(A)}\\ 20 \\qquad \\text{(B)}\\ 21 \\qquad \\text{(C)}\\ 22 \\qquad \\text{(D)}\\ 24 \\qquad \\text{(E)}\\ 30$", "answer": "Let's denote the five squares as follows, where $a$, $b$, $c$, $d$, and $e$ represent the numbers 1, 4, 7, 10, and 13 placed in the squares:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\na & b \\\\\n\\hline\nc & d \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\quad\n\\begin{array}{|c|}\n\\hline\ne \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nThe problem states that the sum of the three numbers in the horizontal row must equal the sum of the three numbers in the vertical column. This can be represented as:\n\n\\[\na + b + e = a + c + e\n\\]\n\nFrom this equation, we can simplify to:\n\n\\[\nb = c\n\\]\n\nSimilarly, for the vertical sums, we have:\n\n\\[\na + c + e = b + d + e\n\\]\n\nSimplifying this, we get:\n\n\\[\na + c = b + d\n\\]\n\nGiven that $b = c$, the equation simplifies further to:\n\n\\[\na = d\n\\]\n\nThus, the numbers in opposite corners must be equal, and the center number $e$ can be any of the five numbers. To maximize the sum, we should place the largest number in the center. Let's place $13$ in the center:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\na & b \\\\\n\\hline\nb & a \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\quad\n\\begin{array}{|c|}\n\\hline\n13 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nNow, we need to distribute the remaining numbers (1, 4, 7, 10) such that $a$ and $b$ are equal or as close as possible to maximize the sum. The best distribution would be to place $10$ and $1$ in one diagonal and $7$ and $4$ in the other:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\n10 & 7 \\\\\n\\hline\n7 & 10 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\quad\n\\begin{array}{|c|}\n\\hline\n13 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nCalculating the sum for the horizontal row or vertical column:\n\n\\[\n10 + 7 + 13 = 30\n\\]\n\nHowever, this sum is not possible as it exceeds the total sum of all numbers. Let's try another arrangement:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\n10 & 4 \\\\\n\\hline\n4 & 10 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\quad\n\\begin{array}{|c|}\n\\hline\n13 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nCalculating the sum for the horizontal row or vertical column:\n\n\\[\n10 + 4 + 13 = 27\n\\]\n\nThis sum is also incorrect. Let's try placing $10$ and $1$ in one diagonal and $7$ and $4$ in the other:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\n10 & 4 \\\\\n\\hline\n7 & 1 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\quad\n\\begin{array}{|c|}\n\\hline\n13 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nCalculating the sum for the horizontal row or vertical column:\n\n\\[\n10 + 4 + 13 = 27\n\\]\n\nThis sum is also incorrect. Let's try placing $10$ and $1$ in one diagonal and $7$ and $4$ in the other:\n\n\\[\n\\begin{array}{|c|c|}\n\\hline\n10 & 1 \\\\\n\\hline\n7 & 4 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\quad\n\\begin{array}{|c|}\n\\hline\n13 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{array}\n\\]\n\nCalculating the sum for the horizontal row or vertical column:\n\n\\[\n10 + 1 + 13 = 24\n\\]\n\nThis sum is correct and maximizes the total. Therefore, the largest possible value for the horizontal or vertical sum is $\\boxed{\\text{(D)}\\ 24}$."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_1025859", "question": "Why is pi an irrational number, and what is the relationship between its digits and the distribution of prime numbers?", "answer": "Pi, the mathematical constant representing the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter, has long been known to be an irrational number, meaning it cannot be expressed as a finite decimal or fraction. This fundamental property of pi arises from its transcendental nature, a concept that has far-reaching implications in mathematics.\n\nOne way to understand why pi is irrational is to consider the notion of a circle's geometry. If pi were rational, it would imply that there exists a finite, integral relationship between the circle's circumference and diameter. However, this would also imply that the circle can be constructed using only finite, integral geometric operations, such as combining polygons with integer side lengths. However, this contradicts the inherent nature of a circle, which is a continuous, non-polygonal shape. The circle's curvature cannot be captured by finite geometric constructions, and this leads to the irrationality of pi.\n\nRegarding the relationship between pi's digits and the distribution of prime numbers, there is an intriguing connection that arises from the study of prime number theory. The distribution of prime numbers, as described by the prime number theorem, is intimately related to the properties of the Riemann zeta function. This function, denoted by ζ(s), is intimately connected to pi through the following identity:\n\nζ(2) = π^2 / 6\n\nThis equation, known as the Basel problem, reveals a deep connection between pi and the distribution of prime numbers. The zeta function, which encodes information about the distribution of prime numbers, is directly linked to pi's value.\n\nFurthermore, the study of the distribution of prime numbers has led to the development of various statistical models, such as the prime number theorem, which describes the asymptotic distribution of prime numbers. The digits of pi, in turn, have been found to exhibit statistical properties that mirror those of prime numbers. For instance, the digits of pi appear to be randomly distributed, with each digit occurring with a frequency that is roughly uniform. This observation is often referred to as the \"normality\" of pi.\n\nWhile the exact relationship between pi's digits and the distribution of prime numbers remains an open question, research has uncovered a web of connections between these two fundamental areas of mathematics. The study of pi's digits has led to new insights into prime number theory, and conversely, the study of prime numbers has shed light on the properties of pi. This interplay highlights the deep interconnectedness of mathematics, where seemingly disparate areas can be linked through subtle yet profound relationships."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_946377", "question": "Susie and Britney each keep chickens, of two different breeds. Susie has 11 Rhode Island Reds and 6 Golden Comets. Britney has twice as many Rhode Island Reds as Susie, but only half as many Golden Comets. How many more chickens are in Britney's flock than in Susie's?", "answer": "To solve this problem, we start by calculating the number of chickens each person has, based on the given information. \n\nFor Britney's Rhode Island Reds, we know she has twice as many as Susie. Since Susie has 11 Rhode Island Reds, Britney has:\n\\[11 \\times 2 = 22\\]\n\nFor Britney's Golden Comets, she has half as many as Susie. Since Susie has 6 Golden Comets, Britney has:\n\\[6 \\div 2 = 3\\]\n\nTo find the total number of chickens Britney has, we add her Rhode Island Reds and Golden Comets:\n\\[22 + 3 = 25\\]\n\nFor Susie's total number of chickens, we add her Rhode Island Reds and Golden Comets:\n\\[11 + 6 = 17\\]\n\nTo find out how many more chickens Britney has than Susie, we subtract Susie's total from Britney's total:\n\\[25 - 17 = 8\\]\n\nTherefore, Britney has 8 more chickens than Susie. \n\nSo, the final answer is $\\boxed{8}$."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_976741", "question": "Let f(x) = (x^2 - 2x + 2)/(x - 2). Find the range of f(x) excluding any vertical asymptotes of the function.", "answer": "To find the range of f(x), we need to understand the behavior of the function as x varies. First, let's consider the denominator, x - 2. This indicates a potential vertical asymptote at x = 2. Since the problem asks us to exclude vertical asymptotes, we'll focus on the behavior of f(x) for x not equal to 2.\n\nWe can rewrite f(x) as f(x) = ((x - 2)^2 + 2)/(x - 2) or f(x) = (x - 2) + 2/(x - 2) by completing the square in the numerator. This form reveals that the function is essentially a hyperbola shifted by 2 units along the x-axis, due to the presence of (x - 2) in both the numerator and the denominator.\n\nNow, consider the second term, 2/(x - 2). For x > 2, this term approaches 0 as x tends to infinity. Therefore, for large positive values of x, f(x) behaves like (x - 2). Similarly, for x < 2, as x tends to negative infinity, the term 2/(x - 2) again approaches 0, and f(x) behaves like (x - 2).\n\nHowever, the range of f(x) is not the entire set of real numbers, due to the term 2/(x - 2). This term can take on any real value except 0, since the numerator is a constant, and the denominator, x - 2, can take on any real value except 0. Therefore, f(x) can be written as (x - 2) + c, where c is any real number except 0. This implies that the range of f(x) is the set of all real numbers except 1, which corresponds to the value of (x - 2) when c is 0.\n\nIn summary, excluding the vertical asymptote at x = 2, the range of f(x) is all real numbers except 1."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_155230", "question": "I'm having an issue with react functional components where I need to update a state once a component mounts. In class components we could use the 'componentDidMount' lifecycle method, but I am unsure how to achieve the same functionality in a functional component.", "answer": "You can use the `useEffect` hook in React functional components to achieve the same functionality as the `componentDidMount` lifecycle method in class components.\n\nHere's an example:\n\n```javascript\nimport React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';\n\nconst MyComponent = () => {\n    const [state, setState] = useState(initialState);\n\n    useEffect(() => {\n        // Code to run when component mounts\n        setState(newState);\n    }, []); // Empty dependency array means this effect runs only once on mount\n\n    return (\n        // JSX\n    );\n};\n```\n\nIn the above code, the `useEffect` hook takes a function to run when the component mounts and an optional dependency array. If you pass an empty array (`[]`), the effect function will only run once when the component mounts.\n\nIf you want to run the effect when the component mounts and also when some state or props change, you can add the relevant state or props to the dependency array.\n\n```javascript\nuseEffect(() => {\n    // Code to run when component mounts or state changes\n}, [state]);\n```"}
