{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_993255", "question": "The distance between the opposite edges of a regular triangular pyramid is equal to $\\frac{\\frac{3}{8}}{8}$ of its lateral edge. Find the angle between the apothem and the adjacent lateral face.", "answer": "1. Let \\( ABCP \\) be a regular triangular pyramid with vertex \\( P \\), and base \\( ABC \\), where \\( AB = BC = AC = a \\).\n2. Let \\( M \\) be the centroid of the triangle \\( ABC \\).\n3. Let \\( K, L, \\) and \\( N \\) be the midpoints of \\( AB \\), \\( BC \\), and \\( AC \\) respectively.\n4. Let \\( F \\) be the foot of the perpendicular dropped from vertex \\( B \\) to the line \\( AP \\).\n\nGiven, \n\\[ FL = \\frac{\\frac{3}{8}}{8}a \\]\n\n5. To find the angle \\(\\alpha\\) between the lateral edge \\( AP \\) and the plane of the base \\( ABC \\), consider the right triangle \\( AFL \\):\n   \\[ \\sin \\alpha = \\sin \\angle FAL = \\frac{FL}{AL} = \\frac{\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8}\\right)a}{\\frac{a \\sqrt{3}}{2}} = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4} \\]\n\n6. Now,\n   \\[ \\cos \\alpha = \\sqrt{1 - \\sin^2 \\alpha} = \\sqrt{1 - \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4}\\right)^2} = \\sqrt{\\frac{16 - 3}{16}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{13}{16}} = \\frac{\\sqrt{13}}{4} \\]\n   \n7. And thus,\n   \\[ \\tan \\alpha = \\frac{\\sin \\alpha}{\\cos \\alpha} = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}/4}{\\sqrt{13}/4} = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{13}} \\]\n\n8. To find \\( AP \\) in terms of \\( \\alpha \\),\n   \\[ AP = \\frac{AM}{\\cos \\alpha} = \\frac{\\frac{a \\sqrt{3}}{3}}{\\frac{\\sqrt{13}}{4}} = \\frac{4a \\sqrt{3}}{3 \\sqrt{13}} \\]\n\n9. Let \\( PM = AM \\cdot \\tan \\alpha \\):\n   \\[ PM = \\frac{a \\sqrt{3}}{3} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{13}} = \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{13}} \\]\n\n10. Denote \\( \\beta \\) as the angle between the lateral face of the pyramid and the plane of the base \\( ABC \\). Consider the right triangle \\( PML \\):\n   \\[ \\tan \\beta = \\frac{PM}{ML} = \\frac{\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{13}}}{\\frac{a \\sqrt{3}}{6}} = \\frac{6}{\\sqrt{39}} = \\frac{2 \\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{13}} \\]\n\n11. Therefore,\n    \\[ \\cos \\beta = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{1+\\tan^2 \\beta}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{1+\\left(\\frac{2 \\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{13}}\\right)^2}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{1+\\frac{12}{13}}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{13}{25}} = \\frac{\\sqrt{13}}{5} \\]\n    \\[ \\sin \\beta = \\sqrt{1 - \\cos^2 \\beta} = \\sqrt{1 - \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{13}}{5}\\right)^2} = \\sqrt{\\frac{12}{25}} = \\frac{2\\sqrt{3}}{5} \\]\n\n12. Let \\(\\phi\\) be the angle formed between the apothem \\( PL \\) and the plane of the face \\( APC \\), and \\( D \\) be the orthogonal projection of \\( L \\) onto the plane \\( APC \\).\n\nWe need to find \\( PL \\):\n\\[ PL = \\sqrt{PM^2 + ML^2} = \\sqrt{\\left(\\frac{a}{\\sqrt{13}}\\right)^2 + \\left(\\frac{a \\sqrt{3}}{6}\\right)^2} = \\sqrt{\\frac{a^2}{13} + \\frac{a^2 \\cdot 3}{36}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{a^2}{13} + \\frac{a^2}{12}} = \\frac{5a}{2\\sqrt{39}} \\]\n\n13. Notice \\(LD\\) is half the distance from \\(L\\) to the plane of face \\(APC\\):\n\\[ LG = BN \\sin \\beta = \\frac{a \\sqrt{3}}{2} \\cdot \\frac{2 \\sqrt{3}}{5} = \\frac{3a}{5} \\]\n\\[ LD = \\frac{1}{2}BN \\sin \\beta = \\frac{3a}{10} \\]\n\n14. Thus,\n\\[ \\sin \\phi = \\frac{LD}{PL} = \\frac{\\frac{3a}{10}}{\\frac{5a}{2 \\sqrt{39}}} = \\frac{3 \\sqrt{39}}{25} \\]\n   \n### Conclusion:\n\\[ \\boxed{\\arcsin \\frac{3\\sqrt{39}}{25}} \\]"}
