{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_470367", "question": "I need help with some Python code. I want to create a function that finds the smallest and largest number in a list, and also provides the average of the list. I have written some code so far:\n\n```\ndef calculate_stats(lst):\n    smallest = min(lst)\n    largest = max(lst)\n    average = sum(lst) / len(lst)\n    return smallest, largest, average\n```\n\nHow can I modify this function to handle the case where the input list is empty? I want to return a meaningful message or handle this case in a way that makes sense. Do you have any suggestions?", "answer": "You can modify your function to handle an empty list by adding a simple check at the beginning. Here's an example of how you can do this:\n\n```python\ndef calculate_stats(lst):\n    if not lst:\n        raise ValueError(\"Input list is empty\")\n    smallest = min(lst)\n    largest = max(lst)\n    average = sum(lst) / len(lst)\n    return smallest, largest, average\n```\n\nIn this version, if the input list is empty, the function raises a ValueError with a message indicating the problem. This is a good practice, as it clearly communicates the issue to the caller.\n\nAlternatively, you could return a special value or a dictionary with a specific key to indicate that the list is empty:\n\n```python\ndef calculate_stats(lst):\n    if not lst:\n        return {\"error\": \"Input list is empty\"}\n    smallest = min(lst)\n    largest = max(lst)\n    average = sum(lst) / len(lst)\n    return {\"smallest\": smallest, \"largest\": largest, \"average\": average}\n```\n\nHowever, raising an exception is generally a better approach, as it allows the caller to handle the error explicitly.\n\nYou could also consider adding some error checking to handle cases where the input is not a list, or where the list contains non-numeric values. This would make your function more robust and easier to use. \n\nHere is how you might do this:\n\n```python\ndef calculate_stats(lst):\n    if not isinstance(lst, list):\n        raise TypeError(\"Input must be a list\")\n    if not all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in lst):\n        raise ValueError(\"List must only contain numbers\")\n    if not lst:\n        raise ValueError(\"Input list is empty\")\n    smallest = min(lst)\n    largest = max(lst)\n    average = sum(lst) / len(lst)\n    return smallest, largest, average\n```"}
