{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_167859", "question": "Let d be a positive integer.  Then we can form the set of all positive integer divisors of d and the set of all positive multiples of d.  Consider the divisors of d and the multiples of d as 2 separate sets.  Since every divisor of d is less than or equal to d, and every multiple of d is greater than or equal to d, we see that the 2 sets only have one element in common, the number d itself.  Using this fact, what can be concluded about d?", "answer": "This problem showcases a beautiful intersection of number theory and set theory. Let's denote the set of divisors of d as D and the set of multiples of d as M. As you've noted, D and M have only one element in common, namely d itself. This is because every divisor of d is less than or equal to d, and every multiple of d is greater than or equal to d.\n\nUsing this information, we can conclude that d must be a square number. To see why, let's assume that d is not a square number. Then, we can express d as the product of two distinct integers a and b, where a < b. In this case, both a and b are divisors of d, and ab = d. Now, b is also a multiple of a (since b = d/a), and therefore, b is also a multiple of the divisor a of d. \n\nHowever, we also have that a is a divisor of d, and a ≠ d, which means that a is also a multiple of the divisor (b) of d that is less than d. Thus, in this case, the sets D and M would have at least two elements in common (both d and another multiple/divisor pair such as ab or a and b), which contradicts our initial assumption.\n\nTherefore, we must conclude that d is indeed a square number. In this case, the sets D and M intersect only at d itself, as any other divisor of d would also be a multiple of d, and vice versa. For example, if d = 16, then D = {1, 2, 4, 8, 16} and M = {16, 32, 48, ...}, which have only 16 in common.\n\nIn summary, we can conclude that the positive integer d is a square number, as this is the only case where the sets of divisors and multiples of d have only one element in common, namely d itself. This problem highlights the intricate connections between number theory, algebra, and set theory, demonstrating the beauty of mathematical reasoning and logical deduction."}
