{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_393598", "question": "A retail appliance store priced a video recorder at 20 percent above the wholesale cost of $200. If a store employee applied the 5 percent employee discount to the retail price to buy the recorder, how much did the employee pay for the recorder?", "answer": "First, let's calculate the retail price of the video recorder. The store priced it at 20 percent above the wholesale cost of $200.\n\n20% of $200 = 0.20 * $200 = $40\n\nSo, the retail price is the wholesale cost plus the 20% markup:\nRetail price = $200 + $40 = $240\n\nNow, let's calculate the 5 percent employee discount on the retail price.\n\n5% of $240 = 0.05 * $240 = $12\n\nThe employee discount amount is $12. To find out how much the employee paid for the recorder, we subtract the discount from the retail price:\n\nEmployee price = Retail price - Employee discount\nEmployee price = $240 - $12 = $228\n\nThe employee paid $\\boxed{\\$228}$  for the video recorder."}
