{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_412747", "question": "The compounded ratio of some ratios including ( 6 : 11 ) and ( 11 : 2 ) is 1.9999999999999998. What is the missing ratio if it is known that it is the first in the sequence?", "answer": "To find the missing ratio, let's denote it as (x : y). Since it is the first in the sequence, the compounded ratio would be the product of the individual ratios. The compounded ratio is given as approximately 2 (since 1.9999999999999998 is very close to 2, and it's likely a result of floating-point arithmetic limitations).\n\nSo, we have:\n\n(x / y) * (6 / 11) * (11 / 2) = 2\n\nNotice that the 11s in the second and third ratios cancel out, simplifying the equation to:\n\n(x / y) * (6 / 2) = 2\n\nNow, simplify the 6 / 2 to get 3:\n\n(x / y) * 3 = 2\n\nNow, to find the ratio (x : y), we need to solve for x / y:\n\nx / y = 2 / 3\n\nSo the missing ratio is $\\boxed{(2}$  : 3)."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_507141", "question": "Let $A,$ $B,$ $C$ be the angles of a non-right triangle.  Compute\n\\[\\begin{vmatrix} \\tan A & 1  & 1 \\\\ 1 & \\tan B & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 & \\tan C \\end{vmatrix}.\\]", "answer": "We can expand the determinant as follows:\n\\begin{align*}\n\\begin{vmatrix} \\tan A & 1  & 1 \\\\ 1 & \\tan B & 1 \\\\ 1 & 1 & \\tan C \\end{vmatrix} &= \\tan A \\begin{vmatrix} \\tan B & 1 \\\\ 1 & \\tan C \\end{vmatrix} - \\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\\\ 1 & \\tan C \\end{vmatrix} + \\begin{vmatrix} 1 & \\tan B \\\\ 1 & 1 \\end{vmatrix} \\\\\n&= \\tan A (\\tan B \\tan C - 1) - (\\tan C - 1) + (1 - \\tan B) \\\\\n&= \\tan A \\tan B \\tan C - \\tan A - \\tan B - \\tan C + 2.\n\\end{align*}\nBy the product-to-sum identities,\n\\[\\tan A + \\tan B + \\tan C = \\tan A \\tan B \\tan C,\\]so the determinant is equal to $\\boxed{2}.$The answer is: 2"}
