{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_57667", "question": "Object of desire: David Gandy in his M&S advert . When John Prescott revealed he had bulimia, the world laughed. Yes, eating disorders are funny. Who knew? The former Deputy Prime Minister had revealed his struggle, no doubt hoping to help others blighted by the condition. But one award-winning political commentator declared a misdiagnosis, saying Prescott was ‘more likely just a greedy incompetent, who gobbled every treat going’. This wasn’t an isolated jibe. Feminist website Jezebel produced a What Prezza Was Eating… Daily Guidelines For Men – complete with fat and carbohydrate content. Would women be spoken about like this? Would it be tolerated? No way. I thought back to Prescott’s revelation in 2008 during the recent uproar over Victoria’s Secret, which launched an advertising campaign called The Perfect Body, showcasing the variety of underwear it sells. Women were outraged, it seems, because all the models were lithe and toned. US advertising trade publication Adweek reported that within days of posters going up, 10,000 people had signed a petition demanding the company ‘apologise for and amend the irresponsible marketing of your new bra range’. Complainants said the advert played on women’s insecurities, sent out damaging messages, and failed to celebrate diversity. Can you imagine if men made a similar response to the David Gandy posters for Marks & Spencer? Many of the same women who later went on to denounce Victoria’s Secret used their newspaper columns to leer at the images in ways that would make a builder blush. ‘Well done M&S on that autumn ad campaign. I’ve spent most of the past fortnight alternately lusting over David Gandy in his pants and that orange coat. But mainly David Gandy,’ said one. A broadsheet interviewer spent an entire article making jokes such as: ‘I’ve just buried my face in David Gandy’s underpants… it was heaven.’ And one famous feminist added: ‘It’s nice to see that objectification sometimes runs both ways.’ Uproar: When Victoria's Secret launched a campaign called The Perfect 'Body', women were outraged . But a diet of David Beckham and Gandy, or whichever Hollywood muscle man of the moment is gracing the cover of Men’s Health, is unarguably as damaging to male self-perception as The Perfect Body is to females. More than 1.6million Britons suffer an eating disorder, ten per cent of whom are men. We have to contend with ‘bigorexia’, which sees men pump their bodies with hormones and protein shakes to get a bigger chest and arms. One leading rugby coach told me that anabolic steroid abuse was endemic among teenage players, desperate to emulate the muscular physiques of their sporting heroes. And at least two British teenage boys have died over the past few years after taking the banned slimming pill called DNP. One was apparently trying to get a ‘six-pack’. Ultimately, there is a wider malaise surrounding male health in general. Not only is there a lack of empathy for our health concerns, there is also a lack of medical care. For example, women are screened for breast, ovarian and cervical cancer, which is great. But there’s no screening programme for prostate cancer, even though it kills four times more men than cervical cancer does women. Ridiculed: Labour peer John Prescott revealed he had bulimia in 2008 . Research from Cancer Research UK illustrates that men are 16 per cent more likely to develop every form of unisex cancer in the first place, then 40 per cent more likely to die from it. Despite cases of oral cancer having risen by 50 per cent among UK men since 1989 – accounting for almost 2,000 deaths annually – there is no vaccination for young men against HPV, which causes it. Between 2007 and 2012, NHS Primary Care Trusts in the London boroughs of Haringey, Hammersmith and Fulham, Brent and Camden ‘spent £4,830,095 commissioning women’s services outside the NHS… and nothing on men’s’. It’s a trend that is visible nationally, with female care almost constantly ranked above that of men. Rather than being the subject of sympathetic public concern or the odd fundraising gala, men are repeatedly told it’s all their fault. But in truth, men aren’t dying sooner because they’re ignorant or proud. When men don’t discuss their health concerns it’s not because they’re wired this way – it’s because if they say anything, they’ll be greeted with shaming tactics to stop them, just like Prescott. I shall leave it to Dr Timothy Spector, Professor of Genetic Epidemiology at London’s King’s College, to summarise: ‘Compared to women, men have shorter markers of longevity, called telomeres – suggesting there’ll always be a biological difference [which justifies the need for men to get greater care]. The state needs to realise men are discriminated against by the set-up of the current UK system.’ I couldn’t have said it better myself. Stand By Your Manhood, by Peter Lloyd, is published this week by Biteback, priced £16.99.", "answer": "The article discusses the disparity in societal and media treatment of men and women regarding body image and health issues. When former Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott revealed his struggle with bulimia in 2008, he faced ridicule and derision, with some dismissing it as mere gluttony. In contrast, when Victoria's Secret launched a campaign called \"The Perfect Body\" featuring slim, toned models, it sparked widespread outrage and a petition demanding an apology for promoting unrealistic body standards for women.\n\nThe author notes that while women's health and body image issues are often taken seriously, similar concerns for men are frequently dismissed or mocked. For instance, advertisements featuring male models like David Gandy for Marks & Spencer were met with lewd comments and objectification, which would be considered unacceptable if directed at women.\n\nThe article highlights the growing issue of eating disorders and body dysmorphia among men, with conditions like \"bigorexia\" and the misuse of anabolic steroids being prevalent. Despite this, there is a lack of empathy and medical support for men's health issues. For example, while women are screened for various cancers, there is no national screening program for prostate cancer, which is more lethal to men. Additionally, men are more likely to develop and die from unisex cancers"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_921544", "question": "What are some ideas for creative social media challenges that people would love to participate in?", "answer": "Imagine a social media challenge that's a fusion of art, music, and self-expression, where people are encouraged to lip-sync their favorite song, but with a twist – they have to create and showcase their own handmade musical instruments. It could be anything from a shaker bottle filled with beads to a guitar made out of a cardboard box. The goal is to get creative with the instruments and have fun while performing.\n\nAnother idea could be a challenge that focuses on storytelling through photography. Participants would have to capture a series of photos that tell a story, with each photo building upon the previous one. The twist? Each photo has to be taken in a different location, and participants have to use a specific prop that ties the entire story together.\n\nYou could also create a challenge that combines dance and sustainability. Participants would have to create a dance routine that incorporates eco-friendly habits, such as reducing plastic use or conserving water. The dance routine would have to be performed in a unique location, such as a park or a beach, and participants would have to use natural elements as props.\n\nA challenge that promotes kindness and gratitude could be one where people have to write letters or create handmade cards for strangers. Participants would have to share a story or a message of appreciation for someone they don't know, and then share it on social media using a specific hashtag. The goal is to spread positivity and inspire others to do the same.\n\nThere's also the idea of a time-lapse challenge, where participants have to showcase a skill or a talent that they've developed over time. It could be anything from learning a new language to mastering a musical instrument. Participants would have to create a time-lapse video that shows their progress, and share it on social media with a caption that tells their story.\n\nLastly, a challenge that celebrates cultural diversity could be one where people have to share a traditional recipe from their culture or a culture they're interested in. Participants would have to create a video or a photo series that showcases the recipe, and share the story behind it. The goal is to promote cross-cultural understanding and appreciation, and to inspire others to try new foods and drinks."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_175585", "question": "Show that the function $y$ satisfies equation (1).\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& y=\\frac{b+x}{1+bx} \\\\\n& y-x \\cdot y^{\\prime}=b\\left(1+x^{2} \\cdot y^{\\prime}\\right)\n\\end{aligned}\n$$", "answer": "1. First, we need to find the derivative $y'$ of the given function \\( y = \\frac{b + x}{1 + b x} \\).\n\n2. Using the quotient rule for differentiation \\( \\left( \\frac{u}{v} \\right)' = \\frac{u'v - uv'}{v^2} \\), we set \\( u = b + x \\) and \\( v = 1 + b x \\). \n\n3. Differentiate both \\( u \\) and \\( v \\):\n   \\[\n   u' = \\frac{d}{dx}(b + x) = 1 \\quad \\text{and} \\quad v' = \\frac{d}{dx}(1 + b x) = b\n   \\]\n\n4. Substitute \\( u, u', v \\) and \\( v' \\) into the quotient rule:\n   \\[\n   y' = \\left( \\frac{b + x}{1 + b x} \\right)' = \\frac{(1)(1 + b x) - (b + x)(b)}{(1 + b x)^2}\n   \\]\n\n5. Simplify the expression inside the numerator:\n   \\[\n   y' = \\frac{1 + b x - b^2 - b x}{(1 + b x)^2} = \\frac{1 - b^2}{(1 + b x)^2}\n   \\]\n\n6. Now we substitute \\( y \\) and \\( y' \\) into the second given equation \\( y - x y' = b \\left( 1 + x^2 y' \\right) \\):\n\n7. Substitute \\( y = \\frac{b + x}{1 + b x} \\) and \\( y' = \\frac{1 - b^2}{(1 + b x)^2} \\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{b + x}{1 + b x} - x \\cdot \\frac{1 - b^2}{(1 + b x)^2} = b \\left( 1 + x^2 \\cdot \\frac{1 - b^2}{(1 + b x)^2} \\right)\n   \\]\n\n8. Simplify the left-hand side by finding a common denominator:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{(b + x) \\cdot (1 + b x) - x \\cdot (1 - b^2)}{(1 + b x)^2}\n   \\]\n\n9. Simplify the right-hand side:\n   \\[\n   b \\left( \\frac{(1 + b x)^2 + x^2(1 - b^2)}{(1 + b x)^2} \\right)\n   \\]\n\n10. Simplify both sides further:\n    \\[\n    \\frac{(b + x) \\cdot (1 + b x) - x (1 - b^2)}{(1 + b x)^2} = \\frac{b \\cdot (1 + 2 b x + b^2 x^2 + x^2 - b^2 x^2)}{(1 + b x)^2}\n    \\]\n\n11. Expressing the left-hand side in expanded form reveals:\n    \\[\n    \\frac{b + b^2 x + x + b x^2 - x + b^2 x}{(1 + b x)^2} = \\frac{b + 2 b^2 x + b x^2}{(1 + b x)^2}\n    \\]\n\n12. Similarly, expand the right-hand side:\n    \\[\n    \\frac{b(1 + 2 b x + b^2 x^2)}{(1 + b x)^2}\n    \\]\n\n13. Both sides become equal, hence the identity holds:\n    \\[\n    0 = 0\n    \\]\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe given function \\( y = \\frac{b + x}{1 + b x} \\) satisfies the differential equation:\n\n\\[\ny - x y' = b (1 + x^2 y')\n\\]\n\nTherefore, we conclude that the function indeed satisfies the equation. \n\n\\(\\blacksquare\\)"}
