{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_27476", "question": "A line is parameterized with its direction vector of the form $\\begin{pmatrix} a \\\\ -2 \\end{pmatrix}$. Find the value of $a$ if the line passes through the points $\\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix}$ and $\\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}$.", "answer": "The direction vector between the points $\\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix}$ and $\\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix}$ is found by subtracting the first point from the second:\n\\[\\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\\\ -1 \\end{pmatrix} - \\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 - (-3) \\\\ -1 - 7 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\\\ -8 \\end{pmatrix}.\\]\n\nTo get a y-coordinate of $-2$, we scale the vector by $\\frac{1}{4}$:\n\\[\\frac{1}{4} \\begin{pmatrix} 5 \\\\ -8 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} \\frac{5}{4} \\\\ -2 \\end{pmatrix}.\\]\nTherefore, $a = \\boxed{\\frac{5}{4}}.$"}
