{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_363204", "question": "$(1){({0.064})^{-\\frac{1}{3}}}-{({-\\frac{7}{8}})^0}+{[{{{({-2})}^3}}]^{-\\frac{4}{3}}}+{16^{-0.25}}$；<br/>$(2)|{{{({\\frac{4}{9}})}^{-\\frac{1}{2}}}-lg5}|+\\sqrt{l{g^2}2-lg4+1}-{3^{1-lo{g_3}2}}$.", "answer": "### Problem 1 Solution:\n\nGiven the expression: $(1){({0.064})^{-\\frac{1}{3}}}-{({-\\frac{7}{8}})^0}+{[{{{({-2})}^3}}]^{-\\frac{4}{3}}}+{16^{-0.25}}$.\n\nWe can break it down step by step:\n\n1. $({0.064})^{-\\frac{1}{3}}$ simplifies to $\\frac{1}{\\sqrt[3]{0.064}}$.\n2. $({-\\frac{7}{8}})^0$ simplifies to $1$ because any number to the power of $0$ equals $1$.\n3. $[{{{({-2})}^3}}]^{-\\frac{4}{3}}$ simplifies to $(-8)^{-\\frac{4}{3}} = \\left(-2\\right)^{-4}$.\n4. $16^{-0.25}$ simplifies to $\\frac{1}{\\sqrt[4]{16}}$.\n\nPutting it all together:\n\n$\\frac{1}{\\sqrt[3]{0.064}} - 1 + \\left(-2\\right)^{-4} + \\frac{1}{\\sqrt[4]{16}} = \\frac{1}{0.4} - 1 + \\frac{1}{16} + \\frac{1}{2}$.\n\nThis simplifies to:\n\n$\\frac{2.5 - 1 + 0.0625 + 0.5}{1} = \\frac{33}{16}$.\n\nSo, the final answer is $\\boxed{\\frac{33}{16}}$.\n\n### Problem 2 Solution:\n\nGiven the expression: $(2)|{{{({\\frac{4}{9}})}^{-\\frac{1}{2}}}-lg5}|+\\sqrt{l{g^2}2-lg4+1}-{3^{1-lo{g_3}2}}$.\n\nWe can break it down step by step:\n\n1. $|{{{({\\frac{4}{9}})}^{-\\frac{1}{2}}}-lg5}|$ simplifies to $|(\\frac{9}{4})^{\\frac{1}{2}}-\\lg 5|$.\n2. $\\sqrt{l{g^2}2-lg4+1}$ simplifies to $\\sqrt{(lg2-1)^{2}}$.\n3. $3^{1-lo{g_3}2}$ simplifies to $3\\cdot {3}^{-lo{g}_{3}2} = 3\\cdot \\frac{1}{2}$.\n\nPutting it all together:\n\n$|(\\frac{9}{4})^{\\frac{1}{2}}-\\lg 5| + \\sqrt{(lg2-1)^{2}} - 3\\cdot \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{3}{2}-\\lg 5 + (1-\\lg 2) - 1.5$.\n\nThis simplifies to:\n\n$1 - (\\lg 5 + \\lg 2) = 1 - \\lg 10$.\n\nSince $\\lg 10 = 1$, the expression simplifies to $1 - 1 = 0$.\n\nSo, the final answer is $\\boxed{0}$."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_616087", "question": "Find the fraction that equals $0.\\overline{6}$.", "answer": "We can express $0.\\overline{6}$ as an infinite geometric series:\n\\[ 0.\\overline{6} = \\frac{6}{10} + \\frac{6}{100} + \\frac{6}{1000} + \\cdots. \\]\nThis series has a first term \\( a = \\frac{6}{10} = \\frac{3}{5} \\) and a common ratio \\( r = \\frac{1}{10} \\).\n\nUsing the sum formula for an infinite geometric series, \\( S = \\frac{a}{1 - r} \\), we calculate:\n\\[ S = \\frac{\\frac{3}{5}}{1 - \\frac{1}{10}} = \\frac{\\frac{3}{5}}{\\frac{9}{10}} = \\frac{3}{5} \\times \\frac{10}{9} = \\frac{30}{45} = \\frac{2}{3}. \\]\n\nThus, the fraction that equals $0.\\overline{6}$ is \\(\\boxed{\\frac{2}{3}}\\)."}
