{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_562014", "question": "What is the most efficient way to implement a stack using Python? \n\n(Note:  this question is from \"Cracking the Coding Interview\" by Gayle Laakmann McDowell and Jackie Bavaro.)", "answer": "You can implement a stack in Python using a list, taking advantage of the built-in list methods `append` (equivalent to push) and `pop` (equivalent to pop). Here's a simple implementation:\n\n```python\nclass Stack:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.items = []\n\n    def push(self, item):\n        self.items.append(item)\n\n    def pop(self):\n        if not self.is_empty():\n            return self.items.pop()\n        else:\n            raise IndexError(\"Stack is empty\")\n\n    def peek(self):\n        if not self.is_empty():\n            return self.items[-1]\n        else:\n            raise IndexError(\"Stack is empty\")\n\n    def is_empty(self):\n        return len(self.items) == 0\n\n    def size(self):\n        return len(self.items)\n```\n\nThis implementation provides standard stack operations: push, pop, peek, is_empty, and size. Note that the `pop` and `peek` operations raise an `IndexError` when the stack is empty.\n\nAlternatively, you can also use Python's built-in `collections.deque`, which provides an efficient implementation of a stack:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass Stack:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.items = deque()\n\n    def push(self, item):\n        self.items.append(item)\n\n    def pop(self):\n        if not self.is_empty():\n            return self.items.pop()\n        else:\n            raise IndexError(\"Stack is empty\")\n\n    def peek(self):\n        if not self.is_empty():\n            return self.items[-1]\n        else:\n            raise IndexError(\"Stack is empty\")\n\n    def is_empty(self):\n        return len(self.items) == 0\n\n    def size(self):\n        return len(self.items)\n```\n\nBoth implementations have a time complexity of O(1) for push and pop operations, but the `deque` version is more memory-efficient and should be preferred when dealing with large stacks."}
