{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_494011", "question": "For a square, two vertices are located on the line \\(y = 2x + 17\\), and the other two vertices are on the parabola \\(y = x^2\\). Determine the smallest possible area of the square.", "answer": "We begin by assuming that the points on the parabola lie on a line \\(y = 2x - k\\). Setting \\(y = x^2\\) gives the equation:\n\\[x^2 = 2x - k.\\]\nThis can be rearranged as:\n\\[x^2 - 2x + k = 0.\\]\nLet \\(x_1\\) and \\(x_2\\) be the roots:\n\\[x_1 + x_2 = 2, \\quad x_1 x_2 = -k.\\]\n\nThe points on the parabola are \\((x_1, 2x_1 - k)\\) and \\((x_2, 2x_2 - k)\\), and thus the square of the distance between them is:\n\\[\n\\begin{align*}\n(x_1 - x_2)^2 + (2x_1 - 2x_2)^2 &= 5(x_1 - x_2)^2 \\\\\n&= 5[(x_1 + x_2)^2 - 4x_1 x_2] \\\\\n&= 5 [4 + 4k] \\\\\n&= 20(1 - k).\n\\end{align*}\n\\]\n\nThe point \\((0, -k)\\) should lie on the line \\(y = 2x + 17\\) as the coordinates:\n\\[0 = 2(0) + 17 \\rightarrow -k = 17.\\]\n\nHence,\n\\[20(1 - k) = \\frac{(k + 17)^2}{5}.\\]\nThis simplifies to:\n\\[k^2 - 62k + 144 = 0.\\]\nSolving using the quadratic formula or factoring methods, we derive two possible valid values for \\(k\\).\n\nFor finding the smallest possible area, we compute from both values of \\(k\\), and validate if they make logical sense and yield valid areas:\n\\[(k - 8)(k - 18) = 0; \\quad k = 8 \\text{ or } k =18.\\]\n\nThus, the area computations are: \\(20(1 - 8) = 140\\) and \\(20(1 - 18) = 340\\), but upon further inspection and resolving discrepancies, the smallest possible area is found to be the feasible one:\n\\[\n\\boxed{140}.\n\\]"}
