{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_248570", "question": "Consider the graph G below:\n\n![Graph G](https://i.imgur.com/rJo14eU.png)\n\n1. Find the automorphism group of the graph G.", "answer": "An automorphism of a graph is a permutation of its vertices that preserves adjacency. The automorphism group of a graph is the set of all its automorphisms.\n\nTo find the automorphism group of graph G, we need to find all possible permutations of its vertices that preserve adjacency. Let's label the vertices as follows:\n\n```\n1 -- 2\n|    |\n4 -- 3\n```\n\nNow, let's find the automorphisms:\n\n1. Identity automorphism: This is the trivial automorphism where each vertex is mapped to itself. It is always an element of the automorphism group.\n```\n1 -> 1\n2 -> 2\n3 -> 3\n4 -> 4\n```\n\n2. Rotation by 90 degrees clockwise:\n```\n1 -> 2\n2 -> 3\n3 -> 4\n4 -> 1\n```\n\n3. Rotation by 180 degrees:\n```\n1 -> 3\n2 -> 4\n3 -> 1\n4 -> 2\n```\n\n4. Rotation by 270 degrees clockwise (or 90 degrees counterclockwise):\n```\n1 -> 4\n2 -> 1\n3 -> 2\n4 -> 3\n```\n\n5. Reflection about the vertical axis:\n```\n1 -> 4\n2 -> 3\n3 -> 2\n4 -> 1\n```\n\n6. Reflection about the horizontal axis:\n```\n1 -> 2\n2 -> 1\n3 -> 4\n4 -> 3\n```\n\n7. Reflection about the diagonal from vertex 1 to vertex 3:\n```\n1 -> 3\n2 -> 2\n3 -> 1\n4 -> 4\n```\n\n8. Reflection about the diagonal from vertex 2 to vertex 4:\n```\n1 -> 1\n2 -> 4\n3 -> 3\n4 -> 2\n```\n\nThese are all the possible automorphisms of graph G. Therefore, the automorphism group of graph G is:\n\n{Identity, Rotation by 90 degrees, Rotation by 180 degrees, Rotation by 270 degrees, Reflection about the vertical axis, Reflection about the horizontal axis, Reflection about the diagonal (1-3), Reflection about the diagonal (2-4)}"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_467070", "question": "What is the best method for adding a test within an existing file which is using TestNG and Selenium with Java?", "answer": "To add a test within an existing file using TestNG and Selenium with Java, follow these steps:\n\n1. Identify the class where you want to add the new test. Ensure this class is annotated with `@Test` and extends a base test class (if applicable).\n2. Create a new method for your test case. This method should be annotated with `@Test` and have a descriptive name that indicates what the test is checking.\n3. Write your test logic inside this method, using Selenium WebDriver to interact with the application under test.\n4. Use assertions to verify the expected behavior or results. TestNG provides various assertions, such as `Assert.assertEquals()`, `Assert.assertTrue()`, etc.\n\nHere's an example:\n\n```java\npublic class ExistingTest {\n    WebDriver driver = new ChromeDriver();\n\n    @BeforeMethod\n    public void setUp() {\n        driver.get(\"https://www.example.com\");\n    }\n\n    @AfterMethod\n    public void tearDown() {\n        driver.quit();\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    public void existingTest() {\n        // existing test logic\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    public void newTest() {\n        // New test logic\n        driver.findElement(By.linkText(\"Link\")).click();\n        Assert.assertEquals(driver.getTitle(), \"Expected Title\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBest practices to keep in mind:\n\n* Keep each test independent and focused on a specific scenario.\n* Use meaningful names for test methods.\n* Use assertions to verify expected behavior.\n* Keep test data separate from test logic, if possible.\n* Use setup and teardown methods to avoid code duplication."}
