{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_304670", "question": "Let f(z) = z / (1 - z). What would f(f(f(z))) look like.", "answer": "To find f(f(f(z))), we start by evaluating f(f(z)). We substitute f(z) = z / (1 - z) into f:\n\nf(f(z)) = f(z / (1 - z)) = (z / (1 - z)) / (1 - (z / (1 - z))).\n\nTo simplify this expression, we first combine the denominator terms:\n\n1 - (z / (1 - z)) = ((1 - z) - z) / (1 - z) = (1 - 2z) / (1 - z).\n\nNow we substitute this result back into our expression for f(f(z)):\n\nf(f(z)) = (z / (1 - z)) / ((1 - 2z) / (1 - z)).\n\nBy dividing one fraction by another, we effectively multiply the first fraction by the reciprocal of the second:\n\nf(f(z)) = (z / (1 - z)) * ((1 - z) / (1 - 2z)) = z / (1 - 2z).\n\nNow we need to find f(f(f(z))) by substituting f(f(z)) = z / (1 - 2z) into f:\n\nf(f(f(z))) = f(z / (1 - 2z)) = (z / (1 - 2z)) / (1 - (z / (1 - 2z))).\n\nWe simplify the denominator as before:\n\n1 - (z / (1 - 2z)) = ((1 - 2z) - z) / (1 - 2z) = (1 - 3z) / (1 - 2z).\n\nThen substitute back:\n\nf(f(f(z))) = (z / (1 - 2z)) / ((1 - 3z) / (1 - 2z)).\n\nAgain, divide one fraction by another by multiplying by the reciprocal:\n\nf(f(f(z))) = (z / (1 - 2z)) * ((1 - 2z) / (1 - 3z)) = z / (1 - 3z).\n\nThus, f(f(f(z))) simplifies to z / (1 - 3z). This iterative process reveals a pattern in the function compositions, highlighting the connection between repeated function application and the growth of the coefficients in the denominator."}
