d by the dice. Audio descriptions of the spaces will be provided as the players move around the board.\n5. Some spaces on the board will have obstacles that players need to navigate around, such as construction sites or busy intersections. Other spaces will have landmarks that players can use to orient themselves, such as parks or museums.\n6. The first player to reach the designated destination wins the game. The destination will be marked on the board and will have a unique audio description to help players identify it.\n7. Throughout the game, players can earn bonus points for correctly identifying landmarks and obstacles on the board.\n8. Audio directions or transcripts will be available for any rules or instructions provided by the game.\nOverall, the City Explorer board game will provide a fun and engaging experience for visually impaired individuals while also helping them to develop their navigation skills. With tactile pieces, a braille guidebook, and audio descriptions, the game will be fully accessible to those who cannot see."}
