{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_144559", "question": "A regular triangular pyramid has a base edge length of $6$ and a side edge length of $\\sqrt{15}$. What is the volume of this regular triangular pyramid?", "answer": "First, let's find the height of the equilateral triangular base. The height of an equilateral triangle with side length $a$ can be calculated using the formula $\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}a$. In this case, the base edge length is $6$, so the height is $3\\sqrt{3}$.\n\nNext, we'll find the height of the pyramid. To do this, we'll use the Pythagorean theorem with the side edge length and half of the base edge length (since the base edge is bisected by the pyramid's height). So, the height of the pyramid is $\\sqrt{(\\sqrt{15})^2 - (\\frac{1}{2} \\cdot 6)^2} = \\sqrt{3}$.\n\nNow, we can calculate the volume of the pyramid using the formula $\\frac{1}{3}\\text{Base Area} \\cdot \\text{Height}$. The base area is $\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4} \\cdot 6^2$ and the height is $\\sqrt{3}$. So, the volume is $\\frac{1}{3} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{4} \\cdot 6^2 \\cdot \\sqrt{3} = \\boxed{9}$.\n\nThis problem tests understanding of pyramid volume, spatial visualization, logical thinking, and computational skills."}
