{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_346540", "question": "If the solution to the system of equations $\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}{{a}_{1}x+y={c}_{1}}\\\\{{a}_{2}x+y={c}_{2}}\\end{array}\\right.$ is $\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}{x=2}\\\\{y=3}\\end{array}\\right.$, then the solution to the system of equations $\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}{{a}_{1}x+y={a}_{1}-{c}_{1}}\\\\{{a}_{2}x+y={a}_{2}-{c}_{2}}\\end{array}\\right.$ is $x=$____,$y=$____.", "answer": "To solve the given problem, we start by substituting the given solution $\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}{x=2}\\\\{y=3}\\end{array}\\right.$ into the first system of equations $\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}{{a}_{1}x+y={c}_{1}}\\\\{{a}_{2}x+y={c}_{2}}\\end{array}\\right.$. This gives us:\n\n1. For the first equation: $2{a}_{1} + 3 = {c}_{1}$\n2. For the second equation: $2{a}_{2} + 3 = {c}_{2}$\n\nFrom these, we can deduce that:\n- $c_{1} - c_{2} = 2(a_{1} - a_{2})$ and\n- $c_{1} - 2a_{1} = 3$\n\nNow, considering the second system of equations $\\left\\{\\begin{array}{l}{{a}_{1}x+y={a}_{1}-{c}_{1}}\\\\{{a}_{2}x+y={a}_{2}-{c}_{2}}\\end{array}\\right.$, and subtracting the second equation from the first, we get:\n\n$(a_{1}-a_{2})x = a_{1} - a_{2} - (c_{1} - c_{2})$\n\nSubstituting $c_{1} - c_{2} = 2(a_{1} - a_{2})$ into the equation, we find:\n\n$(a_{1}-a_{2})x = -(a_{1} - a_{2})$\n\nThis simplifies to:\n\n$x = -1$\n\nNext, we substitute $x = -1$ into the first equation of the second system of equations to find $y$:\n\n$-a_{1} + y = a_{1} - c_{1}$\n\nSolving for $y$, we get:\n\n$y = 2a_{1} - c_{1} = -(c_{1} - 2a_{1}) = -3$\n\nTherefore, the solution to the second system of equations is $\\boxed{x = -1, y = -3}$."}
