{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_250686", "question": "Consider a polynomial P(x) = 2x^3 + 5x^2 - x + 1, and let Q(x) be the polynomial obtained by reversing the coefficients of P(x), so Q(x) = x^3 + x^2 - 5x + 2. Evaluate the sum P(x) + Q(x) when x = 2, and discuss any notable properties of the resulting polynomial P(x) + Q(x).", "answer": "To begin, we find the sum of P(x) and Q(x), giving us P(x) + Q(x) = (2x^3 + 5x^2 - x + 1) + (x^3 + x^2 - 5x + 2). Combining like terms, we get P(x) + Q(x) = 3x^3 + 6x^2 - 6x + 3.\n\nNext, we evaluate the sum at x = 2: P(2) + Q(2) = 3(2)^3 + 6(2)^2 - 6(2) + 3 = 24 + 24 - 12 + 3 = 39.\n\nA notable property of the resulting polynomial P(x) + Q(x) is its symmetry. Notice that the coefficients of P(x) + Q(x) are symmetric about the middle terms. This is not a coincidence and is a consequence of the way P(x) and Q(x) are constructed as \"reverses\" of each other. Specifically, the coefficients of P(x) + Q(x) can be seen as a symmetric convolution of the coefficients of P(x) and Q(x).\n\nMoreover, observe that P(x) + Q(x) can be factored by dividing out the greatest common factor, which in this case is 3: P(x) + Q(x) = 3(x^3 + 2x^2 - 2x + 1). However, the expression inside the parenthesis cannot be easily factored further.\n\nThe symmetry of the coefficients can lead to interesting properties, such as being able to deduce the value of P(x) + Q(x) at certain values of x by exploiting the symmetric nature of the coefficients. For example, substituting x = 1/x' into P(x) + Q(x) yields a new expression that has a clear relationship to the original expression evaluated at x' due to the symmetry."}
