{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_965854", "question": "Chords  $BC$  and  $DE$  of circle  $\\omega$  meet at point  $A$ .  The line through  $D$  parallel to  $BC$  meets  $\\omega$  again at  $F$ , and  $FA$  meets  $\\omega$  again at  $T$ .  Let  $M = ET \\cap BC$  and let  $N$  be the reflection of  $A$  over  $M$ .  Show that  $(DEN)$  passes through the midpoint of  $BC$ .", "answer": "1. **Given Information and Initial Setup:**\n   - Chords \\( BC \\) and \\( DE \\) of circle \\( \\omega \\) meet at point \\( A \\).\n   - The line through \\( D \\) parallel to \\( BC \\) meets \\( \\omega \\) again at \\( F \\).\n   - Line \\( FA \\) meets \\( \\omega \\) again at \\( T \\).\n   - Let \\( M = ET \\cap BC \\).\n   - Let \\( N \\) be the reflection of \\( A \\) over \\( M \\).\n\n2. **Inversion and Reflection:**\n   - We use inversion around point \\( A \\) with radius \\( \\sqrt{AB \\cdot AC} \\) followed by a reflection around \\( A \\). This inversion swaps the pairs of points \\( (B, C) \\) and \\( (D, E) \\).\n   - Under this inversion, \\( M \\) maps to a point \\( M^* \\) on \\( BC \\) such that \\( AD \\cdot AE = AB \\cdot AC \\).\n\n3. **Properties of Trapezoids:**\n   - Since \\( DF \\parallel BC \\), quadrilateral \\( ADFM^* \\) is an isosceles trapezoid.\n   - Note that \\( N \\) maps to the midpoint of \\( AM^* \\).\n\n4. **Congruence and Midpoints:**\n   - Since \\( BDFC \\) is also an isosceles trapezoid, \\( N \\) maps to the midpoint of \\( BC \\).\n   - The midpoint of \\( BC \\) is denoted as \\( K \\).\n\n5. **Conclusion:**\n   - Since our map swaps \\( N \\) and \\( K \\), we conclude that \\( (DEN) \\) passes through the midpoint of \\( BC \\).\n\n\\(\\blacksquare\\)"}
