ese lines will already cover the plane entirely.\n\n3. **Intersection Analysis**:\n    If all boundary lines are non-parallel, consider combinations that intersect at various points. Assume the half-planes leak coverage. If any of these half-planes intersect at a common point \\( X \\), we still see redundancy. The other half-planes need to intersect such that they fill in the gaps thus rendering one half-plane unnecessary.\n\nConsidering these cases and sub-cases, we can see that:\n1. For any such configuration, one half-plane will always be redundant given that any three can be chosen such that they still cover the entire plane.\n\n### Conclusion:\nThus, we have shown that if four open half-planes cover the entire plane, it is always possible to select three of these half-planes that still cover the plane.\n\\[\n\\boxed{}\n\\]"}
