{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_8147", "question": "Consider the complex-valued function f(z) = z^2 / (z - 1)^2. What can be said about the behavior of this function near the point z = 1?", "answer": "The function f(z) = z^2 / (z - 1)^2 has a singularity at z = 1 due to the zero in the denominator. To analyze the behavior near this point, we can examine the limit as z approaches 1. \n\nWe note that the numerator approaches 1 as z approaches 1, but the denominator approaches 0, causing the function to approach infinity. However, the nature of this singularity is more nuanced, as both the numerator and denominator have zeros of order 2 at z = 1, or in the case of the denominator, a pole of order 2.\n\nThis type of singularity can be further investigated using Laurent series expansion. A Laurent series around the point z = 1 would involve rewriting f(z) in a series of terms with both positive and negative powers of (z - 1). In this case, we would find that the principal part of the series (the part with negative powers) contains a term proportional to 1 / (z - 1)^2, which dominates the behavior near z = 1.\n\nThis indicates that the function f(z) has a pole of order 2 at z = 1, which means the function approaches infinity in such a way that (z - 1)^2 f(z) approaches a finite value as z approaches 1. However, it's also important to note that, in a neighborhood of z = 1 (but not at z = 1 itself), f(z) can be approximated by a simpler function that captures its main features near the singularity.\n\nGeometrically, if we consider the function f(z) as a mapping from the z-plane to the w-plane, the point z = 1 corresponds to the point at infinity in the w-plane. This suggests that the function f(z) 'stretches' the neighborhood of z = 1 in the z-plane to the point at infinity in the w-plane."}
