{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_920133", "question": "I'm struggling with writing about characters. I'm trying to create characters that seem more real. What is it about characters that makes them feel more real and nuanced to readers?", "answer": "Crafting characters that breathe with life is a delicate art. One key aspect that makes characters feel more real and nuanced to readers is their multi-dimensionality. Think of it this way: real people are not one-trick ponies, but rather complex, messy, and often contradictory beings. Your characters should reflect this.\n\nGive your characters conflicting desires, fears, and motivations that tug at them from different directions. Perhaps your character is a brave warrior, but also secretly terrified of failure. Or, they're a brilliant scientist, but their obsessive focus on their work stems from a deep-seated insecurity. This internal tug-of-war will make your characters feel more authentic and relatable.\n\nAnother important aspect is their emotional resonance. Characters that evoke emotions in the reader - whether it's sympathy, admiration, or even frustration - are more likely to stick in their minds. Show your characters' vulnerabilities, their moments of weakness, and their capacity for love and compassion. Make the reader feel invested in their journey, and the character will start to feel more real.\n\nIt's also crucial to remember that people are products of their experiences, environments, and relationships. Give your characters a rich backstory, but don't feel the need to reveal everything at once. Drop subtle hints throughout the narrative, and let the reader piece together the puzzle of who this character is.\n\nLastly, be mindful of the little things - the way your character speaks, moves, and interacts with others. A unique voice, a quirky habit, or a distinctive mannerism can go a long way in making your character feel more fleshed out.\n\nRemember, creating real, nuanced characters is an ongoing process that unfolds throughout the story. Don't be afraid to experiment, take risks, and push your characters to grow and evolve. With time and practice, your characters will start to feel like old friends - flawed, fascinating, and full of life."}
