{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_853824", "question": "Let $n$ be an odd number. Prove that there exist $2n$ integers $a_{1}, a_{2}, \\cdots, a_{n}; b_{1}, b_{2}, \\cdots, b_{n}$ such that for any integer $k$ with $0 < k < n$, the following $3n$ numbers\n$$\na_{i}+a_{i+1}, a_{i}+b_{i}, b_{i}+b_{i+k}\n$$\n(where $i=1,2, \\cdots, n$, $a_{n+1}=a_{1}$, $b_{n+j}=b_{j}$, $0 < j < n$) have different remainders when divided by $3n$.", "answer": "Given \\( n \\) is an odd number, we need to prove that there exist \\( 2n \\) integers \\( a_1, a_2, \\cdots, a_n \\) and \\( b_1, b_2, \\cdots, b_n \\), such that the following set of numbers:\n\\[\na_i + a_{i+1},\\, a_i + b_i,\\, b_i + b_{i+k}\n\\]\nfor \\( 1 \\leq i \\leq n \\) and \\( 0 < k < n \\), have distinct remainders modulo \\( 3n \\). We define \\( a_{n+1} = a_1 \\) and \\( b_{n+j} = b_j \\) for \\( 0 < j < n \\).\n\n1. **Defining the Sequences:**\n   Define the two sequences as follows:\n   \\[\n   \\begin{aligned}\n   & a_1 = 1,\\, a_2 = 4, \\cdots,\\, a_n = 3n-2, \\\\\n   & b_1 = 2,\\, b_2 = 5, \\cdots,\\, b_n = 3n-1.\n   \\end{aligned}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Finding Residues:**\n   For any integer \\( i \\) and \\( k \\) such that \\( 1 \\leq i \\leq n \\) and \\( 1 \\leq k \\leq n-1 \\), calculate the residues modulo \\( 3 \\):\n   \\[\n   \\begin{aligned}\n   & a_i + a_{i+1} \\equiv 2 \\pmod{3}, \\\\\n   & a_i + b_i \\equiv 0 \\pmod{3}, \\\\\n   & b_i + b_{i+k} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{3}.\n   \\end{aligned}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Showing Distinct Remainders:**\n   By construction, it is not possible to find distinct indices \\( i_1, i_2, i_3 \\) and \\( k \\) such that any of the following congruences hold:\n   \\[\n   \\begin{aligned}\n   & a_{i_1} + a_{i_1+1} \\equiv a_{i_2} + b_{i_2} \\pmod{3n}, \\\\\n   & a_{i_1} + a_{i_1+1} \\equiv a_{i_3} + b_{i_3+k} \\pmod{3n}, \\\\\n   & a_{i_2} + b_{i_2} \\equiv b_{i_3} + b_{i_3+k} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\end{aligned}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Verifying \\( b_{i_1} + b_{i_1+k} \\not\\equiv b_{i_2} + b_{i_2+k} \\):**\n   Assume there exist distinct indices \\( i_1, i_2 \\) such that:\n   \\[\n   b_{i_1} + b_{i_1+k} \\equiv b_{i_2} + b_{i_2+k} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\]\n   Then,\n   \\[\n   \\begin{aligned}\n   & b_{i_1} + b_{i_1+k} \\equiv b_{i_2} + b_{i_2+k} \\pmod{3n}, \\\\\n   \\Rightarrow & b_{i_1} + b_{i_1+k} = b_{i_2} + b_{i_2+k}, \\\\\n   \\Rightarrow & b_{i_1} + b_{i_1} + 3k \\equiv b_{i_2} + b_{i_2} + 3k \\pmod{3n}, \\\\\n   \\Rightarrow & 2b_{i_1} \\equiv 2b_{i_2} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\end{aligned}\n   \\]\n   Since \\( n \\) is odd and \\( (2, 3n) = 1 \\),\n   \\[\n   b_{i_1} \\equiv b_{i_2} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\]\n   Given \\( 0 < b_{i_1}, b_{i_2} < 3n \\), we conclude \\( b_{i_1} = b_{i_2} \\), implying \\( i_1 = i_2 \\), a contradiction.\n\n5. **Verifying \\( a_{i_1} + a_{i_1+1} \\not\\equiv a_{i_2} + a_{i_2+1} \\):**\n   A similar argument to step 4 shows:\n   \\[\n   a_{i_1} + a_{i_{1}+1} \\not\\equiv a_{i_2} + a_{i_2+1} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\]\n\n6. **Verifying \\( a_{i_1} + b_{i_1} \\not\\equiv a_{i_2} + b_{i_2} \\):**\n   Assume there exist distinct indices \\( i_1, i_2 \\) such that:\n   \\[\n   a_{i_1} + b_{i_1} \\equiv a_{i_2} + b_{i_2} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\]\n   Then,\n   \\[\n   \\begin{aligned}\n   & a_{i_1} + b_{i_1} = a_{i_2} + b_{i_2}, \\\\\n   & \\Rightarrow a_{i_1} + a_{i_1+1} \\equiv a_{i_2} + a_{i_2+1} \\pmod{3n}, \\\\\n   & \\Rightarrow 2a_{i_1} \\equiv 2a_{i_2} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\end{aligned}\n   \\]\n   Since \\( n \\) is odd and \\( (2, 3n) = 1 \\),\n   \\[\n   a_{i_1} \\equiv a_{i_2} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\]\n   Thus by \\( 0 < a_{i_1}, a_{i_2} < 3n \\), we find \\( a_{i_1} = a_{i_2} \\), implying \\( i_1 = i_2 \\), a contradiction. Therefore,\n   \\[\n   a_{i_1} + b_{i_1} \\not\\equiv a_{i_2} + b_{i_2} \\pmod{3n}.\n   \\]\n\nConclusion: Therefore, the sequences \\( a_1, a_2, \\cdots, a_n \\) and \\( b_1, b_2, \\cdots, b_n \\) satisfy the conditions given in the problem statement, and the residues modulo \\( 3n \\) of the set numbers are distinct. \n$\\blacksquare$"}
