{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_327629", "question": "30 square stone slabs of equal size were needed to cover a floor area of 58.8 sq . m . find the length of each stone slab ?", "answer": "To find the length of each stone slab, we first need to determine the area of one stone slab. Since we have 30 stone slabs covering a total area of 58.8 square meters, we can divide the total area by the number of slabs to find the area of one slab.\n\nArea of one stone slab = Total area / Number of slabs\nArea of one stone slab = 58.8 sq. m / 30\nArea of one stone slab = 1.96 sq. m\n\nNow, assuming that each stone slab is square in shape (since the question mentions \"square stone slabs\"), the length of each side of the slab would be the square root of the area.\n\nLength of one side of the stone slab = √(Area of one stone slab)\nLength of one side of the stone slab = √(1.96 sq. m)\nLength of one side of the stone slab = 1.4 m\n\nTherefore, the length of each square stone slab is $\\boxed{1.4}$  meters."}
