{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_340410", "question": "Write a Python function that takes two lists of tag objects (each with a `.name` attribute) and returns a tuple of two values: a boolean indicating whether the two lists have any common tags, and a string containing the tag names that are common to both lists.", "answer": "Here's an example implementation of the function:\n\n```python\ndef common_tags(list1, list2):\n    set1 = set(tag.name for tag in list1)\n    common = any(tag.name in set1 for tag in list2)\n    common_tag_names = ', '.join(tag.name for tag in list2 if tag.name in set1)\n    return common, common_tag_names\n```\n\nThis function uses a set to store the names of the tags from the first list, then checks if the names of the tags in the second list are present in the set. If a common tag is found, its name is appended to the `common_tag_names` string. The `common` variable is a boolean indicating whether any common tags were found."}
