{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_880804", "question": "Prove that \\(\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} (-1)^n \\log n = \\infty\\).", "answer": "Given the problem, we need to prove that\n\\[\n\\lim _{n \\rightarrow \\infty}(-1)^{n} \\lg n = \\infty.\n\\]\n\n1. Consider any $\\varepsilon > 0$.\n2. Evaluate the absolute value $\\left|(-1)^{n} \\lg n\\right|$:\n   \\[\n   \\left|(-1)^{n} \\lg n \\right| = \\lg n.\n   \\]\n3. We want to find when $\\lg n$ exceeds $\\varepsilon$:\n   \\[\n   \\lg n > \\varepsilon.\n   \\]\n4. Recall the equivalence between logarithmic and exponential functions:\n   \\[\n   \\lg n > \\varepsilon \\Leftrightarrow n > 10^{\\varepsilon}.\n   \\]\n5. Set \\( N = \\left\\lfloor 10^{\\varepsilon} \\right\\rfloor \\). For instance,\n   if \\(\\varepsilon = 100\\), then \\( N = 10^{100} \\).\n\n6. Now, if \\( n > N \\), we have:\n   \\[\n   \\lg n > \\varepsilon \\implies \\left|(-1)^{n} \\lg n\\right| > \\varepsilon.\n   \\]\n\n7. This shows that for any \\( \\varepsilon > 0 \\), there exists \\( N \\) such that whenever \\( n > N \\),\n   \\(\\left|(-1)^{n} \\lg n\\right| > \\varepsilon\\), confirming that:\n   \\[\n   \\lim _{n \\rightarrow \\infty}(-1)^{n} \\lg n = \\infty.\n   \\]\n\nConclusively, it is established that \\( \\lim _{n \\rightarrow \\infty}(-1)^{n} \\lg n = \\infty \\).\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\infty}\n\\]"}
