 it is necessary.\n\nSome argue that foreign aid can hinder development by creating dependency on the donor country, leaving recipient countries unable to support themselves when aid is withdrawn. Moreover, foreign aid is often misused due to corruption and mismanagement of funds, resulting in significant debt burdens. However, there are also notable benefits.\n\nForeign aid can be instrumental in alleviating poverty in developing countries by providing essential necessities like food and water. Additionally, it can facilitate the development of better infrastructure and sanitation systems. These improvements can have a lasting impact on the quality of life for local communities.\n\nHowever, I agree with those who advocate for conditional foreign aid to ensure a positive impact. One key condition is the effective use of aid, which can be achieved through stringent regulations and anti-corruption measures. It is also crucial that recipient countries have a clear plan for eventually becoming self-sufficient.\n\nUltimately, foreign aid can be beneficial, but only under certain conditions. To ensure that aid is used productively, strict regulations must be in place, and corruption must be minimal. By adopting a more nuanced approach to foreign aid, we can maximize its benefits while minimizing its drawbacks.\n\nSome specific changes made include:\n\n* Revising sentence structures to improve clarity and flow\n* Using more precise vocabulary (e.g., \"contentious\" instead of \"controversial\")\n* Adding transitional phrases to connect ideas between sentences and paragraphs\n* Using more concise language to convey the same message\n* Changing some phrases to make them more formal and suitable for an essay\n* Emphasizing the importance of effective aid use and self-sufficiency for recipient countries."}
