{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_81812", "question": "A snail is at the bottom of a 20-foot well. Each day, it climbs up 3 feet, but at night, it slips back 2 feet. How many days will it take for the snail to reach the top of the well?", "answer": "To solve this problem, let's analyze the snail's progress. The snail effectively climbs 1 foot per day (3 feet up during the day, then slips 2 feet back at night). However, on the day it reaches the top of the well, it won't slip back because it's already at the top.\n\nSince the well is 20 feet deep, the snail needs to climb 20 feet to reach the top. To climb 17 feet (20 - 3 feet that it climbs on the final day), it would take the snail 17 days (since it climbs 1 foot per day effectively). But on the 18th day, when it climbs 3 feet, it will reach the top. \n\nTherefore, it will take the snail 18 days to reach the top of the well."}
