{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_23476", "question": "A group of $15$ pirates agree to divide a treasure chest of gold coins among themselves as follows. The $k^\\text{th}$ pirate to take a share takes $\\frac{k}{15}$ of the coins that remain in the chest. The number of coins initially in the chest is the smallest number for which this arrangement will allow each pirate to receive a positive whole number of coins. How many coins does the $15^{\\text{th}}$ pirate receive?\nA. $3^4 \\cdot 5^4 \\cdot 7 \\cdot 11 \\cdot 13$\nB. $3^{14} \\cdot 5^{14}$\nC. $14!$\nD. $15^{14}$", "answer": "1. **Initial Setup and Recursive Formula**:\n   Let $x$ be the initial number of coins. The $k^\\text{th}$ pirate takes $\\frac{k}{15}$ of the remaining coins. We can express the number of coins left after each pirate takes their share recursively:\n   - After the 1st pirate: $x_1 = \\frac{14}{15}x$\n   - After the 2nd pirate: $x_2 = \\frac{13}{15}x_1$\n   - Continue this pattern until the $15^\\text{th}$ pirate.\n\n2. **Expression for the $15^\\text{th}$ Pirate**:\n   The $15^\\text{th}$ pirate takes all remaining coins, denoted as $x_{14}$. Calculating $x_{14}$:\n   \\[\n   x_{14} = \\left(\\frac{1}{15}\\right) \\left(\\frac{2}{15}\\right) \\cdots \\left(\\frac{14}{15}\\right) x = \\frac{14!}{15^{14}} x\n   \\]\n\n3. **Finding the Smallest $x$**:\n   We need $x_{14}$ to be an integer. Therefore, $x$ must be a multiple of the denominator of $\\frac{14!}{15^{14}}$ when reduced. Simplifying the factors:\n   \\[\n   15^{14} = (3 \\cdot 5)^{14} = 3^{14} \\cdot 5^{14}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   14! = 14 \\cdot 13 \\cdot \\dots \\cdot 2 \\cdot 1\n   \\]\n   After factoring and simplifying, we find the smallest multiple that makes all terms integers:\n   \\[\n   x = 3^{14} \\cdot 5^{14} / \\text{factors from } 14!\n   \\]\n   Calculating the least common multiple and smallest $x$, we find that the smallest valid $x$ is determined by the missing factors above, which are primarily powers of 3 and 5. We find that $x = 3^4 \\cdot 5^4 \\cdot 7 \\cdot 11 \\cdot 13$.\n\n4. **Conclusion**:\n   The $15^\\text{th}$ pirate receives:\n   \\[\n   3^4 \\cdot 5^4 \\cdot 7 \\cdot 11 \\cdot 13\n   \\]\nThe final answer is $\\boxed{A}$"}
