{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_514475", "question": "Simplify $\\dfrac{x^{2}-y^{2}}{x-y}$.", "answer": "**Analysis**\n\nThis problem mainly tests the mixed operation of fractions, factorization, and reduction. The key to solving it is to factorize the numerator and denominator, then simplify to get the simplest algebraic expression.\n\n**Solution**\n\nGiven expression $= \\dfrac{x^{2}-y^{2}}{x-y} = \\dfrac{(x+y)(x-y)}{x-y} = x+y$.\n\nTherefore, the answer is $\\boxed{x+y}$."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_24560", "question": "I am trying to find the derivative of f(x) = (2x + 1) / (x - 1).  I applied the quotient rule. Can you walk me through the steps and evaluate my work?", "answer": "To find the derivative of f(x) = (2x + 1) / (x - 1), applying the quotient rule is a good approach. The quotient rule states that if f(x) = g(x) / h(x), then f'(x) = (h(x)g'(x) - g(x)h'(x)) / (h(x))^2.\n\nLet's break down your function: g(x) = 2x + 1 and h(x) = x - 1. The derivatives of these functions are g'(x) = 2 and h'(x) = 1.\n\nNow, applying the quotient rule: f'(x) = ((x - 1)(2) - (2x + 1)(1)) / (x - 1)^2.\n\nThis simplifies to f'(x) = (2x - 2 - 2x - 1) / (x - 1)^2. The numerator can be further simplified to -3.\n\nSo, f'(x) = -3 / (x - 1)^2. This is the derivative of your original function. \n\nDid your work match this solution? If you made any mistakes, this should help you identify the error."}
