{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_109037", "question": "Eighteen years after a teenager's naked body was found floating in a Utah river, police have arrested a convicted murderer thanks to DNA from a cigarette butt. Michael Simpson, 46, from Florida, is . being held on suspicion of aggravated murder in the killing of . 17-year-old Krystal Lynn Beslanowitch, whose bloodied and broken body . was found on December 6, 1995, along the Provo River in Utah. The lead investigator at the time, Wasatch County Sheriff Todd Bonner, flew to Sarasota County to help take Simpson into custody. After years of dead-end leads, DNA . technology improved and last January, investigators finally got a match . on Simpson from evidence at the scene, authorities said. Michael Simpson, 46, right, is . being held on suspicion of aggravated murder in the killing of . Krystal Lynn Beslanowitch, 17, left whose bloodied and broken body . was found December 6, 1995 . To corroborate the evidence, Bonner and . another detective flew to Florida on August 25, and were able to get a . new DNA sample from Simpson from a discarded cigarette after following him for days. Though it is not clear how or if the two knew each other, Krystal's mother told The Deseret News in 1996 that her daughter was involved with drugs and was prostituting by age 15. 'Every time she came home she had her arms spread out wide and a big smile on her face. I never refused her. I always loved her,' Linde Toreson said at the time. 'Whatever she was doing (she thought) was more important than living a normal life.' Krystal and her boyfriend had only moved to Utah from their home town of Spokane, Washington, just five months before she was killed. He reported her missing two days after she failed to return from a late-night trip to a Salt Lake convenience store. Bonner said at a news conference yesterday that he was thrilled at . the arrest, the Salt Lake Tribune reported. 'It's a case that's haunted me for . almost my whole career,' he said, adding that Krystal's parents  were 'relieved and emotional' at the news and happy it was moving forward. Previously, Simpson was charged with second-degree felony murder in 1987 and pleaded guilty two months later, according to Utah court documents. He was paroled from the Utah State Prison in April 1995, and was free at the time of Krystal's slaying, according to Utah Board of Pardons and Parole records.", "answer": "Eighteen years after the brutal murder of 17-year-old Krystal Lynn Beslanowitch, whose body was found in the Provo River in Utah on December 6, 1995, police have arrested Michael Simpson, 46, from Florida. Simpson, a convicted murderer, is being held on suspicion of aggravated murder. The breakthrough came when DNA technology advanced, allowing investigators to match Simpson's DNA to evidence from the crime scene. To confirm the match, investigators followed Simpson in Florida and obtained a new DNA sample from a discarded cigarette butt. Krystal, who had moved to Utah from Spokane, Washington, with her boyfriend just five months before her death, was involved in drugs and prostitution. Her mother, Linde Toreson, had always welcomed her back home despite her lifestyle. The lead investigator, Wasatch County Sheriff Todd Bonner, expressed relief and emotion at the arrest, noting that the case had haunted him throughout his career. Simpson, who was paroled from Utah State Prison in April 1995, was free at the time of Krystal's murder."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_185208", "question": "I am interested in switching careers, going from a corporate job to a non-profit.  I have 20 years of experience and multiple skill sets that could translate.  I am also in my early 50's.  What are some considerations to take into account when making this career transition?", "answer": "Making a career transition from a corporate job to a non-profit can be a rewarding and fulfilling move, especially when you have a strong foundation of transferable skills. Considering your 20 years of experience and multiple skill sets, you'll likely be an attractive candidate to non-profit organizations. However, it's essential to take into account a few key considerations to ensure a smooth transition.\n\nOne crucial factor is the potential pay cut. Non-profit salaries can be lower compared to corporate salaries, so it's essential to assess your financial situation and determine if you can accommodate a possible reduction in income. Additionally, you may need to consider adjusting your lifestyle or exploring other sources of income to supplement your non-profit salary.\n\nAnother vital consideration is the cultural shift. Non-profits often have a distinct culture that may be different from what you're used to in the corporate world. Be prepared to adapt to a more collaborative and mission-driven environment, where resources may be limited, and creativity is encouraged.\n\nYour age can also be a factor in this transition. While ageism is not unique to non-profits, it's essential to be aware of potential biases. Focus on highlighting your relevant skills, experience, and achievements in your application materials and during interviews. Emphasize your enthusiasm for the non-profit sector and the value you can bring to the organization.\n\nNetworking is also crucial in this transition. Attend industry events, join non-profit professional associations, and connect with people in your desired field. Building relationships and learning from others who have made similar transitions can help you navigate this new landscape.\n\nLastly, consider taking a strategic approach to your job search. Look for organizations that align with your values and passions, and explore different types of non-profits, such as foundations, advocacy groups, or direct service providers. You may also want to explore volunteer or consulting opportunities to gain experience and build connections in the non-profit sector before making a full-time transition.\n\nBy carefully considering these factors, you can set yourself up for success in your transition to a non-profit career and find a fulfilling and meaningful role that leverages your skills and experience."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_449390", "question": "You are the President of the United States. America is facing an economic crisis and there have been riots in major cities. What steps are you taking to bring order back to the country?", "answer": "My fellow Americans, these are indeed trying times for our great nation. As the President of the United States, my top priority is to restore order, stability, and confidence in our economy and our communities. To address the economic crisis, I've convened an emergency meeting with my economic advisors, Congressional leaders, and the Federal Reserve to implement immediate measures to stimulate growth, create jobs, and support affected industries.\n\nFirst, we're working on a comprehensive stimulus package that will inject vital funding into critical sectors, such as infrastructure development, education, and small business support. This package will not only create jobs but also invest in the long-term growth and competitiveness of our economy.\n\nSecond, I've directed our law enforcement agencies to work closely with state and local authorities to quell the riots and maintain public safety. We will not tolerate violence or lawlessness in our streets, and those responsible will be held accountable. However, we also recognize the underlying frustrations that have led to these protests, and we're committed to addressing the root causes of inequality, poverty, and social injustice.\n\nTo this end, I've established a task force to engage with community leaders, civil rights organizations, and social service providers to develop concrete solutions to these pressing issues. We'll be working to increase access to affordable healthcare, education, and job training programs, as well as implementing policies to address housing affordability and economic mobility.\n\nFurthermore, I've authorized the deployment of National Guard units to support local law enforcement in maintaining order and protecting critical infrastructure. However, I want to emphasize that our approach will be guided by a commitment to de-escalation and community engagement, rather than relying solely on military force.\n\nLastly, I'm calling on all Americans to come together in this time of crisis. We must put aside our differences and work towards a common purpose: rebuilding our economy, restoring our communities, and reaffirming our commitment to the values of justice, equality, and opportunity for all. We will get through this, and we will emerge stronger, more resilient, and more united than ever."}
