{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_236711", "question": "For some positive integers $a$ and $b$, compute $a+b$ if the product \\[\\log_a(a+1) \\cdot \\log_{a+1} (a+2) \\dotsm \\log_{b-2} (b-1) \\cdot \\log_{b-1} b\\] contains exactly $1560$ terms, and its value is $3.$", "answer": "By using the change-of-base formula, the expression simplifies to \\[\\frac{\\log b}{\\log a},\\] which is \\(\\log_a b\\). Setting \\(\\log_a b = 3\\), we get \\(b = a^3\\).\n\nGiven that the expression has $1560$ logarithms, the number of terms is $(b-1) - a + 1 = 1560$. Simplifying gives $b-a=1560$. Substituting $b=a^3$ into $b-a=1560$ yields:\n\\[a^3 - a = 1560.\\]\nThis simplifies to:\n\\[a^3 - a - 1560 = 0.\\]\n\nUsing numerical methods or trial and error, we find \\(a = 12\\). Substituting back, we get \\(b = 12^3 = 1728\\).\n\nThus, \\(a+b = 12 + 1728 = \\boxed{1740}.\\)"}
