{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_974589", "question": "In Python, a class attribute is a piece of data that is associated with the class itself. It is shared by all instances of that class. You can access a class attribute using the class name, followed by a dot (.) and the attribute name. You can also assign a new value to a class attribute, which will change the value for all instances of that class.\n\nWrite a Python function `convert_attributes_to_camel_case(obj)` that takes an object `obj` as input and converts every attribute name of that object to camel case, assuming that the attribute names are all lowercase words separated by underscores. The function should return the modified object.\n\nFor example, if the input object has an attribute `hello_world`, the function should modify it to `helloWorld`.", "answer": "In Python, a class attribute is a piece of data that is associated with the class itself. It is shared by all instances of that class. You can access a class attribute using the class name, followed by a dot (.) and the attribute name. You can also assign a new value to a class attribute, which will change the value for all instances of that class.\n\nIn this instruction, you are asked to write a Python function `convert_attributes_to_camel_case(obj)` that takes an object `obj` as input and converts every attribute name of that object to camel case, assuming that the attribute names are all lowercase words separated by underscores. The function should return the modified object.\n\nHere is the implementation of the `convert_attributes_to_camel_case(obj)` function using the built-in `re` module and `setattr` function:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\ndef convert_attributes_to_camel_case(obj):\n    for name in dir(obj):\n        if name.startswith('_'):\n            continue\n\n        value = getattr(obj, name)\n\n        if isinstance(value, (int, float, str)):\n            new_name = re.sub(r'_[a-z]', lambda m: m.group(0)[1].upper(), name)\n            setattr(obj, new_name, value)\n            delattr(obj, name)\n```"}
