{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_954924", "question": "Write a simple program to demonstrate the use of Python's built-in data structures such as\nlists, dictionaries, sets, and tuples.", "answer": "Here's an example program demonstrating the use of Python's built-in data structures:\n\n```python\n# Lists\nfruits = ['apple', 'banana', 'cherry']\nprint(\"Fruits (list):\", fruits)\nprint(\"Accessing list element:\", fruits[0])\nfruits.append('date')\nprint(\"List after appending:\", fruits)\n\n# Dictionaries\nperson = {'name': 'John', 'age': 30, 'city': 'New York'}\nprint(\"\\nPerson (dictionary):\", person)\nprint(\"Accessing dictionary value:\", person['name'])\nperson['country'] = 'USA'\nprint(\"Dictionary after adding key-value pair:\", person)\n\n# Sets\ncolors = {'red', 'green', 'blue'}\nprint(\"\\nColors (set):\", colors)\ncolors.add('yellow')\nprint(\"Set after adding element:\", colors)\ncolors.remove('green')\nprint(\"Set after removing element:\", colors)\n\n# Tuples\nnumbers = (1, 2, 3)\nprint(\"\\nNumbers (tuple):\", numbers)\nprint(\"Accessing tuple element:\", numbers[0])\n# Tuples are immutable, so we can't modify them\ntry:\n    numbers[0] = 10\nexcept TypeError:\n    print(\"Error: Tuples are immutable\")\n\n# Example of combining data structures\nstudents = [\n    {'name': 'Alice', 'grade': 'A'},\n    {'name': 'Bob', 'grade': 'B'},\n    {'name': 'Charlie', 'grade': 'A'}\n]\nprint(\"\\nStudents (list of dictionaries):\")\nfor student in students:\n    print(student['name'], \":\", student['grade'])\n\n# Example of using set operations\nstudents_with_A_grade = {student['name'] for student in students if student['grade'] == 'A'}\nprint(\"\\nStudents with A grade (set):\", students_with_A_grade)\n```\n\nIn this example, we create instances of each data structure, perform common operations on them, and demonstrate how to access and modify their elements. We also show how to combine data structures, such as a list of dictionaries, and use set operations to extract specific data."}
