{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_84406", "question": "Given the sets $A=\\{-2,0,1\\}$ and $B=\\{x \\mid x^2 > 1\\}$, find the intersection $A \\cap B = \\text{________}$.", "answer": "Let us analyze the given sets:\n\nSet $A$ consists of the elements $\\{-2,0,1\\}$. \n\nThe set $B$ consists of all the elements $x$ such that $x^2 > 1$. This translates to values of $x$ which are less than $-1$ or greater than $1$ because both negative and positive values of $x$ can result in a square greater than $1$. Thus, $B = \\{x \\mid x < -1 \\text{ or } x > 1\\}$.\n\nNow we are interested in finding the intersection of sets $A$ and $B$, denoted by $A \\cap B$. The intersection consists of all elements that are common to both sets $A$ and $B$. By examining the elements of set $A$, we notice that only $-2$ satisfies the condition $x^2 > 1$ (since $(-2)^2 = 4 > 1$), while the other elements $0$ and $1$ do not.\n\nTherefore, the intersection of sets $A$ and $B$ is $\\boxed{\\{-2\\}}$."}
