{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_73533", "question": "A rectangular field is to be fenced on three sides leaving a side of 30 feet uncovered. If 70 feet of fencing will be required, what is the area of the field?", "answer": "Let's call the length of the uncovered side L and the length of the other two sides that need to be fenced W (for width). We know that L = 30 feet.\n\nThe total amount of fencing required is 70 feet, and this will be used to cover two widths and one length. Since one length (L) is not covered by the fencing, we only need to account for the two widths (2W) in our calculation.\n\nSo, we have:\nL + 2W = 70 feet\n\nWe know L = 30 feet, so we can substitute that into the equation:\n30 + 2W = 70\n\nNow, we solve for W:\n2W = 70 - 30\n2W = 40\nW = 40 / 2\nW = 20 feet\n\nNow that we have both the length and the width, we can calculate the area of the field:\nArea = L * W\nArea = 30 feet * 20 feet\nArea = 600 square feet\n\nThe area of the field is $\\boxed{600}$  square feet."}
