{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_438153", "question": "Consider the line parameterized by\n\\[\n\\begin{align*}\nx &= 3t + 1,\\\\\ny &= 2t + 3.\n\\end{align*}\n\\]\nFind a vector $\\begin{pmatrix} a \\\\ b \\end{pmatrix}$ pointing from the origin to this line that is parallel to $\\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix}$.", "answer": "We start by representing the line and vector as:\n\\[\n\\begin{pmatrix} x \\\\ y \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 3t + 1 \\\\ 2t + 3 \\end{pmatrix}, \\quad \\text{and} \\quad \\begin{pmatrix} a \\\\ b \\end{pmatrix} = k \\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\\\ 2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 3k \\\\ 2k \\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\nfor some real number $k$.\n\nTo find the intersection of the vector and the line, equate the vector and line equations:\n\\[\n\\begin{pmatrix} 3t + 1 \\\\ 2t + 3 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 3k \\\\ 2k \\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\nSolving the equations \\(3t + 1 = 3k\\) and \\(2t + 3 = 2k\\), we get from the first equation \\(t + \\frac{1}{3} = k\\) and from the second \\(t + \\frac{3}{2} = k\\).\n\nSetting these equal gives:\n\\[\nt + \\frac{1}{3} = t + \\frac{3}{2}\n\\]\nSolving this, we find \\(t = -\\frac{7}{6}\\). Plugging back into \\(k = t + \\frac{1}{3}\\), we get \\(k = -1\\).\n\nThus, the intersection point is:\n\\[\n\\begin{pmatrix} 3(-1) \\\\ 2(-1) \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\\\ -2 \\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\n\nSince the vector must point from the origin to the line, the vector is:\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\\\ -2 \\end{pmatrix}}\n\\]"}
