{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_672798", "question": "A snail is at the bottom of a 20-foot well. Each day, it climbs up 3 feet, but at night, it slips back 2 feet. How many days will it take for the snail to reach the top of the well?", "answer": "To solve this problem, we need to think about the daily progress of the snail. Each day, it climbs 3 feet and then slips back 2 feet at night, so the net gain each day is 1 foot. \n\nHowever, when the snail reaches 18 feet, it can climb 3 feet and reach the top in the daytime. At this point, it won't slip back at night because it has already reached the top. \n\nSo, the snail needs to cover 18 feet with a net gain of 1 foot per day, which takes 18 days. Then, on the 19th day, it can climb the remaining 2 feet to reach the top and the final climb on that day will put it out of the well.\n\nTherefore, it will take 18 days for the snail to climb the first 18 feet, and on the 19th day, it will reach the top, making the total number of days 18 + 1 = 19 days for the snail to reach the top of the well,"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_852056", "question": "What is the value of the sum $-1 + 2 - 3 + 4 - 5 + 6 - 7 +\\dots+ 10,\\!000$?", "answer": "We can group the terms in pairs to make it easier to calculate.\nThe sum of each pair is $-1 + 2 = 1$, $-3 + 4 = 1$, $-5 + 6 = 1$, and so on.\nSince there are $10,\\!000$ terms, there are $10,\\!000/2 = 5000$ pairs.\nSo the sum of all the terms is $1\\cdot 5000 = \\boxed{5000}$.\nThe answer is: 5000"}
