{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_956500", "question": "Given the function $f(x)= \\begin{cases} 3+\\log_{2}x, & x > 0 \\\\ x^{2}-x-1, & x \\leqslant 0 \\end{cases}$, find the solution set for the inequality $f(x)\\leqslant 5$.\n\nA: $[-1,1]$\nB: $(-\\infty,-2]\\cup(0, 4)$\nC: $[-2,4]$\nD: $(-\\infty,-2]\\cup[0,4]$", "answer": "Since $f(x)= \\begin{cases} 3+\\log_{2}x, & x > 0 \\\\ x^{2}-x-1, & x \\leqslant 0 \\end{cases}$,\n\nFor $x > 0$, $3+\\log_{2}x \\leqslant 5$, which implies $\\log_{2}x \\leqslant 2=\\log_{2}4$. Solving this, we obtain $0 < x \\leqslant 4$.\n\nFor $x \\leqslant 0$, $x^{2}-x-1 \\leqslant 5$, which implies $(x-3)(x+2) \\leqslant 0$. Solving this, we obtain $-2 \\leqslant x \\leqslant 3$.\n\nTherefore, the solution set for the inequality $f(x)\\leqslant 5$ is $\\boxed{[-2,4]}$.\n\nSo the answer is: C.\n\nTo solve this problem, we need to analyze the inequality based on the piecewise function, solve each inequality separately, and then find their union. This problem tests basic knowledge of piecewise functions, inequality solving, and set operations."}
