riding Black. The man blamed himself and the horse for her death, leading to his decision to sell the horse.\n\nDespite the odds stacked against them, Alec and Black ultimately make it to a prestigious racing event where they have the chance to prove themselves. In the movie's climax, they face off against their biggest rivals in the most important race of their lives.\n\nIn the final race, Alec and Black manage to overcome all challenges, including betrayal and sabotage, and win the race in a thrilling photo finish. Their victory proves that talent and hard work, combined with a genuine connection between rider and horse, can overcome any obstacles.\n\nStep 4: Close the story\nThe movie ends with Alec and Black becoming legendary figures in the horse racing world. The mysterious man who sold Black comes to terms with his past, having seen Alec help the horse reach its true potential. Alec's persistence and dedication to his dream inspires others to believe in themselves and work towards their goals."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_962132", "question": "Let f(x) = x^3 + x^2 - 6x - 6 and g(x) = x^2 - 3x - 3.  Find (f/g)(x).", "answer": "To find the quotient of f(x) and g(x), we can perform polynomial long division. \n\nWe divide the leading term of f(x), x^3, by the leading term of g(x), x^2, to get x. We then multiply g(x) by x to obtain x^3 - 3x^2 - 3x, which we subtract from f(x). This leaves us with 4x^2 + 3x - 6.\n\nNow we divide the leading term of the remainder, 4x^2, by the leading term of g(x), x^2, to get 4. We multiply g(x) by 4 to get 4x^2 - 12x - 12, and subtract this from the remainder to get 15x + 6.\n\nSo, we have (f/g)(x) = x + 4 + (15x + 6)/(x^2 - 3x - 3).\n\nWe can stop here, but it's worth noting that the remainder can't be further divided by g(x) since its degree is lower than that of g(x)."}
