{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_458585", "question": "Determine all prime numbers \\( p \\) such that \n$$\n5^{p} + 4 \\cdot p^{4}\n$$\nis a perfect square, i.e., the square of an integer.", "answer": "1. Let the expression \\(5^p + 4 \\cdot p^4 = q^2\\), where \\(q\\) is an integer.\n\n2. Rewrite the given equation in the form of two factors involving \\(q\\):\n   \\[\n   5^p = (q - 2p^2)(q + 2p^2)\n   \\]\n\n3. Because \\(5^p\\) is a power of prime \\(5\\), both factors \\((q - 2p^2)\\) and \\((q + 2p^2)\\) must also be powers of \\(5\\):\n   \\[\n   q - 2p^2 = 5^s \\quad \\text{and} \\quad q + 2p^2 = 5^t\n   \\]\n   where \\(0 \\leq s < t\\) and \\(s + t = p\\).\n\n4. By eliminating \\(q\\) from these equations, we get:\n   \\[\n   q + 2p^2 - (q - 2p^2) = 5^t - 5^s\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   4p^2 = 5^s (5^{t-s} - 1)\n   \\]\n\n5. If \\(s > 0\\), we have \\(5 \\mid 4p^2\\). Since \\(4p^2\\) is divisible by \\(5\\), \\(p\\) must be divisible by \\(5\\). Therefore, \\(p = 5\\) is a candidate, and we can check if the expression is indeed a perfect square:\n   \\[\n   (p = 5) \\quad 5^5 + 4 \\cdot 5^4 = 3125 + 2500 = 5625\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   5625 = 75^2\n   \\]\n   So, it is indeed a perfect square when \\(p = 5\\).\n\n6. If \\(s = 0\\), then \\(t = p\\). This gives us the equation:\n   \\[\n   5^p = 4p^2 + 1\n   \\]\n\n7. To show that \\(5^k > 4k^2 + 1\\) for \\(k \\geq 2\\), we use mathematical induction:\n\n    - **Base case:** Check for \\(k = 2\\):\n      \\[\n      5^2 = 25 \\quad \\text{and} \\quad 4 \\cdot 2^2 + 1 = 4 \\cdot 4 + 1 = 17\n      \\]\n      \\[\n      25 > 17 \\quad \\text{Thus, the base case holds.}\n      \\]\n\n    - **Induction hypothesis:** Assume for some \\(k \\geq 2\\), \\(5^k > 4k^2 + 1\\).\n\n    - **Inductive step:** Show it holds for \\(k + 1\\):\n      \\[\n      5^{k+1} = 5 \\cdot 5^k > 5 \\cdot (4k^2 + 1)\n      \\]\n      \\[\n      5 \\cdot (4k^2 + 1) = 20k^2 + 5\n      \\]\n      Now, we need to show:\n      \\[\n      20k^2 + 5 > 4(k+1)^2 + 1\n      \\]\n      \\[\n      20k^2 + 5 > 4(k^2 + 2k + 1) + 1\n      \\]\n      Simplify:\n      \\[\n      20k^2 + 5 > 4k^2 + 8k + 4 + 1\n      \\]\n      \\[\n      20k^2 + 5 > 4k^2 + 8k + 5\n      \\]\n      \\[\n      20k^2 > 4k^2 + 8k\n      \\]\n      \\[\n      16k^2 > 8k\n      \\]\n      \\[\n      2k > 1\n      \\]\n      Since \\(k \\geq 2\\), the inequality \\(2k > 1\\) always holds. Thus, by induction, \\(5^k > 4k^2 + 1\\) holds for all \\(k \\geq 2\\).\n\nTherefore, there are no other primes \\(p\\) satisfying the original equation other than \\(p=5\\).\n\n### Conclusion:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{5}\n\\]"}
