{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_203870", "question": "In front of the elevator doors are people with masses of $150, 62, 63, 66, 70, 75, 79, 84, 95, 96,$ and $99$ kg. The load capacity of the elevator is $190$ kg. What is the minimum number of trips required to ensure all people can be transported?", "answer": "1. **Identify Constraints**: \n   The given masses of people are \\(150, 62, 63, 66, 70, 75, 79, 84, 95, 96\\) and \\(99\\) kg. The maximum load capacity of the elevator is \\(190\\) kg.\n\n2. **Calculate and Validate Basic Constraints**:\n   Since the elevator can carry at most \\(190\\) kg, we check the minimum combined mass of three people:\n   \\[\n   62 + 63 + 66 = 191 \\quad (\\text{which is greater than } 190)\n   \\]\n   Therefore, it's impossible for three people to ride together without exceeding the limit. Consequently, the elevator can carry at most two people at a time or one if their mass exceeds \\(190\\) kg when adding another individual.\n\n3. **Single-Ride for the Heaviest Person**:\n   The individual weighing \\(150\\) kg must ride alone because the combined mass with any other individual exceeds \\(190\\) kg.\n\n4. **Pairs for Remaining People**: \n   We need to find pairs of the remaining people such that the total mass for each pair is less than or equal to \\(190\\) kg. \n\n   Calculate pairs:\n   - \\(62\\) kg and \\(99\\) kg: \n     \\[\n     62 + 99 = 161 \\quad (\\text{which is less than } 190)\n     \\]\n   - \\(63\\) kg and \\(96\\) kg:\n     \\[\n     63 + 96 = 159 \\quad (\\text{which is less than } 190)\n     \\]\n   - \\(66\\) kg and \\(95\\) kg:\n     \\[\n     66 + 95 = 161 \\quad (\\text{which is less than } 190)\n     \\]\n   - \\(70\\) kg and \\(84\\) kg:\n     \\[\n     70 + 84 = 154 \\quad (\\text{which is less than } 190)\n     \\]\n   - \\(75\\) kg and \\(79\\) kg:\n     \\[\n     75 + 79 = 154 \\quad (\\text{which is less than } 190)\n     \\]\n\n5. **Count the Total Number of Rides**:\n   - Each of the five pairs accounts for one ride each.\n   - The individual weighing \\(150\\) kg accounts for one additional ride.\n\n   Therefore, the total number of rides required to transport all individuals is:\n   \\[\n   5 \\text{ (for pairs)} + 1 \\text{ (for the single heaviest individual)} = 6 \\text{ rides}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Considering Elevator Return Trips** (Optional):\n   If the problem involves counting return trips as well, where the elevator comes back down empty to fetch the next set of people, we account for those extra trips:\n   - \\(5 \\text{ trips for pairs} \\times 2 \\text{ (round trip)} = 10\\) rides (up and down)\n   - \\(1 \\text{ trip for the single rider} \\times 2 = 2\\) rides (up and down)\n\n   Sum of all rides then would be:\n   \\[\n   10 + 2 = 12 \\text{ rides in total} (if round trips are counted)\n   \\]\n   However, since it is an optional consideration, the necessary answer based purely on up trips is:\n\n**Conclusion**:\n\\[\n\\boxed{6}\n\\]"}
