{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_824129", "question": "Implement a Golang function that accepts a string as input and returns its reverse without using any built-in functions or libraries.", "answer": "Here's a simple Golang function that reverses a given string without using any built-in functions or libraries:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n)\n\nfunc reverseString(s string) string {\n\trunes := []rune(s)\n\tlength := len(runes)\n\tfor i := 0; i < length/2; i++ {\n\t\trunes[i], runes[length-1-i] = runes[length-1-i], runes[i]\n\t}\n\treturn string(runes)\n}\n\nfunc main() {\n\tinput := \"Hello, World!\"\n\treversed := reverseString(input)\n\tfmt.Println(\"Original:\", input)\n\tfmt.Println(\"Reversed:\", reversed)\n}\n```\n\nThis code defines a `reverseString` function that takes a string as input and returns its reverse. The function first converts the input string to an array of runes (to handle multi-byte characters properly). Then, it iterates through half of the rune array, swapping elements at positions `i` and `length-1-i`. Finally, it converts the modified rune array back to a string and returns it.\n\nIn the `main` function, we call `reverseString` with a sample input and print both the original and reversed strings."}
