{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_54186", "question": "I am using connection pooling in my application. Is it explicitly required to close the statement before closing the connection in a connection pooled environment? I have checked the jdbc 4.0 functional specs and it states that all statement objects created from a given connection object will be closed when the close method for the object is called. However, I'm not sure if this applies to connection pooled environments as well. Can someone clarify if I need to close the statements in a connection pooled environment?", "answer": "In a connection pooled environment, the connection is not actually closed but rather returned to the free connection pool. The jdbc specs mandate closing all statements at the time of closing the connection, but it is unclear if this applies to connection pooled environments as well. However, it is generally recommended to close the statements before closing the connection to ensure proper resource management. The reason for this is that objects with a close() method, such as the connection object, typically require invoking this method to release the object's resources when it is no longer in use. In the case of a pooled java.sql.Connection, the connection is pushed back into the pool as an available connection. While it is technically the responsibility of the connection pool to handle resource management, closing the statements before closing the connection can help ensure proper cleanup and avoid potential resource leaks. Therefore, it is good practice to close the statements before closing the connection, even in a connection pooled environment."}
