t legs, with only a dozen passengers on board, a far cry from the thirty or more who used to ride it when the Smith farm was still in operation.\n\nI made several changes to enhance the passage:\n\n- Simplified sentence structures to improve clarity and flow\n- Corrected grammatical errors (e.g., \"it had done\" to \"its daily route taking it,\" \"was swaying gently\" to \"swaying,\" \"hadnt\" to \"hadn't,\" \"no more\" to \"anymore\")\n- Changed some word choices to make the language more concise and engaging (e.g., \"chugging\" to \"rattled,\" \"many appeared abandoned\" to \"many abandoned or falling into disrepair\")\n- Emphasized the connection between the Smith farm's closure and the decline of the small farms and the bus route\n- Removed unnecessary words and phrases to make the passage more concise (e.g., \"for years now,\" \"so far out here\")\n\nOverall, these changes should help to make your passage more engaging, concise, and error-free, while preserving the essence of your narrative voice and setting."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_211371", "question": "In $\\triangle ABC$, the sum of $\\angle A$ and $\\angle B$ is $80^\\circ$. Additionally, there is an external angle at vertex C, which measures $100^\\circ$. What is the measure of $\\angle C$?", "answer": "1. From the triangle angle sum property, the sum of the three angles in any triangle is $180^\\circ$. Given, $\\angle A + \\angle B = 80^\\circ$.\n2. To find $\\angle C$: \n   \\[\n   \\angle C = 180^\\circ - 80^\\circ = 100^\\circ.\n   \\]\n3. The external angle at vertex C is the sum of the non-adjacent interior angles ($\\angle A + \\angle B$). Therefore, the external angle should also be $100^\\circ$, which matches the given problem statement.\n\nConclusion: The measure of $\\angle C$ in $\\triangle ABC$ is $\\boxed{100^\\circ}$."}
