{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_434130", "question": "I have been asked to explain why all the \"eigen\" words are called that - \"eigen\" is Dutch for \"own\" in english but how does that relate to eigenvalues and eigenvectors. Can you explain?", "answer": "The term \"eigen\" in the context of eigenvalues and eigenvectors originates from German, not Dutch. In German, \"eigen\" is an adjective that translates to \"own\" or \"inherent\" in English. The term was introduced by the German mathematician David Hilbert in the late 19th century.\n\nThe connection between the word \"eigen\" and eigenvalues and eigenvectors lies in the idea that these mathematical objects are, in a sense, inherent or characteristic to a particular linear transformation or matrix. An eigenvector of a matrix is a non-zero vector that, when transformed by the matrix, results in a scaled version of itself. In other words, the eigenvector is not changed in direction, only in magnitude, which is determined by the corresponding eigenvalue.\n\nThink of it as a vector that is \"owned\" by the transformation or matrix, in the sense that it is not altered in any fundamental way when the transformation is applied. The eigenvalue represents the amount of scaling or stretching that occurs when the eigenvector is transformed. This notion of an \"inherent\" or \"own\" vector that is preserved by a transformation is where the term \"eigen\" originates.\n\nThis concept is closely related to the idea of invariant subspaces in linear algebra. An invariant subspace of a linear transformation is a subspace that is mapped to itself by the transformation. Eigenvectors and eigenvalues can be seen as a way to decompose a linear transformation into its constituent parts, revealing the underlying structure of the transformation and the vectors that are \"owned\" by it."}
