{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_846234", "question": "Provide a Python function to extract columns by name in pandas dataframe and this function should be efficient enough to work with large dataframes. \n\n```python\n# Assume this is how the dataframe looks like\ndata = {\n    'Name': ['Tom', 'Nick', 'John', 'Tom', 'John'],\n    'Age': [20, 21, 19, 20, 18],\n    'Score': [90, 85, 88, 92, 89]\n}\ndf = pd.DataFrame(data)\n```", "answer": "Here is a Python function that efficiently extracts columns by name from a pandas DataFrame:\n\n```python\nimport pandas as pd\n\ndef extract_columns(df, column_names):\n    \"\"\"\n    Extract columns by name from a pandas DataFrame.\n\n    Args:\n        df (pd.DataFrame): The input DataFrame.\n        column_names (list): A list of column names to extract.\n\n    Returns:\n        pd.DataFrame: A new DataFrame containing the extracted columns.\n    \"\"\"\n    return df[column_names].copy()\n\n# Example usage\ndata = {\n    'Name': ['Tom', 'Nick', 'John', 'Tom', 'John'],\n    'Age': [20, 21, 19, 20, 18],\n    'Score': [90, 85, 88, 92, 89]\n}\ndf = pd.DataFrame(data)\n\nextracted_df = extract_columns(df, ['Name', 'Score'])\nprint(extracted_df)\n```\n\nThis function uses pandas' label-based indexing to efficiently extract the specified columns. The `.copy()` method is used to create a new DataFrame that is independent of the original DataFrame.\n\nThis approach is efficient because it:\n\n1. Avoids iterating over the DataFrame, which can be slow for large datasets.\n2. Uses optimized pandas operations, which are implemented in C and therefore faster than pure Python code.\n3. Creates a new DataFrame that is independent of the original, which prevents unintentional modifications to the original data.\n\nNote that this function assumes that all specified column names exist in the DataFrame. If a column name is missing, pandas will raise a `KeyError`. You may want to add error handling to handle such cases if necessary."}
