{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_165608", "question": "How do I convert markdown files to PDF and HTML?\nA markdown file is text file ending in \".md\" that uses a simple syntax formatting.", "answer": "You can convert markdown files to PDF and HTML using various tools and libraries. Here are a few approaches:\n\n**Using Command-Line Tools:**\n\n1. **Pandoc**: A popular and versatile tool for converting between various document formats, including markdown, HTML, and PDF. You can install pandoc using your system's package manager.\n\n   To convert markdown to HTML:\n   ```bash\npandoc -f markdown -t html -o output.html input.md\n```\n   To convert markdown to PDF:\n   ```bash\npandoc -f markdown -t pdf -o output.pdf input.md\n```\n\n2. **Markdown2pdf**: A command-line tool specifically designed for converting markdown to PDF.\n   ```bash\nmarkdown2pdf input.md -o output.pdf\n```\n\n**Using Programming Libraries:**\n\n1. **Python**:\n   - You can use the `markdown` library to convert markdown to HTML:\n     ```python\nimport markdown\nwith open('input.md', 'r') as f:\n    md = f.read()\nhtml = markdown.markdown(md)\nwith open('output.html', 'w') as f:\n    f.write(html)\n```\n   - To convert markdown to PDF, you can use the `pdfkit` library:\n     ```python\nimport markdown\nimport pdfkit\nwith open('input.md', 'r') as f:\n    md = f.read()\nhtml = markdown.markdown(md)\npdfkit.from_string(html, 'output.pdf')\n```\n\n2. **JavaScript**:\n   - You can use the `marked` library to convert markdown to HTML:\n     ```javascript\nconst marked = require('marked');\nconst fs = require('fs');\nconst html = marked(fs.readFileSync('input.md', 'utf8'));\nfs.writeFileSync('output.html', html);\n```\n   - To convert markdown to PDF, you can use the `pdfMake` library:\n     ```javascript\nconst marked = require('marked');\nconst pdfMake = require('pdfmake/build/pdfmake');\nconst fs = require('fs');\nconst html = marked(fs.readFileSync('input.md', 'utf8'));\nconst docDefinition = {\n  content: html\n};\nconst pdfDoc = pdfMake.createPdf(docDefinition);\npdfDoc.write('output.pdf', (err) => {\n  if (err) console.error(err);\n});\n```\n\nNote: These examples are just a starting point, and you may need to customize them to suit your specific requirements."}
