{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_596623", "question": "Write code to sort a stack using another stack\n**Language: Java**", "answer": "Here's a Java implementation that sorts a stack in ascending order using another stack.\n\n```java\nimport java.util.Stack;\n\npublic class StackSorter {\n    public static Stack<Integer> sortStack(Stack<Integer> stack) {\n        Stack<Integer> tempStack = new Stack<>();\n\n        while (!stack.isEmpty()) {\n            int temp = stack.pop();\n\n            // Move elements from tempStack to stack if they are greater than temp\n            while (!tempStack.isEmpty() && tempStack.peek() > temp) {\n                stack.push(tempStack.pop());\n            }\n\n            // Push temp to tempStack\n            tempStack.push(temp);\n        }\n\n        return tempStack;\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();\n        stack.push(5);\n        stack.push(3);\n        stack.push(8);\n        stack.push(1);\n        stack.push(2);\n\n        Stack<Integer> sortedStack = sortStack(stack);\n\n        System.out.println(\"Sorted stack: \");\n        while (!sortedStack.isEmpty()) {\n            System.out.println(sortedStack.pop());\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis code works by maintaining a temporary stack (`tempStack`) that is always sorted in ascending order. Elements from the original stack are popped and pushed onto `tempStack` in such a way that `tempStack` remains sorted. If the top element of `tempStack` is greater than the popped element, elements are moved from `tempStack` to the original stack until a smaller or equal element is found or `tempStack` becomes empty. The popped element is then pushed onto `tempStack`, maintaining the sorted order. This process continues until the original stack is empty. The resulting `tempStack` contains the elements in sorted order."}
