{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_769226", "question": "I am planning a two-week road trip to the American West this summer. I will have a rental car to drive. I will start and end the trip in Las Vegas, Nevada. I want to visit Yellowstone, Yosemite, the Grand Canyon, and Mount Rushmore. I am open to visiting any other sites along the way that will not throw the trip off schedule.", "answer": "That sounds like an exciting trip. Given the locations you've listed and the two-week timeframe, I'd recommend dividing the trip into manageable segments to minimize long drives and allow for exploration time at each site. \n\nYou can start by driving from Las Vegas to the Grand Canyon, which is about a 2.5-hour drive. Spend a day or two exploring the South Rim, taking in the breathtaking views, and hiking some of the many trails. From there, head north to Yellowstone National Park, which is about a 14-hour drive. To break this up, consider stopping in Salt Lake City, Utah, or Jackson, Wyoming, for the night. \n\nOnce you arrive at Yellowstone, plan to spend at least three days exploring the park's geysers, hot springs, and wildlife. After Yellowstone, head to Mount Rushmore, which is about a 5.5-hour drive. Take a day to visit the monument and explore the surrounding Black Hills.\n\nThe drive from Mount Rushmore to Yosemite is quite long (around 16 hours), so I recommend breaking it up with a stop in Reno, Nevada, or Lake Tahoe. Spend the last two days of your trip exploring Yosemite's stunning valleys, waterfalls, and hiking trails. Finally, drive back to Las Vegas, which is about a 6-hour drive from Yosemite.\n\nSome additional sites you might consider visiting along the way include Monument Valley, the Badlands, or the scenic Beartooth Highway. However, keep in mind that adding too many stops may make the trip feel rushed, so prioritize your interests and focus on the main destinations.\n\nTo stay on schedule, plan to drive around 4-6 hours per day and allocate the rest of the