{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_465012", "question": "I'm writing a small program to convert between temperatures in Celsius and Fahrenheit. How can I implement that in Python? \n\nHere's what I have so far:\n```\ndef convert_celsius_to_fahrenheit(celsius):\n    fahrenheit = celsius * 9 / 5 + 32\n    return fahrenheit\n\ndef convert_fahrenheit_to_celsius(fahrenheit):\n    celsius = (fahrenheit - 32) * 5 / 9\n    return celsius\n\n# Example usage\ncelsius = 30\nfahrenheit = convert_celsius_to_fahrenheit(celsius)\nprint(f\"{celsius} degrees Celsius is equal to {fahrenheit} degrees Fahrenheit\")\n\nfahrenheit = 86\ncelsius = convert_fahrenheit_to_celsius(fahrenheit)\nprint(f\"{fahrenheit} degrees Fahrenheit is equal to {celsius} degrees Celsius\")\n```\n\nI'd like to run it from the command line and pass the temperature value and unit as arguments. How do I modify the existing code to accomplish this?", "answer": "You can use Python's built-in `argparse` module to parse command line arguments. Here's how you can modify your existing code:\n\n```python\nimport argparse\n\ndef convert_celsius_to_fahrenheit(celsius):\n    fahrenheit = celsius * 9 / 5 + 32\n    return fahrenheit\n\ndef convert_fahrenheit_to_celsius(fahrenheit):\n    celsius = (fahrenheit - 32) * 5 / 9\n    return celsius\n\ndef main():\n    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser(description=\"Temperature conversion tool\")\n    parser.add_argument(\"-t\", \"--temperature\", type=float, required=True, help=\"Temperature value\")\n    parser.add_argument(\"-u\", \"--unit\", choices=[\"celsius\", \"fahrenheit\"], required=True, help=\"Temperature unit\")\n    args = parser.parse_args()\n\n    if args.unit == \"celsius\":\n        fahrenheit = convert_celsius_to_fahrenheit(args.temperature)\n        print(f\"{args.temperature} degrees Celsius is equal to {fahrenheit} degrees Fahrenheit\")\n    elif args.unit == \"fahrenheit\":\n        celsius = convert_fahrenheit_to_celsius(args.temperature)\n        print(f\"{args.temperature} degrees Fahrenheit is equal to {celsius} degrees Celsius\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    main()\n```\n\nYou can run this script from the command line like this:\n\n```bash\npython temperature_converter.py -t 30 -u celsius\npython temperature_converter.py -t 86 -u fahrenheit\n```\n\nThis will output the equivalent temperature in the other unit. If you need help with the command line arguments, you can run `python temperature_converter.py -h` to see the usage message."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_878056", "question": "Given $\\tan \\theta= \\frac{1}{2}$, find the value of $\\cos 2\\theta$.", "answer": "Since $\\tan \\theta= \\frac{1}{2}$, we can use the double angle identity for cosine to find $\\cos 2\\theta$.\n\nThe double angle identity for cosine is $\\cos 2\\theta = \\cos^2 \\theta - \\sin^2 \\theta$. We can express this in terms of tangent using the Pythagorean identity, $\\cos^2 \\theta = \\frac{1}{1 + \\tan^2 \\theta}$ and $\\sin^2 \\theta = \\frac{\\tan^2 \\theta}{1 + \\tan^2 \\theta}$.\n\nSubstituting these into the double angle identity, we get:\n\n$$\\cos 2\\theta = \\frac{1}{1 + \\tan^2 \\theta} - \\frac{\\tan^2 \\theta}{1 + \\tan^2 \\theta}$$\n\nSubstituting $\\tan \\theta = \\frac{1}{2}$ into the equation, we get:\n\n$$\\cos 2\\theta = \\frac{1}{1 + \\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^2} - \\frac{\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^2}{1 + \\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)^2}$$\n\nSimplifying this expression gives:\n\n$$\\cos 2\\theta = \\frac{1}{\\frac{5}{4}} - \\frac{\\frac{1}{4}}{\\frac{5}{4}} = \\frac{4}{5} - \\frac{1}{5} = \\boxed{\\frac{3}{5}}$$"}
