{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_218918", "question": "Define the operation $*$ for non-zero integers as $a * b = \\frac{1}{a} + \\frac{1}{b}$. If $a - b = 9$ and $a \\div b = 20$, find the value of $a * b$ expressed as a common fraction.", "answer": "Given that $a * b = \\frac{1}{a} + \\frac{1}{b}$ and $a - b = 9$ and $a \\div b = 20$, first solve for $a$ and $b$.\n\n1. From $a \\div b = 20$, we can write this as $a = 20b$.\n2. Substitute into the second equation: $20b - b = 9$,\n   \\[\n   19b = 9 \\implies b = \\frac{9}{19}, a = 20b = 20 \\times \\frac{9}{19} = \\frac{180}{19}.\n   \\]\n3. Now, substitute $a = \\frac{180}{19}$ and $b = \\frac{9}{19}$ into the $*$ operation:\n   \\[\n   a * b = \\frac{1}{a} + \\frac{1}{b} = \\frac{1}{\\frac{180}{19}} + \\frac{1}{\\frac{9}{19}} = \\frac{19}{180} + \\frac{19}{9}.\n   \\]\n   Simplify further:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{19}{180} + \\frac{38}{180} = \\frac{57}{180} = \\frac{19}{60}.\n   \\]\n\nThus, $a * b = \\boxed{\\frac{19}{60}}$."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_1032862", "question": "Consider a finite sequence of positive integers 1, x1, x2, ..., xn, where n is a positive integer. We define two types of operations: \n\n- Type 1: Replace any two consecutive terms of the sequence by a single term that is the sum of the two terms.\n- Type 2: Insert any positive integer between any two consecutive terms.\n\nGiven that the original sequence can be reduced to a sequence of length 2 using only operations of Type 1, it is claimed that the order of the sequence does not matter. \n\nIs the claim true or false? Explain your reasoning.\n\nThen consider one of the possible re-orderings of the sequence and show an example of the process in use (start with some initial sequence e.g. 1, 4, 5, 3, 7, and apply the rules).", "answer": "The claim is true. To see why, let's consider the sum of all terms in the original sequence. This sum is preserved under both types of operations. When we apply Type 1 operation, we replace two terms by their sum, which does not change the overall sum of the sequence. Similarly, when we apply Type 2 operation, we insert a new term, but this does not affect the sum of the terms that were already present in the sequence.\n\nNow, suppose we can reduce the original sequence to a sequence of length 2 using only Type 1 operations. This means that the sum of all terms in the original sequence can be expressed as the sum of two terms. Let's denote these two terms as A and B.\n\nIf the original sequence can be reduced to A and B, then any re-ordering of the sequence can also be reduced to A and B. This is because the sum of the terms in the original sequence is preserved under re-ordering, and we can apply the same sequence of Type 1 operations to reduce the re-ordered sequence to A and B.\n\nFor example, consider the initial sequence 1, 4, 5, 3, 7. One possible re-ordering of this sequence is 7, 5, 3, 4, 1. We can reduce the original sequence to a sequence of length 2 using Type 1 operations as follows:\n\n1, 4, 5, 3, 7 -> 5, 5, 3, 7 (by replacing 1 and 4 with their sum 5)\n5, 5, 3, 7 -> 10, 3, 7 (by replacing the two 5s with their sum 10)\n10, 3, 7 -> 13, 7 (by replacing 10 and 3 with their sum 13)\n13, 7 -> 20 (by replacing 13 and 7 with their sum 20)\n\nHowever, we are asked to reduce the sequence to a length of 2, so we stop one step earlier:\n\n1, 4, 5, 3, 7 -> 5, 5, 3, 7\n5, 5, 3, 7 -> 10, 3, 7\n10, 3, 7 -> 13, 7\n\nNow, let's apply the same sequence of Type 1 operations to the re-ordered sequence 7, 5, 3, 4, 1:\n\n7, 5, 3, 4, 1 -> 7, 5, 7, 1 (by replacing 3 and 4 with their sum 7)\n7, 5, 7, 1 -> 12, 7, 1 (by replacing 7 and 5 with their sum 12)\n12, 7, 1 -> 19, 1 (by replacing 12 and 7 with their sum 19)\n19, 1 -> 20 (by replacing 19 and 1 with their sum 20)\n\nAgain, we stop one step earlier to get a sequence of length 2:\n\n7, 5, 3, 4, 1 -> 7, 5, 7, 1\n7, 5, 7, 1 -> 12, 7, 1\n12, 7, 1 -> 19, 1\n\nAs we can see, both sequences can be reduced to a sequence of length 2 with the same sum (20), which confirms our initial claim."}
