{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_460302", "question": "I want to write a Python function that parses function definitions into their components. The function should accept a string that represents the function definition and return a dictionary containing the following information:\n- function name\n- parameters (including default values if present)\n- return type (if present)\n- docstring (if present)\n\nThe function should handle edge cases such as:\n- default parameter values\n- return type declarations\n- docstrings\n- nested function definitions", "answer": "You can approach this problem by splitting the function definition into its components using regular expressions. For example, you can use a regular expression to match the function name, parameters, default values, return type, and docstring.\n\nHere's a possible implementation in Python:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\ndef parse_function_definition(func_def):\n    name_regex = r'(?<=def\\s)[\\w_]+'\n    params_regex = r'\\((.*?)\\)'\n    return_type_regex = r'->\\s*([\\w\\[\\]\\(\\)]+)'\n    docstring_regex = r'\"\"\"(.*?)\"\"\"'\n    name = re.search(name_regex, func_def).group(0)\n    params = re.search(params_regex, func_def).group(0)\n    return_type = re.search(return_type_regex, func_def)\n    docstring = re.search(docstring_regex, func_def)\n    if return_type is not None:\n        return_type = return_type.group(1)\n    if docstring is not None:\n        docstring = docstring.group(1)\n    return {\n        'name': name,\n        'parameters': params,\n        'return_type': return_type,\n        'docstring': docstring\n    }\n```"}
