{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_607225", "question": "Consider the set of all natural numbers N = {1,2,3...}. What are some of the properties of this set?", "answer": "The set of all natural numbers N = {1,2,3...} is a fundamental object of study in mathematics. One of its most basic properties is that it is infinite, meaning it has no end and contains an unbounded number of elements. This infiniteness is often denoted by the symbol ∞, but it's essential to note that infinity is not a number in the classical sense, rather a property of certain sets.\n\nAnother crucial property of N is that it is well-ordered. This means that every non-empty subset of N has a least element. In simpler terms, given any subset of N, we can always find a smallest element in that subset. For example, the subset {4, 9, 12} has 4 as its least element, while the subset {11, 17, 22} has 11 as its least element.\n\nFurthermore, N is closed under addition and multiplication, which means that adding or multiplying any two elements of N always results in another element of N. For instance, 3 + 5 = 8 and 4 × 6 = 24 are both elements of N.\n\nThe set N also satisfies the Peano axioms, a set of fundamental axioms that define the properties of the natural numbers. These axioms include the existence of a successor function (which can be thought of as \"adding 1\" to a number), the fact that there is no natural number that comes before 1, and the principle of mathematical induction, which allows us to prove statements about all natural numbers.\n\nLastly, it's worth noting that the set N is countably infinite, which means that its elements can be put into a one-to-one correspondence with the integers. This property is often demonstrated using a simple counting argument, showing that we can pair up each natural number with a unique integer, and vice versa.\n\nThese properties make the set of natural numbers a rich and fascinating object of study, and form the foundation of many areas of mathematics, including number theory, algebra, and analysis."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_1041011", "question": "Given that $\\{a\\_n\\}$ is an arithmetic sequence, $\\{b\\_n\\}$ is a geometric sequence, $S\\_n$ is the sum of the first $n$ terms of the sequence $\\{a\\_n\\}$, $a\\_1=b\\_1=1$, and $b\\_3S\\_3=36$, $b\\_2S\\_2=8$.\n\n1. Find the general term formula for the sequences $\\{a\\_n\\}$ and $\\{b\\_n\\}$.\n2. If $a\\_n < a\\_{n+1}$, find the sum $T\\_n$ of the first $n$ terms of the sequence $\\{ \\frac {1}{a\\_n a\\_{n+1}} \\}$.", "answer": "1. Let $\\{a\\_n\\}$ be an arithmetic sequence with common difference $d$, and $\\{b\\_n\\}$ be a geometric sequence with common ratio $q$.\nFrom the given conditions, we have the system of equations:\n\n$$\\begin{cases} q^2(3+3d)=36 \\\\ q(2+d)=8 \\end{cases}$$\n\nSolving this system, we find two possible solutions:\n\n$$\\begin{cases} d=2 \\\\ q=2 \\end{cases} \\text{ or } \\begin{cases} d=-\\frac {2}{3} \\\\ q=6 \\end{cases}$$\n\nThus, the sequences are either:\n$$a\\_n = 2n-1, \\quad b\\_n = 2^{n-1}$$\nor\n$$a\\_n = \\frac{1}{3}(5-2n), \\quad b\\_n = 6^{n-1}$$\n\n2. If $a\\_n < a\\_{n+1}$, then from part 1, we have $a\\_n = 2n-1$. Therefore,\n\n$$\\frac {1}{a\\_n a\\_{n+1}} = \\frac {1}{(2n-1)(2n+1)} = \\frac {1}{2} \\left( \\frac {1}{2n-1} - \\frac {1}{2n+1} \\right)$$\n\nSumming both sides over $n$, we get\n\n$$T\\_n = \\frac{1}{2} \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{3} + \\frac{1}{3} - \\frac{1}{5} + \\ldots + \\frac{1}{2n-1} - \\frac{1}{2n+1}\\right) = \\frac{n}{2n+1}$$\n\nThus, the sum of the first $n$ terms of the sequence $\\{ \\frac {1}{a\\_n a\\_{n+1}} \\}$ is:\n\n$$\\boxed{T\\_n = \\frac{n}{2n+1}}$$"}
