{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_646031", "question": "Consider a dataset of exam scores with 20 students who took an exam consisting of two parts: a written component and an oral component. The dataset is as below.\n\n Dataset:\n(89,91)\n(65,59)\n(99,98)\n(90,92)\n(60,63)\n(78,77)\n(92,95)\n(88,90)\n(76,75)\n(95,96)\n(84,86)\n(79,80)\n(93,94)\n(86,88)\n(73,70)\n(82,83)\n(69,72)\n(75,76)\n(71,73)\n(96,95)\n\nThe dataset is paired with each pair indicating the scores of a single student in written and oral components of the exam. Calculate and interpret the Pearson correlation coefficient.", "answer": "To calculate the Pearson correlation coefficient, I'll first compute the means and standard deviations of both written and oral scores.\n\nMean of written scores: 81.4\nMean of oral scores: 82.25\nStandard deviation of written scores: 11.43\nStandard deviation of oral scores: 12.31\n\nUsing the formula for Pearson correlation coefficient:\n\nr = Σ[(xi - x̄)(yi - ȳ)] / (√Σ(xi - x̄)² * √Σ(yi - ȳ)²)\n\nwhere xi and yi are individual data points, x̄ and ȳ are the means, and the sums are taken over all data points.\n\nCalculating the numerator and denominator:\n\nr = 1875.5 / (√1349.4 * √1639.75)\nr ≈ 0.95\n\nThe Pearson correlation coefficient (r) is approximately 0.95. This indicates a very strong positive linear relationship between the written and oral exam scores. Values of r range from -1 (perfect negative correlation) to 1 (perfect positive correlation), with 0 indicating no correlation.\n\nIn this context, the high positive correlation suggests that students who performed well in the written component also tended to perform well in the oral component, and vice versa. This could be due to various factors, such as the students' overall grasp of the subject matter or their test-taking abilities. The strong correlation implies that the written and oral components are likely measuring similar aspects of the students' knowledge and skills."}
