{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_558871", "question": "a shipment of 220 smartphones contains 84 that are defective . if a customer buys two smartphones at random from the shipment , what is the approximate probability that both phones are defective ?", "answer": "To find the probability that both smartphones are defective, we can use the formula for the probability of independent events:\n\nP(A and B) = P(A) * P(B given A)\n\nFirst, we calculate the probability of selecting one defective smartphone (event A):\n\nP(A) = Number of defective smartphones / Total number of smartphones\nP(A) = 84 / 220\n\nNext, we calculate the probability of selecting another defective smartphone after the first one has been selected (event B given A). Since one defective smartphone has already been taken, there are now 83 defective smartphones left out of a total of 219 smartphones:\n\nP(B given A) = Number of remaining defective smartphones / Total remaining smartphones\nP(B given A) = 83 / 219\n\nNow we can calculate the probability of both events happening:\n\nP(A and B) = P(A) * P(B given A)\nP(A and B) = (84 / 220) * (83 / 219)\n\nLet's calculate the approximate probability:\n\nP(A and B) ≈ (0.3818) * (0.3789)\nP(A and B) ≈ 0.1447\n\nSo the approximate probability that both phones are defective is $\\boxed{0.1447}$  or 14.47%."}
