{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_1003175", "question": "Given $f(x)=x\\ln x-ax^{2}+(2a-1)x$, where $a\\in R$.\n\n(1) Let $g(x)=f'(x)$, find the monotonic intervals of $g(x)$;\n\n(2) Given that $f(x)$ reaches its maximum value at $x=1$, find the range of values for the real number $a$.", "answer": "(1) Since $f(x)=x\\ln x-ax^{2}+(2a-1)x$, $(x > 0)$,\n\nthen $g(x)=f'(x)=\\ln x-2ax+2a$,\n\nand $g'(x)= \\frac{1}{x}-2a= \\frac{1-2ax}{x}$,\n\nWhen $a\\leqslant 0$, $g'(x) > 0$ always holds, so the monotonically increasing interval of $g(x)$ is $(0,+\\infty)$,\n\nWhen $a > 0$, $g'(x) < 0$ when $x > \\frac{1}{2a}$, the function is decreasing,\n\nand $g'(x) > 0$ when $0 < x < \\frac{1}{2a}$, the function is increasing,\n\nTherefore, when $a\\leqslant 0$, the monotonically increasing interval of $g(x)$ is $(0,+\\infty)$,\n\nWhen $a > 0$, the monotonically increasing interval of $g(x)$ is $\\left(0, \\frac{1}{2a}\\right)$, and the monotonically decreasing interval is $\\left( \\frac{1}{2a},+\\infty\\right)$;\n\n(2) Since $f(x)$ reaches its maximum value at $x=1$,\n\nthen $f'(1)=0$,\n\n$\\boxed{(1)}$ When $a\\leqslant 0$, $f'(x)$ is monotonically increasing,\n\nthen $f'(x) < 0$ when $0 < x < 1$, $f(x)$ is monotonically decreasing,\n\nand $f'(x) > 0$ when $x > 1$, $f(x)$ is monotonically increasing,\n\nTherefore, $f(x)$ reaches its minimum value at $x=1$, which does not meet the requirement;\n\n$\\boxed{(2)}$ When $0 < a < \\frac{1}{2}$, $\\frac{1}{2a} > 1$, according to $(1)$, $f(x)$ is monotonically increasing within $\\left(0, \\frac{1}{2a}\\right)$,\n\nthen $f'(x) < 0$ when $0 < x < 1$, and $f'(x) > 0$ when $1 < x < \\frac{1}{2a}$,\n\nTherefore, $f(x)$ is monotonically decreasing within $(0,1)$, and monotonically increasing within $\\left(1, \\frac{1}{2a}\\right)$,\n\nThat is, $f(x)$ reaches its minimum value at $x=1$, which does not meet the requirement;\n\n$\\boxed{(3)}$ When $a= \\frac{1}{2}$, $\\frac{1}{2a}=1$, $f'(x)$ is monotonically increasing within $(0,1)$, and monotonically decreasing on $(1,+\\infty)$,\n\nthen $f'(x)\\leqslant 0$ when $x > 0$, $f(x)$ is monotonically decreasing, which does not meet the requirement;\n\n$\\boxed{(4)}$ When $a > \\frac{1}{2}$, $0 < \\frac{1}{2a} < 1$,\n\nthen $f'(x) > 0$ when $\\frac{1}{2a} < x < 1$, $f(x)$ is monotonically increasing,\n\nand $f'(x) < 0$ when $x > 1$, $f(x)$ is monotonically decreasing,\n\nTherefore, $f(x)$ reaches its maximum value when $x=1$, which meets the condition.\n\nIn conclusion, the range of values for the real number $a$ is $a > \\frac{1}{2}$."}
