aining the notes of my predecessors and the records of my own experiments. Some, I've already committed to memory; others, I've not looked at in years. Perhaps it's time to let them go? But which ones? The memories they hold are dear to me, reminders of trials and triumphs, of discoveries that shaped me into the wizard I am today.\n\nAs I work, the silence of the tower is broken only by the soft rustling of parchment and the creaking of wooden shelves. The task ahead of me is long, but I'm determined to see it through. For in the end, it's not just a matter of sorting through possessions – it's a reflection of a life well-lived, and the passing of knowledge from one era to the next."}
