{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_125051", "question": "Typing can be a slow process. Would it be faster for 10 people to type one 10 page document, or 1 person to type 10 different one page documents?", "answer": "To analyze this situation, let's consider the total workload involved in both scenarios. In the first scenario, 10 people are typing one 10-page document, and in the second scenario, 1 person is typing 10 different one-page documents. \n\nIn both scenarios, the total workload is equivalent to 10 pages of typing. The difference lies in how the workload is distributed among the typists. \n\nWhen 10 people type one 10-page document, they can divide the workload equally among themselves, with each person typing one page. Assuming each person types at the same speed, this approach would be significantly faster than having one person type the entire 10-page document.\n\nOn the other hand, if one person is typing 10 different one-page documents, they would still have to type a total of 10 pages, which is the same workload as typing a single 10-page document.\n\nTherefore, based on the information given, having 10 people type one 10-page document would be faster than having one person type 10 different one-page documents, as the workload is distributed more efficiently among multiple typists."}
