{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_634595", "question": "What are the different approaches to create a Ruby on Rails application with static pages such as Home, About, and Contact? I am looking for code examples or resources to understand how to build simple web apps with this functionality instead of just using a gem.", "answer": "There are multiple ways to handle the content for static pages in a Ruby on Rails application. \n\nApproach #1 - Store content in views:\nIf you want to store all the content in ERB views, you can follow a simple approach by creating a PagesController. This controller will have separate actions for each static page.\n\n```ruby\nclass PagesController < ApplicationController\n  def home\n  end\n\n  def about\n  end\n\n  def contact\n  end\nend\n```\n\nTo define the routes for these pages, you can add the following lines in your routes.rb file:\n\n```ruby\nget '/home', to: 'pages#home'\nget '/about', to: 'pages#about'\nget '/contact', to: 'pages#contact'\n```\n\nNext, you can create separate views for each page (home.html.erb, about.html.erb, and contact.html.erb) under the app/views/pages directory. These views can contain the desired content for each static page and will use the default application.html.erb layout by default.\n\nAdditionally, you may consider implementing page caching to improve the performance of your application. You can learn more about page caching in the Rails guides: [Page Caching](http://guides.rubyonrails.org/caching_with_rails.html#page-caching).\n\nApproach #2 - Store content in the database:\nAnother approach is to create a basic Content Management System (CMS) for static pages. In this approach, each page is represented as a model and the content is stored in the database. You can use the friendly_id gem to handle slugs for each page, allowing you to retrieve pages using pretty names in the URL (e.g., /about) instead of IDs.\n\nFirst, define a Page model:\n\n```ruby\nclass Page < ActiveRecord::Base\n  attr_accessible :title, :content\n\n  validates_presence_of :title, :content\n\n  has_friendly_id :title, use_slug: true, approximate_ascii: true\nend\n```\n\nNext, create a PagesController with a show action to display the content of a specific page:\n\n```ruby\nclass PagesController < ApplicationController\n  def show\n    @page = Page.find(params[:id])\n    render 'shared/404', status: 404 if @page.nil?\n  end\nend\n```\n\nCreate a show.html.erb view to render the content of the page:\n\n```erb\n<%= raw @page.content %>\n```\n\nTo define the route for the pages, add the following line to your routes.rb file (place it at the end since it matches everything):\n\n```ruby\nget '/:id', to: 'pages#show'\n```\n\nWith this approach, you can create, edit, and update pages as needed. You can choose to create an admin interface or integrate the page management into your public interface. This approach can also benefit from page caching for improved performance.\n\nI hope these examples help you in creating your Ruby on Rails application with static pages. Let me know if you have any further questions!"}
