{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_738862", "question": "Consider a normal distribution of scores with a mean of 80 and standard deviation of 10. What is the z-score of a test score of 95? And what percentage of students would be expected to have scored at or above that score?", "answer": "To find the z-score of a test score of 95, we use the z-score formula: \n\nz = (X - μ) / σ, \n\nwhere X is the test score, μ is the mean, and σ is the standard deviation. \n\nPlugging in the values, we get:\n\nz = (95 - 80) / 10 \nz = 15 / 10 \nz = 1.5\n\nThis means that the test score of 95 is 1.5 standard deviations above the mean.\n\nTo find the percentage of students who scored at or above 95, we can use a standard normal distribution table (z-table) to find the area to the right of a z-score of 1.5. The area to the right of z = 1.5 is approximately 0.0668, or 6.68%. \n\nTherefore, about 6.68% of students would be expected to have scored at or above 95."}
