{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_439750", "question": "Prove there is no rational number r that satisfies r^2 = 2 using proof of contradiction.", "answer": "To prove that there is no rational number r that satisfies r^2 = 2, we will use a proof by contradiction. Assume, on the contrary, that there is a rational number r such that r^2 = 2. Since r is rational, it can be expressed as a fraction, r = p/q, where p and q are integers with no common factors other than 1.\n\nSquaring both sides of the equation r = p/q gives r^2 = (p/q)^2 = p^2/q^2. Since r^2 = 2, we have p^2/q^2 = 2. Multiplying both sides by q^2, we obtain p^2 = 2q^2.\n\nNow, p^2 is an even integer since it is equal to 2q^2. This implies that p itself must be even, because the square of an odd number is always odd. Let p = 2m for some integer m. Then, p^2 = 4m^2 = 2q^2. Dividing both sides by 2, we get 2m^2 = q^2.\n\nSince 2m^2 is an even integer, q^2 must also be even, which means q must be even. However, this contradicts our initial assumption that p and q have no common factors other than 1. If both p and q are even, then they have 2 as a common factor, which is not allowed. This contradiction implies that our initial assumption - that there is a rational number r satisfying r^2 = 2 - must be false. Therefore, there is no rational number r that satisfies r^2 = 2."}
