{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_512625", "question": "A bag contains 800 balls. Initially, 70% of the balls are red, and the rest are blue. How many red balls must be removed so that 60% of the remaining balls are red?\nA) 150\nB) 200\nC) 250\nD) 300\nE) 350", "answer": "1. **Determine the initial number of red and blue balls:**\n   Given that 70% of the 800 balls are red, we calculate the number of red balls as:\n   \\[\n   0.7 \\times 800 = 560 \\text{ red balls}\n   \\]\n   The remaining balls are blue, so:\n   \\[\n   800 - 560 = 240 \\text{ blue balls}\n   \\]\n\n2. **Set up the equation for the desired condition:**\n   We need to find the number of red balls \\( x \\) to remove so that 60% of the remaining balls are red. The new number of red balls is \\( 560 - x \\), and the total number of remaining balls is \\( 800 - x \\). The proportion of red balls should then be \\( 60\\% \\) or \\( \\frac{3}{5} \\). We set up the equation:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{560 - x}{800 - x} = \\frac{3}{5}\n   \\]\n\n3. **Solve the equation:**\n   Cross-multiply to eliminate the fraction:\n   \\[\n   5(560 - x) = 3(800 - x)\n   \\]\n   Simplify and solve for \\( x \\):\n   \\[\n   2800 - 5x = 2400 - 3x\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   2800 - 2400 = 5x - 3x\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   400 = 2x\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   x = 200\n   \\]\n   \n4. **Conclusion:**\n   Therefore, \\( 200 \\) red balls must be removed so that \\( 60\\% \\) of the remaining balls are red. The correct answer is boxed: $200$.\nThe final answer is $\\boxed{B) 200}$"}
