{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_1014832", "question": "How can I create a subplot for all variables using Seaborn boxplot? I have a dataframe and while I can create a single boxplot, I am having trouble creating a subplot for all variables. I tried using a for loop but it did not produce the desired output. Here's the code I used:\n\n```python\nimport seaborn as sns\nimport pandas as pd\n%pylab inline\n\ndf = pd.DataFrame({'a' :['one','one','two','two','one','two','one','one','one','two'], \n                   'b': [1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,1], \n                   'c': [1,2,3,4,6,1,2,3,4,6]})\n\nsns.boxplot(y=\"b\", x=\"a\", data=df, orient='v')\n\nnames = ['b', 'c']\nplt.subplots(1,2)\nsub = []\nfor name in names:\n    ax = sns.boxplot(y=name, x=\"a\", data=df, orient='v')\n    sub.append(ax)\n```\n\nThis outputs two boxplots overlapped on each other, instead of two separate subplots.", "answer": "The issue is that you are creating the subplots but not assigning each boxplot to a subplot. You need to create the subplot axes first and then associate each box plot with one of these axes. The following code does this:\n\n```python\nimport seaborn as sns\nimport pandas as pd\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\ndf = pd.DataFrame({'a' :['one','one','two','two','one','two','one','one','one','two'], \n                   'b': [1,2,1,2,1,2,1,2,1,1], \n                   'c': [1,2,3,4,6,1,2,3,4,6]})\n\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)\nnames = ['b', 'c']\n\nfor ax, name in zip(axes, names):\n    sns.boxplot(y=name, x=\"a\", data=df, orient='v', ax=ax)\n    \nplt.show()\n```\n\nIn this corrected code, we first create a figure and axes using the `plt.subplots()` function. This returns a figure and an array of Axes objects. Then we iterate over the axes and the names simultaneously using the `zip()` function. Inside the loop, we create a boxplot on the current axis (`ax`) for the current variable (`name`). This results in two separate boxplots each in its own subplot as desired."}
