{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_179807", "question": "Cutting equilateral triangle $BFC$ out of square $ABCD$ and translating it to the left of the square creates the shaded figure $ABFCDE$. The perimeter of square $ABCD$ was 48 inches. What is the perimeter, in inches, of $ABFCDE$?\n\n[asy]\nfilldraw((0,0)--(sqrt(3),1)--(sqrt(3)+2,1)--(2,0)--(sqrt(3)+2,-1)--(sqrt(3),-1)--(0,0)--cycle,gray,linewidth(1));\ndraw((sqrt(3),1)--(sqrt(3),-1),linewidth(1));\ndraw((sqrt(3)+2,-1)--(sqrt(3)+2,1)--(2,0)--(sqrt(3)+2,-1)--cycle,dashed);\n\nlabel(\"A\",(sqrt(3),1),N);\nlabel(\"B\",(sqrt(3)+2,1),N);\nlabel(\"C\",(sqrt(3)+2,-1),S);\nlabel(\"D\",(sqrt(3),-1),S);\nlabel(\"E\",(0,0),W);\nlabel(\"F\",(2,0),N);\n[/asy]", "answer": "Since $ABCD$ is a square, each side has length $48/4 = 12$ inches.\nThe perimeter of $ABFCDE$ consists of the sides $AB$, $BC$, $CF$, $FD$, $DE$, and $EA$.\nThe side $AB$ has length $12$ inches.\nThe side $BC$ is part of the original square and also has length $12$ inches.\nThe side $CF$ is the same length as side $BC$, so it is $12$ inches.\nThe side $FD$ is the same length as side $AB$, so it is $12$ inches.\nThe side $DE$ is part of the original square and also has length $12$ inches.\nThe side $EA$ is part of the original square and also has length $12$ inches.\nAdding up the lengths of all the sides, the perimeter of $ABFCDE$ is $12+12+12+12+12+12 = \\boxed{72}$ inches.\nThe answer is: 72"}
