{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_937800", "question": "Let x1, x2, x3, x4 be positive real numbers such that x1x2x3x4 = 1.  Prove that x1 + x2 + x3 + x4  ≥  4.", "answer": "This is a classic problem, often solved using the Arithmetic Mean-Geometric Mean (AM-GM) inequality. This inequality states that for any non-negative real numbers a1, a2, ..., an, the following holds: \n\n(a1 + a2 + ... + an) / n ≥ (a1 * a2 * ... * an)^(1/n).\n\nIn our case, we have four positive real numbers x1, x2, x3, and x4, with x1x2x3x4 = 1. We want to prove that x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 ≥ 4. Applying the AM-GM inequality directly to these numbers, we have:\n\n(x1 + x2 + x3 + x4) / 4 ≥ (x1 * x2 * x3 * x4)^(1/4) = 1^(1/4) = 1.\n\nMultiplying both sides by 4, we get x1 + x2 + x3 + x4 ≥ 4, as desired.\n\nThis solution showcases the power of the AM-GM inequality in establishing lower bounds on sums of variables given a constraint on their product. The inequality itself is a fundamental tool in mathematics, especially in optimization problems and inequalities involving symmetric functions of variables. In this case, it provides a straightforward and elegant way to prove the given statement."}
