{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_676367", "question": "Assuming we implement a new calendrical system where leap years happen every four years, but also every fifth year is designated as a leap year. In a 105-year period, how many leap years would there be at most?", "answer": "- **Top Calculation**: Determine leap years accruing every four years. $105 \\div 4 = 26.25$, thus there are 26 full four-year cycles in 105 years.\n- **Fifth Year Leap Calculation**: Determine additional leap years that occur every five years. $105 \\div 5 = 21$. There are 21 full five-year cycles within 105 years.\n- **Handling Overlap**: The overlapped years create duplicate counts. A year is shared between the 4-year and 5-year cycle if it is a multiple of the least common multiple (LCM) of 4 and 5, which is 20. Therefore, $105 \\div 20 = 5.25$. Thus, there are 5 leap years which have been double counted.\n- **Net Leap Years**: Calculate total unique leap years in 105 years which is $26 + 21 - 5 = 42$.\n\nTherefore, in a 105-year period, the maximum number of leap years, ensuring no repetition and considering both every four and every five years as leap years under the new rule, is $\\boxed{42}$."}
