{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_282243", "question": "Consider the Sierpinski pyramid shown below:\n```\n          /\\          \n         /__\\         \n        /\\  /\\        \n       /__\\/__\\       \n      /\\      /\\      \n     /__\\    /__\\     \n    /\\  /\\  /\\  /\\    \n   /__\\/__\\/__\\/__\\   \n  /\\              /\\  \n /__\\            /__\\ \n/\\  /\\          /\\  /\\\n```\nSuppose the base of the pyramid has side length 8. What is the volume of the pyramid? (Assume the height of the pyramid is also 8.)", "answer": "To find the volume of the pyramid, we can use the formula for the volume of a tetrahedron, which is V = (1/3) * base_area * height. In this case, the base is an equilateral triangle with side length 8, and the height is also 8.\n\nFirst, we need to find the area of the equilateral triangle base. The formula for the area of an equilateral triangle is A = (s^2 * √3) / 4, where s is the side length. \n\nA = (8^2 * √3) / 4\nA = (64 * √3) / 4\nA = 16√3\n\nNow we can find the volume of the pyramid:\n\nV = (1/3) * base_area * height\nV = (1/3) * 16√3 * 8\nV = (1/3) * 128√3\nV ≈ 74.330343736592\n\nSo, the volume of the pyramid is approximately 74.33 cubic units."}
