{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_370512", "question": "Create a function in Python that takes a list of integers and a target integer. This function should return a list of the indices of the numbers in the list that add up to the target. If no such pair exists, return an empty list.\n\nExample:\ninput: [2, 7, 11, 15], target = 9\noutput: [0, 1]", "answer": "Here is a Python function that uses a dictionary to store the indices of the numbers we've seen so far and their complements.\n\n```python\ndef two_sum(nums, target):\n    seen = {}\n    for i, num in enumerate(nums):\n        complement = target - num\n        if complement in seen:\n            return [seen[complement], i]\n        seen[num] = i\n    return []\n```\n\nYou can use this function with your example input like this:\n\n```python\nprint(two_sum([2, 7, 11, 15], 9))  # Output: [0, 1]\n```\n\nThis function works by iterating over the list of numbers. For each number, it checks if its complement (the number that needs to be added to it to reach the target) is in the dictionary. If it is, it returns the indices of the complement and the current number. If it's not, it adds the current number and its index to the dictionary. If it iterates over the entire list without finding a pair of numbers that add up to the target, it returns an empty list. This function runs in O(n) time, where n is the length of the list of numbers."}
