{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_989915", "question": "I am analyzing a dataset that contains information about the average cost of a hotel room per night in various cities around the world. I have calculated the mean cost to be $120 per night. However, as I look through the data, I notice that there is one observation that significantly stands out from the rest: a luxury hotel in a major city that costs $1,500 per night. How should I handle this outlier, and what impact will it have on my analysis?", "answer": "The presence of this luxury hotel observation is likely skewing your mean cost calculation, making it less representative of the typical hotel room cost. In this case, the mean is sensitive to extreme values, also known as outliers. \n\nTo address this issue, you have several options:\n\nYou can remove the outlier from your dataset before recalculating the mean, but this approach is not recommended unless you're certain that the data point is an error. Removing a legitimate data point can introduce bias and affect the accuracy of your analysis.\n\nAnother approach is to use a more robust measure of central tendency, such as the median. The median is less sensitive to outliers and provides a better representation of the middle value in your dataset.\n\nAlternatively, you can consider using a trimmed mean, where you remove a certain percentage (e.g., 1% or 5%) of the most extreme values from both the upper and lower ends of the distribution before calculating the mean.\n\nIt's also worth noting that the presence of this luxury hotel might be an interesting aspect of your dataset, providing insight into the high-end market. Consider analyzing the data with and without the outlier to understand its impact on your overall findings.\n\nTo further understand the distribution of hotel costs, consider visualizing your data using a histogram or a box plot. This will help you identify any other potential outliers and get a sense of the spread of hotel costs across cities.