{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_263344", "question": "Suppose for some numbers \\( p, q, r \\) we have \\( p+q+r = 4 \\), \\( pq+pr+qr = 3 \\), and \\( pqr = -6 \\). What is \\( p^3+q^3+r^3 \\)?", "answer": "Given the equations \\( p+q+r = 4 \\), \\( pq+pr+qr = 3 \\), and \\( pqr = -6 \\), we can form the polynomial whose roots are \\( p, q, \\) and \\( r \\):\n\\[\nx^3 - (p+q+r)x^2 + (pq+pr+qr)x - pqr = x^3 - 4x^2 + 3x + 6\n\\]\nTo find the roots of this polynomial, we solve:\n\\[\nx^3 - 4x^2 + 3x + 6 = 0\n\\]\nBy rational root theorem or other factoring techniques, find that the roots of this equation are \\( x = -1, 2, 3 \\). These represent \\( p, q, \\) and \\( r \\).\n\nThen we can compute:\n\\[\np^3 + q^3 + r^3 = (-1)^3 + 2^3 + 3^3 = -1 + 8 + 27 = 34\n\\]\n\nConclusion:\nTherefore, \\( p^3 + q^3 + r^3 = \\boxed{34} \\)."}
