{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_769501", "question": "an amount at compound interest sums to rs . 17640 / - in 2 years and to rs . 22932 / - in 3 years at the same rate of interest . find the rate percentage ?", "answer": "To find the rate of interest, we can use the formula for compound interest:\n\nA = P(1 + r/n)^(nt)\n\nWhere:\nA = the amount of money accumulated after n years, including interest.\nP = the principal amount (the initial amount of money).\nr = the annual interest rate (in decimal).\nn = the number of times that interest is compounded per year.\nt = the time the money is invested for, in years.\n\nIn this case, we are given two amounts (A) for two different times (t), but we are not given the number of times the interest is compounded per year (n). We will assume that the interest is compounded annually (n = 1) for simplicity.\n\nLet's denote the principal amount by P and the annual interest rate by r.\n\nFor the first scenario (after 2 years):\nA1 = P(1 + r)^2 = 17640\n\nFor the second scenario (after 3 years):\nA2 = P(1 + r)^3 = 22932\n\nWe can create a system of equations with these two scenarios. First, let's solve the first equation for P:\n\nP = A1 / (1 + r)^2\n\nNow, let's substitute this expression for P into the second equation:\n\nA2 = (A1 / (1 + r)^2) * (1 + r)^3\nA2 = A1 * (1 + r)\n\nNow we can solve for r:\n\n22932 = 17640 * (1 + r)\n1 + r = 22932 / 17640\n1 + r = 1.3\n\nNow subtract 1 from both sides to find r:\n\nr = 1.3 - 1\nr = 0.3\n\nTo express r as a percentage, we multiply by 100:\n\nr = 0.3 * 100\nr = 30%\n\nTherefore, the annual interest rate is $\\boxed{30\\%}$ ."}
