{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_732941", "question": "A team of workers is doing repairs in an apartment. To avoid damaging the floor in a room (a checkered square with dimensions $4 \\times 4$), they laid out 13 two-cell rugs along the grid lines. Suddenly, it turned out that one rug was needed in another room. Prove that the workers will be able to choose a rug so that the repairs in the apartment can continue without damaging the floor.", "answer": "1. **Suppose the contrary**: assume it is not possible to remove a mat without leaving any part of the floor uncovered.\n\n2. **Covering Cells Analysis**: Since the mats are 2-cell covers, each mat must cover two cells that are currently not uncovered. Let's analyze the constraints.\n\n3. **Double Coverage and Single Coverage**:\n    - If we have 13 mats, each covering 2 cells, the total number of cells covered by the mats when placed on the grid would be:\n      \\[\n      2 \\cdot 13 = 26 \\text{ cells}\n      \\]\n    - The 4 by 4 cell grid consists of:\n      \\[\n      4 \\cdot 4 = 16 \\text{ cells}\n      \\]\n    \n4. **Double Counting Cells**:\n    - If it is not possible to remove any mat without uncovering the floor, then every mat must cover at least one cell that is only covered once. Hence, we can infer:\n      - At least 13 cells must be covered exactly once, because if a cell were covered twice or more, removing one mat would not uncover the floor at that cell.\n    \n5. **Remaining Cells Analysis**:\n    - Given that at least 13 cells are covered exactly once, the remaining cells (if any) must be covered by more than one mat. The number of remaining cells is:\n      \\[\n      16 - 13 = 3 \\text{ cells}\n      \\]\n    - These 3 cells must then be covered by more than one mat. Let us denote these cells as being doubly covered. If each cell can be doubly covered in up to 4 different placement configurations for a given grid configuration, then each cell can have at most:\n      \\[\n      2 \\times 3 = 6 \\text{ cells (considering double counting for 3 cells)}\n      \\]\n    \n6. **Total covered cells Calculation**:\n    - We calculated that potentially the total cells covered by mats is:\n      \\[\n      13 \\cdot 1 + 4 \\cdot 3 = 13 + 12 = 25 \\text{ cells}\n      \\]\n    - However, the initial assumption was that 13 mats must cover 26 cells, thus this leads to a contradiction as:\n      \\[\n      2 \\times 13 = 26 > 25\n      \\]\n\n7. **Conclusion**:\n    - Since 13 mats must adequately cover 26 cells but we calculated a contradiction that only 25 could be covered in the overlapping scenario, it infers that it is possible to remove one mat such without uncovering any floor cells.\n\nThus, the workers can remove one mat and continue the repair without exposing the floor. \n\n\\[\n\\blacksquare\n\\]"}
