{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_618422", "question": "If $x^2+bx+16$ has at least one real root, find all possible values of $b$. Express your answer in interval notation.", "answer": "For a quadratic equation to have at least one real root, the discriminant must be nonnegative.\nThe discriminant of $x^2+bx+16$ is $b^2-4(1)(16)=b^2-64$.\nSo, we want $b^2-64 \\ge 0$.\nThis inequality is satisfied when $b \\le -8$ or $b \\ge 8$.\nTherefore, the possible values of $b$ are $\\boxed{(-\\infty,-8] \\cup [8,\\infty)}$.\nThe answer is: (-\\infty,-8]\\cup[8,\\infty)"}
