{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_841217", "question": "I want to create a Java method that takes a list of strings and returns a new list of strings containing only the strings where the length is greater than 5. Can you provide me with a code example to solve this problem?", "answer": "Certainly! Here's an example of a Java method that achieves this:\n\n```java\npublic List<String> getStringsLongerThanFive(List<String> strings) {\n    List<String> stringsLongerThanFive = new ArrayList<String>();\n    for (String str : strings) {\n        if (str.length() > 5) {\n            stringsLongerThanFive.add(str);\n        }\n    }\n    return stringsLongerThanFive;\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `getStringsLongerThanFive` method takes a parameter `strings` which is the input list of strings. It creates a new `ArrayList` called `stringsLongerThanFive` to store the strings with a length greater than 5. \n\nNext, it iterates over each string in the input list using a for-each loop. Inside the loop, it checks if the length of the current string `str` is greater than 5 using the `length()` method. If it is, the string is added to the `stringsLongerThanFive` list using the `add()` method.\n\nFinally, the method returns the `stringsLongerThanFive` list containing only the strings with a length greater than 5.\n\nYou can call this method by passing your desired list of strings as an argument. The method will return a new list containing only the strings that meet the length criteria."}
