{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_910424", "question": "What is the purpose of \"require('module') .. exports = in node and how can you use it to set up for an API build?", "answer": "In Node.js, `require` and `exports` are used to implement the CommonJS module system, which allows developers to create and manage modules of reusable code.\n\n- `require('module')`: This function imports a module, allowing you to access its functionality. When you require a module, Node.js looks for a file with that name in the current directory, then in the parent directories, and finally in the global module directories. If the module is found, its contents are returned, and you can use them in your code.\n\n- `exports` or `module.exports`: These objects are used to expose functions, variables, or objects from a module, making them available to other parts of your application. Any property added to the `exports` object can be accessed from outside the module using the `require` function.\n\nHere's an example of how to use `require` and `exports` to set up a simple API build:\n\nLet's create a simple math module (`math.js`):\n\n```javascript\n// math.js\nfunction add(a, b) {\n  return a + b;\n}\n\nfunction subtract(a, b) {\n  return a - b;\n}\n\nmodule.exports = {\n  add,\n  subtract\n};\n```\n\nNow, let's create a main module (`app.js`) that uses the math module:\n\n```javascript\n// app.js\nconst math = require('./math');\n\nconst api = {\n  add: (req, res) => {\n    const { a, b } = req.body;\n    const result = math.add(a, b);\n    res.json({ result });\n  },\n  subtract: (req, res) => {\n    const { a, b } = req.body;\n    const result = math.subtract(a, b);\n    res.json({ result });\n  }\n};\n\n// Assuming you're using Express.js as your web framework\nconst express = require('express');\nconst app = express();\napp.use(express.json());\n\napp.post('/add', api.add);\napp.post('/subtract', api.subtract);\n\nconst port = 3000;\napp.listen(port, () => {\n  console.log(`API listening on port ${port}`);\n});\n```\n\nIn this example, the `math.js` module exports two functions: `add` and `subtract`. The `app.js` module imports the math module and uses its functions to implement two API endpoints: `/add` and `/subtract`."}
