{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_733893", "question": "Write a Python script snippet that Checks Whether a Number is Prime or Not\n ```python\ndef is_prime(num):\n    \"\"\"Check if number is prime.\"\"\"\n    # Your Code here\n\n# Driver Code\nnum = 25\nif is_prime(num):\n    print(f'{num} is a Prime Number')\nelse:\n    print(f'{num} is not a Prime Number')\n```", "answer": "```python\ndef is_prime(num):\n    \"\"\"Check if number is prime.\"\"\"\n    if num <= 1:\n        return False\n    for i in range(2, num):\n        if num % i == 0:\n            return False\n    return True\n\n# Driver Code\nnum = 25\nif is_prime(num):\n    print(f'{num} is a Prime Number')\nelse:\n    print(f'{num} is not a Prime Number')\n```\n\nHowever, this is not the most efficient solution for larger numbers as it checks divisibility up to the number itself. We can optimize it to only check up to the square root of the number:\n\n```python\nimport math\n\ndef is_prime(num):\n    \"\"\"Check if number is prime.\"\"\"\n    if num <= 1:\n        return False\n    for i in range(2, int(math.sqrt(num)) + 1):\n        if num % i == 0:\n            return False\n    return True\n\n# Driver Code\nnum = 25\nif is_prime(num):\n    print(f'{num} is a Prime Number')\nelse:\n    print(f'{num} is not a Prime Number')\n```"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_494625", "question": "What is the following argument's conclusion, what are its premisses, and is the argument sound?\n\n'Since the majority of investors believe the stock will go up and since the majority of stock analysts believe the stock will go up, it must be a good investment because if the majority of smart people share this view, their opinion must be the correct view.'\n\nIdentify the specific fallacy this argument is committing.", "answer": "The conclusion of this argument is that the stock is a good investment. The premisses are: \n\n1) the majority of investors believe the stock will go up, \n2) the majority of stock analysts believe the stock will go up, and \n3) if the majority of smart people share this view, their opinion must be the correct view.\n\nHowever, this argument is not sound. The problem lies in the assumption that the majority opinion, even if shared by smart people or experts, necessarily makes something true. This type of argument commits the \"appeal to authority\" fallacy, which is a specific type of the more general \"argumentum ad populum\" fallacy (also known as the \"appeal to popular opinion\" fallacy).\n\nThe \"appeal to authority\" fallacy occurs when an argument assumes that because an authority figure or a group of authority figures believe something, it must be true. However, this ignores the possibility that the authority figures may be wrong or that their opinions are not universally applicable to every individual's situation.\n\nIn this case, the argument assumes that the opinions of the majority of investors and analysts are sufficient to make the investment good, without considering other factors such as the investors' and analysts' track records, potential biases, or the underlying fundamentals of the stock itself. Therefore, the argument is unsound due to its reliance on a logical fallacy."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_40811", "question": "For how many integers \\( x \\) does a triangle with side lengths 12, 20, and \\( x \\) have all its angles acute?\n$\\textbf{(A)}\\ 4\\qquad \\textbf{(B)}\\ 5\\qquad \\textbf{(C)}\\ 6\\qquad \\textbf{(D)}\\ 7\\qquad \\textbf{(E)}\\ 8$", "answer": "First, apply the triangle inequality to establish possible values for \\( x \\):\n1. \\( 12 + 20 > x \\) → \\( x < 32 \\)\n2. \\( 12 + x > 20 \\) → \\( x > 8 \\)\n3. \\( 20 + x > 12 \\) → \\( x > -8 \\) (which is always true since \\( x \\) must be positive)\n\nUsing these inequalities, the possible values of \\( x \\) must satisfy \\( 8 < x < 32 \\).\n\nNext, we consider the condition for all acute angles:\n- To avoid right or obtuse angles, the square of the largest side must be less than the sum of the squares of the other two sides.\n\nFor \\( x \\) as the longest side (\\( x > 20 \\)):\n- We require \\( x^2 < 12^2 + 20^2 = 144 + 400 = 544 \\).\n- Hence, \\( x < \\sqrt{544} \\approx 23.3 \\).\n\nFor \\( 20 \\) as the longest side (when \\( 8 < x \\leq 20 \\)):\n- We need \\( 20^2 < 12^2 + x^2 = 144 + x^2 \\),\n- Thus, \\( 400 < 144 + x^2 \\) leading to \\( x^2 > 256 \\) and therefore \\( x > 16 \\).\n\nCombining these conditions:\n- \\( x \\) must be greater than 16 and less than approximately 23.3.\n- \\( x \\) must satisfy \\( 8 < x < 32 \\).\n\nThe integer values of \\( x \\) satisfying these conditions are \\( 17, 18, 19, 20, 21, 22, 23 \\).\n\nConclusion:\nThere are 7 integer values of \\( x \\) that satisfy the conditions for the triangle to have all acute angles. Thus, the answer is $7$.\nThe final answer is The final answer, considering the arithmetic and logical reasoning applied, is $\\boxed{\\textbf{(D)}\\ 7}$."}
