{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_283284", "question": "I have a string `brackets` which consists of characters \"(\" , \")\" , \"[\" , \"]\" , \"{\" , \"}\". I need to check if all types of brackets are correctly paired and correctly nested within each other. How can I achieve this using Go?", "answer": "You can use the following code in Go to check if the brackets are correctly paired and nested. \n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"strings\"\n)\n\nfunc CorrectBracketing(brackets string) bool {\n    stack := []rune{}\n    for _, c := range brackets {\n        switch c {\n        case '(', '[', '{':\n            stack = append(stack, c)\n        case ')', ']', '}':\n            if len(stack) == 0 {\n                return false\n            }\n            lastBracket := stack[len(stack)-1]\n            stack = stack[:len(stack)-1] // Pop from stack\n            if (c == ')' && lastBracket != '(') || (c == ']' && lastBracket != '[') || (c == '}' && lastBracket != '{') {\n                return false\n            }\n        default:\n            // Ignore non-bracket characters\n        }\n    }\n    return len(stack) == 0 // If stack is empty, all brackets were correctly paired\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we use a stack to solve the problem. The code iterates over the characters in the input string `brackets` one-by-one. If it encounters an opening bracket (i.e., '(', '[', or '{'), it pushes it onto the stack. If it encounters a closing bracket (i.e., ')', ']', or '}'), it pops the last bracket from the stack and checks if they match. If they don't match, or if there's nothing on the stack to pop, then the bracket balancing is incorrect.\n\nThe complexity of this algorithm is O(n), where n is the length of the input string `brackets`, because it iterates over the string once. It uses additional memory proportional to the input size in the worst case, when all brackets are opening brackets. Therefore, its space complexity is also O(n)."}
