{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_402790", "question": "The overall goal is to turn 23 \"on\" switches to all 23 being \"off\". You can turn an \"on\" switch to \"off\", but you cannot turn an \"off\" switch to \"on\". You can turn 3 switches at a time, but you cannot revisit a switch you've turned \"off\". This is a tough logic puzzle, but if you work through it correctly you can get all 23 switches turned \"off\" in 12 moves or less.", "answer": "To solve this problem, let's consider the total number of switches and how we can turn them off in the fewest number of moves possible. We're limited to turning three switches at a time and cannot revisit any switch that's already been turned off.\n\nIf we divide 23 by 3 (the number of switches that can be turned off at a time), we get 7 with a remainder of 2. This suggests that we'll need at least 8 moves to turn off 24 switches (if we had that many), since 7 * 3 is 21 and we'd still need to account for the remaining 3 switches. However, we only have 23 switches.\n\nTo optimize our solution, we can prioritize the first 21 switches, turning them off in 7 moves (21 divided by 3). This would leave us with 2 switches that are still on. We can then use one additional move to turn off these last two switches, but we'll need to include a \"dummy\" or sacrificial switch in the final move since we can only turn off 3 switches at a time and we can't revisit switches that are already off.\n\nHere's how we can approach it: \n\nTurn off switches 1-3, then 4-6, and so on until we turn off switches 19-21. At this point, we'll have turned off 21 switches in 7 moves. \n\nWe now have 2 switches left that are still on. Since we can only turn off 3 switches at a time and can't revisit switches that are already off, we need to include one of the switches we've already turned off as a \"dummy\" in the final move. \n\nHowever, we're not finished yet because we still have to figure out how to turn off the last two switches. We can do this in a few more moves. To minimize the total number of moves, we should turn off switches 22 and 23, and use one of the already-off switches as our third switch for the 8th move (the \"dummy\"). This still leaves a problem - switches 22 and 23 are turned off now, but we had to revisit one of the switches.\n\nInstead of going back and turning off switches in a straightforward manner, we can rearrange some of our moves so that one of the switches we'll use for our final move (with the two remaining \"on\" switches) is not turned off earlier. Consider that we could have left one switch on when we turned off the 21 switches. Instead of 7 moves for 21 switches and then turning off the remaining two switches with a \"dummy\" in the 8th move, we could leave one switch \"on\" from the first 21 switches, turn off switches 22 and 23, and then turn off the remaining switch we left \"on\" from the first 21. This would only require one additional move beyond the 8th move we initially thought we'd need.\n\nThe key is that we include one of the switches from the 21 we turned off as one of the switches to be turned off in the 8th move. We don't actually need to include one that's already \"off\" - we can simply leave it \"on\" initially. \n\nWe then only need a few more moves to account for the switches 22 and 23, along with the switch we left \"on\" from the initial 21 switches. However, this can be optimized by realizing we don't need to do these three separately. We can plan ahead and leave more switches \"on\" initially, ensuring that we can turn them all off in 12 moves or less.\n\nA better way to look at it would be to leave 4 switches \"on\" from the first 21 switches (turning off the other 17 in 6 moves - 17 divided by 3 with a remainder of 2 that's not needed since we're leaving more switches \"on\"). Then turn off 3 of the switches we left \"on\" along with switches 22 and 23 in the final moves - we need 2 additional moves beyond the initial 6 to account for the 4 remaining switches and switches 22 and 23."}
