{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_666619", "question": "A wire of length \\( 95 \\text{ m} \\) is cut into three pieces such that the length of each piece is \\( 50\\% \\) greater than the previous piece. What is the length of the largest piece?\nA) \\( 36 \\text{ m} \\)\nB) \\( 42 \\text{ m} \\)\nC) \\( 45 \\text{ m} \\)\nD) \\( 46 \\text{ m} \\)\nE) \\( 48 \\text{ m} \\)", "answer": "To find the length of the largest piece when a wire of length $95 \\, \\mathrm{m}$ is cut into three pieces, with each piece being $50\\%$ greater than the previous piece, we proceed as follows:\n\n1. **Let the length of the smallest piece be \\( v \\)**.\n   - This sets up our first piece of length \\( v \\).\n\n2. **Calculate the length of the middle piece**.\n   - The middle piece is $50\\%$ greater than the previous piece, so:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Length of the middle piece} = \\frac{3}{2} v\n   \\]\n\n3. **Calculate the length of the largest piece**.\n   - The largest piece is $50\\%$ greater than the middle piece, so:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Length of the largest piece} = \\frac{3}{2} \\left( \\frac{3}{2} v \\right) = \\frac{9}{4} v\n   \\]\n\n4. **Sum the lengths of the three pieces to equal the total wire length**.\n   - The equation for the total length of the wire is:\n   \\[\n   v + \\frac{3}{2} v + \\frac{9}{4} v = 95 \\, \\mathrm{m}\n   \\]\n\n5. **Combine the terms**.\n   - To combine like terms, it's helpful to have a common denominator:\n   \\[\n   v + \\frac{3}{2} v + \\frac{9}{4} v = \\frac{4v}{4} + \\frac{6v}{4} + \\frac{9v}{4} = \\frac{19v}{4}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Solve for \\( v \\)**.\n   - Setting the total length equal to $95 \\, \\mathrm{m}$:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{19v}{4} = 95\n   \\]\n   - Multiply both sides by $4$ to clear the fraction:\n   \\[\n   19v = 380\n   \\]\n\n7. **Isolate \\( v \\)**.\n   - Divide both sides by 19:\n   \\[\n   v = \\frac{380}{19} = 20 \\, \\mathrm{m}\n   \\]\n\n8. **Find the length of the largest piece**.\n   - Substituting \\( v = 20 \\, \\mathrm{m} \\) back into the length of the largest piece:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Length of the largest piece} = \\frac{9}{4} v = \\frac{9}{4} \\times 20 = 45 \\, \\mathrm{m}\n   \\]\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe length of the largest piece is \n\\[\n\\boxed{45 \\, \\mathrm{m}}\n\\]"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_861250", "question": "An inspector rejects 10% of the meters as defective. He examined a certain number of meters and found 15 defective ones. How many meters did he examine in total?", "answer": "Let's call the total number of meters the inspector examined \"x\". According to the problem, 10% of these meters are defective. So, 10% of x is equal to the number of defective meters found, which is 15.\n\nWe can set up the equation as follows:\n\n10% of x = 15\n0.10 * x = 15\n\nNow, we solve for x:\n\nx = 15 / 0.10\nx = 150\n\nTherefore, the inspector examined $\\boxed{150}$  meters in total."}
