{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_832097", "question": "I am creating a simple Python script to count how many different types of fruit are in my fruit salad. The script asks the user for the different fruits and then outputs the number of unique fruits. \n\nI want to add some error checking to handle cases where the user inputs the same fruit multiple times. \n\nHere is my script so far:\n\n```\ndef count_unique_fruits():\n    fruits = []\n    while True:\n        user_input = input(\"Enter a fruit (or 'done' to finish): \")\n        if user_input.lower() == 'done':\n            break\n        fruits.append(user_input)\n    return len(set(fruits))\n\nprint(\"Number of unique fruits:\", count_unique_fruits())\n```\n\nHow can I modify this script to handle cases where the user inputs the same fruit multiple times? \n\nAlso, I would like to convert all user inputs to lowercase to handle inputs like 'Apple' and 'apple' as the same fruit.", "answer": "You're already using a `set` to count unique fruits, which automatically removes duplicates. However, to handle cases where the user inputs the same fruit multiple times and to provide feedback to the user, you can modify your script as follows:\n\n```python\ndef count_unique_fruits():\n    fruits = set()\n    while True:\n        user_input = input(\"Enter a fruit (or 'done' to finish): \").strip().lower()\n        if user_input == 'done':\n            break\n        if user_input in fruits:\n            print(f\"You already added {user_input}. Please try again.\")\n        else:\n            fruits.add(user_input)\n    return len(fruits)\n\nprint(\"Number of unique fruits:\", count_unique_fruits())\n```\n\nIn this modified script:\n\n*   We convert the user input to lowercase using `lower()` to ensure 'Apple' and 'apple' are treated as the same fruit.\n*   We use `strip()` to remove leading and trailing whitespace from the user input.\n*   We check if the user input is already in the `fruits` set. If it is, we print a message and don't add it again.\n*   We use `add()` to add the user input to the `fruits` set if it's not already present.\n\nThis way, you handle duplicate inputs, provide feedback to the user, and accurately count the unique fruits in the fruit salad."}
