{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_229362", "question": "There are \\( n \\) boys \\( B_1, B_2, \\ldots, B_n \\) and \\( n \\) girls \\( G_1, G_2, \\ldots, G_n \\). Each boy ranks the girls in order of preference, and each girl ranks the boys in order of preference. Show that we can arrange the boys and girls into \\( n \\) pairs so that we cannot find a boy and a girl who prefer each other to their partners. For example, if \\((B_1, G_3)\\) and \\((B_4, G_7)\\) are two of the pairs, then it must not be the case that \\( B_4 \\) prefers \\( G_3 \\) to \\( G_7 \\) and \\( G_3 \\) prefers \\( B_4 \\) to \\( B_1 \\).", "answer": "To demonstrate that we can pair boys and girls such that no boy and girl prefer each other over their assigned partners, we will use the algorithm often referred to as the **Gale-Shapley algorithm** or **Stable Marriage Algorithm**. Here is a detailed, step-by-step solution:\n\n1. **Initialization**:\n   - There are \\( n \\) boys \\( \\{B_1, B_2, \\ldots, B_n\\} \\) and \\( n \\) girls \\( \\{G_1, G_2, \\ldots, G_n\\} \\).\n   - Each boy ranks all the girls in a strict order of preference.\n   - Each girl ranks all the boys in a strict order of preference.\n\n2. **Proposal Steps (Iterative Rounds)**:\n   - Start with all boys and girls being unpaired.\n   - In each round \\( k \\), each unpaired boy makes a proposal to the girl he ranks highest among those he has not yet proposed to.\n\n3. **Accepting and Rejecting Proposals**:\n   - If a girl \\( G \\) receives a proposal from a boy \\( B \\):\n     - If \\( G \\) is unpaired at the moment, she accepts the proposal and temporarily pairs with \\( B \\).\n     - If \\( G \\) is already paired with another boy \\( B'\\):\n       - \\( G \\) will compare \\( B \\) and \\( B' \\) based on her preference.\n       - If \\( G \\) prefers \\( B \\) over \\( B' \\), she will switch pairing to \\( B \\), leaving \\( B' \\) unpaired.\n       - If \\( G \\) prefers \\( B' \\) over \\( B \\), she will reject \\( B \\).\n\n4. **Termination of the Algorithm**:\n   - Each boy can propose to at most \\( n \\) girls, and since there are \\( n \\) boys, the process must terminate within \\( n^2 \\) rounds or fewer.\n\n5. **Ensuring All Boys and Girls are Paired**:\n   - Once paired, a girl remains paired, although her partner may change if a better option according to her preference comes along.\n   - If we assume, for contradiction, that a girl \\( G \\) remains unpaired at the end of the process, then there must be a boy \\( B \\) who is also unpaired (since \\( n \\) equals \\( n \\)).\n   - By algorithm design, \\( B \\) must have proposed to every girl including \\( G \\). Hence, \\( G \\) must have received a proposal and should be paired. Contradiction. Thus, every girl must be paired.\n\n6. **Stability**:\n   - We need to show that there are no two pairs \\((B, G)\\) and \\((B', G')\\) where:\n     - \\( B \\) prefers \\( G' \\) to \\( G \\)\n     - \\( G' \\) prefers \\( B \\) to \\( B' \\)\n   - Suppose, for contradiction, that such unstable pairs \\((B, G)\\) and \\((B', G')\\) exist. This implies \\( B \\) proposed to \\( G' \\) before \\( G \\) based on his preference.\n     - When \\( B \\) proposed to \\( G' \\):\n       - \\( G' \\) must have either been unpaired and accepted \\( B \\), or \\( G' \\) was paired with \\( B'' \\) whom she preferred over \\( B \\).\n     - If \\( G' \\) paired with \\( B'' \\) whom she preferred over \\( B \\), and later \\( G' \\) pairs with \\( B' \\), then \\( G' \\) must prefer \\( B' \\) over \\( B \\).\n   - Therefore, to have \\( G' \\) prefer \\( B \\) over \\( B' \\) contradicts the stability condition established by the algorithm.\n   - This contradiction proves that no such unstable pairs exist.\n\n### Conclusion:\nBy executing the above steps, we achieve a stable pairing where no boy and girl prefer each other over their assigned partners. Thus, the pairing is stable, achieving the stable marriage condition. \n\n$\\bla