{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_1007762", "question": "Show that the sum of the squares of the reciprocals of the positive integers is equal to pi^2/6.", "answer": "This result is a classic example in mathematics known as Basel's problem. The problem asks to show that the sum of the reciprocals of the squares of the positive integers is equal to π^2/6. Mathematically, we want to prove that:\n\n1 + 1/2^2 + 1/3^2 + 1/4^2 + ... = π^2/6\n\nTo approach this, we'll use the power of complex analysis, particularly the theory of Fourier series and the properties of trigonometric functions. \n\nThe starting point is the Fourier series of the function f(x) = x^2 on the interval [-π, π]. The Fourier series representation of this function can be derived, but we'll directly utilize the result, which is:\n\nx^2 = π^2/3 + 4 ∑[n=1 to ∞] (-1)^(n) cos(nx)/n^2\n\nHere, the summation runs from 1 to infinity. Evaluating this equation at x = 0, we get:\n\n0 = π^2/3 + 4 ∑[n=1 to ∞] (-1)^(n) /n^2\n\nHowever, we notice that (-1)^n simply alternates between 1 and -1 for odd and even values of n, respectively. So, we can rewrite this as:\n\n0 = π^2/3 + 4 (∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/(2n)^2 - ∑[n=0 to ∞] 1/(2n+1)^2)\n\nSimplifying the equation, we have:\n\n0 = π^2/3 - 4 (∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/(2n)^2 + ∑[n=0 to ∞] 1/(2n+1)^2 - 2∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/(2n)^2)\n\nNow, we know that ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2 = ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/(2n)^2 + ∑[n=0 to ∞] 1/(2n+1)^2. Using this, we can simplify further and obtain:\n\n0 = π^2/3 - 4 ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2 + 4 ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/(2n)^2\n\nNow, the sum we're interested in, ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2, can be expressed in terms of itself and the simplified equation above:\n\n∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2 = π^2/6 + ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/(2n)^2\n\nSubstituting the definition of the sum ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/(2n)^2 in terms of ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2, we get an expression which is ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2 = π^2/6 + (1/4) ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2\n\nCombining like terms:\n\n(3/4) ∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2 = π^2/6\n\nMultiplying both sides by 4/3, we arrive at the final answer:\n\n∑[n=1 to ∞] 1/n^2 = π^2/6\n\nThis proves that the sum of the reciprocals of the squares of the positive integers is indeed equal to π^2/6, establishing the solution to Basel's problem."}
