{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_877384", "question": "Given a list of integers, write a Python function that returns the first even number that is greater than 3. If no such number exists, return None. Use filtering and short-circuiting of a loop to implement this function.", "answer": "To find the first even number that is greater than 3, we can use list comprehension to filter the list and only keep the even numbers that are greater than 3. Then, we can use the `next()` function to return the first element from the filtered list. If the filtered list is empty, `next()` will return `None` by default.\n\n```python\ndef first_even_greater_than_3(numbers):\n    filtered_numbers = [\n        number\n        for number in numbers\n        if number % 2 == 0 and number > 3\n    ]\n    return next(iter(filtered_numbers), None)\n```"}
