{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_240761", "question": "Implement a Python function `intersects(rect1, rect2)` that takes two rectangles (each represented as a tuple of two tuples) and returns a boolean indicating whether they intersect or not. A rectangle is represented as a tuple of two points `(x1, x2)` and `(y1, y2)`, where `x1`, `x2`, `y1`, and `y2` are the respective Cartesian coordinates of the lower-left and upper-right corners of the rectangle. The intersection of two rectangles is defined as a rectangle, where the lower-left corner has the maximum x- and y-coordinates of the lower-left corners of the two rectangles, and the upper-right corner has the minimum x- and y-coordinates of the upper-right corners of the two rectangles.\n\nIf the two rectangles do not intersect, then return `False`. Otherwise, return `True`.\n\nYour code should pass the following assertions:\n```python\nassert intersects(((0, 0), (0, 0)), ((1, 1), (1, 1))) == False\nassert intersects(((2, 2), (4, 4)), ((5, 5), (7, 7))) == False\nassert intersects(((0, 0), (0, 0)), ((1, 1), (1, 1))) == False\nassert intersects(((0, 0), (2, 2)), ((3, 3), (5, 5))) == False\n```", "answer": "To check if two rectangles intersect, it is sufficient to check if their left and right edges, as well as their bottom and top edges, overlap. If any of these pairs of edges do not overlap, then the rectangles do not intersect.\n\nWe implement the `intersects` function using the following steps:\n\n1. Define the left, right, bottom, and top functions, which take a rectangle and return the left, right, bottom, and top edges of the rectangle, respectively.\n2. Define the `intersects` function, which takes two rectangles and returns a boolean indicating whether they intersect.\n3. Compute the left, right, bottom, and top edges of each rectangle using the `left`, `right`, `bottom`, and `top` functions.\n4. Check if the left and right edges of the two rectangles overlap.\n5. Check if the bottom and top edges of the two rectangles overlap.\n6. Return `True` if both pairs of edges overlap, and `False` otherwise.\n\nHere is the implementation of the `intersects` function:\n\n```python\ndef left(rect):\n    return rect[0][0]\n\ndef right(rect):\n    return rect[1][0]\n\ndef bottom(rect):\n    return rect[0][1]\n\ndef top(rect):\n    return rect[1][1]\n\ndef intersects(rect1, rect2):\n    left_edge_overlap = left(rect1) < right(rect2)\n    right_edge_overlap = right(rect1) > left(rect2)\n    bottom_edge_overlap = bottom(rect1) < top(rect2)\n    top_edge_overlap = top(rect1) > bottom(rect2)\n    return left_edge_overlap and right_edge_overlap and bottom_edge_overlap and top_edge_overlap\n```\n\nThis function implements the concept of finding the intersection of two rectangles. It takes two rectangles as input and returns a boolean indicating whether they intersect or not. The `left`, `right`, `bottom`, and `top` functions are used to obtain the edges of each rectangle. The `intersects` function checks if the left and right edges of the two rectangles overlap, and if the bottom and top edges of the two rectangles overlap. If both pairs of edges overlap, then the rectangles intersect, and `True` is returned. Otherwise, `False` is returned."}
