{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_843062", "question": "Given $$\\begin{vmatrix} \\cos\\alpha & \\sin\\alpha \\\\ \\sin\\beta & \\cos\\beta \\end{vmatrix}= \\frac {1}{3}$$, find the value of $\\cos2(\\alpha+\\beta)$.", "answer": "From the given determinant $$\\begin{vmatrix} \\cos\\alpha & \\sin\\alpha \\\\ \\sin\\beta & \\cos\\beta \\end{vmatrix}= \\frac {1}{3}$$, we can calculate the determinant as follows:\n\\begin{align*}\n\\cos\\alpha \\cdot \\cos\\beta - \\sin\\alpha \\cdot \\sin\\beta &= \\frac {1}{3}, \\\\\n\\therefore \\cos(\\alpha+\\beta) &= \\frac {1}{3}.\n\\end{align*}\n\nTo find $\\cos2(\\alpha+\\beta)$, we use the double angle formula:\n$$\\cos2\\theta = 2\\cos^2\\theta - 1.$$\nApplying this to $\\cos2(\\alpha+\\beta)$, we have:\n\\begin{align*}\n\\cos2(\\alpha+\\beta) &= 2\\cos^2(\\alpha+\\beta) - 1 \\\\\n&= 2\\left(\\frac {1}{3}\\right)^2 - 1 \\\\\n&= 2\\left(\\frac {1}{9}\\right) - 1 \\\\\n&= \\frac {2}{9} - 1 \\\\\n&= \\frac {2}{9} - \\frac {9}{9} \\\\\n&= -\\frac {7}{9}.\n\\end{align*}\n\nTherefore, the solution is $\\boxed{-\\frac {7}{9}}$."}
