{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_360322", "question": "Consider the general second-order differential equation of the form y'' + P(x)y' + Q(x)y = 0, where P(x) and Q(x) are continuous functions. If y1(x) and y2(x) are two linearly independent solutions to this differential equation, then the Wronskian W(y1, y2) is defined as W(y1, y2)(x) = y1(x)y2'(x) - y1'(x)y2(x). Prove that the Wronskian W(y1, y2) is equal to Ce^(-∫P(x)dx), where C is a constant.", "answer": "To prove that the Wronskian W(y1, y2) equals Ce^(-∫P(x)dx), we first differentiate W(y1, y2)(x) with respect to x, yielding W'(y1, y2)(x) = y1'(x)y2'(x) + y1(x)y2''(x) - y1''(x)y2(x) - y1'(x)y2'(x). We can simplify this expression to W'(y1, y2)(x) = y1(x)y2''(x) - y1''(x)y2(x).\n\nSince y1(x) and y2(x) are solutions to the differential equation y'' + P(x)y' + Q(x)y = 0, we can express y1''(x) and y2''(x) in terms of y1(x), y1'(x), y2(x), and y2'(x). Specifically, y1''(x) = -P(x)y1'(x) - Q(x)y1(x) and y2''(x) = -P(x)y2'(x) - Q(x)y2(x). Substituting these expressions into the equation for W'(y1, y2)(x), we get W'(y1, y2)(x) = y1(x)(-P(x)y2'(x) - Q(x)y2(x)) - (-P(x)y1'(x) - Q(x)y1(x))y2(x).\n\nThis simplifies to W'(y1, y2)(x) = -P(x)(y1(x)y2'(x) - y1'(x)y2(x)) - Q(x)(y1(x)y2(x) - y1(x)y2(x)). The latter term vanishes, and the equation reduces to W'(y1, y2)(x) = -P(x)(y1(x)y2'(x) - y1'(x)y2(x)) = -P(x)W(y1, y2)(x).\n\nThus, we have a first-order linear differential equation for the Wronskian: W'(y1, y2)(x) + P(x)W(y1, y2)(x) = 0. To solve this equation, we can use an integrating factor, which in this case is e^(∫P(x)dx). Multiplying both sides of the equation by the integrating factor, we get d/dx (W(y1, y2)(x)e^(∫P(x)dx)) = 0.\n\nIntegrating this equation with respect to x, we obtain W(y1, y2)(x)e^(∫P(x)dx) = C, where C is a constant. Dividing both sides by e^(∫P(x)dx), we finally get W(y1, y2)(x) = Ce^(-∫P(x)dx), as desired.\n\nThis result has significant implications in the theory of differential equations, as it provides a useful tool for determining whether two solutions are linearly independent. If the Wronskian is non-zero at any point, then the solutions are guaranteed to be linearly independent. The connection to the integrating factor highlights the underlying structure of the differential equation and illustrates the power of using mathematical techniques to uncover fundamental properties of solutions."}
