ame + \"_timestamp\", col(col_name).cast(\"timestamp\"))\n        \n        # Check if any row is not null\n        if df_timestamp.select(col_name + \"_timestamp\").filter(col(col_name + \"_timestamp\").isNotNull()).first():\n            # If successful, replace original column with new timestamp column\n            df = df_timestamp.drop(col_name).withColumnRenamed(col_name + \"_timestamp\", col_name)\n    except Exception as e:\n        # If casting fails, just ignore it and move on to the next column\n        pass\n\n# Write DataFrame to Hive table\ndf.write.saveAsTable(\"your_hive_table_name\")\n```\n\nYou can also use `udf` (User Defined Function) with regular expression to match timestamp formats.\n\n```python\nimport re\nfrom pyspark.sql.functions import col, udf\nfrom pyspark.sql.types import TimestampType\nfrom dateutil.parser import parse\n\ndef is_timestamp(s):\n    try:\n        return parse(s) is not None\n    except ValueError:\n        return False\n\nis_timestamp_udf = udf(is_timestamp, 'boolean')\n\n# Get all string columns\nstring_cols = [f.name for f in df.schema.fields if isinstance(f.dataType, StringType)]\n\n# Try to cast each string column to timestamp\nfor col_name in string_cols:\n    # Use udf to identify timestamp columns\n    df_timestamp = df.withColumn(col_name + \"_timestamp\", is_timestamp_udf(col(col_name)))\n    \n    # Count number of true values\n    count = df_timestamp.filter(col(col_name + \"_timestamp\") == True).count()\n    \n    # If count is greater than 0, it means column has timestamp data\n    if count > 0:\n        df = df.withColumn(col_name, col(col_name).cast(TimestampType()))\n\n# Write DataFrame to Hive table\ndf.write.saveAsTable(\"your_hive_table_name\")\n```\n\nNote: You can add or remove timestamp formats from the function `is_timestamp` based on your data. The current function checks for all the common timestamp formats. Also, the regular expression approach may not cover all possible timestamp formats. Ther