{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_757961", "question": "A snail is at the bottom of a 20-foot well. Each day, it climbs up 3 feet, but at night, it slips back 2 feet. How many days will it take for the snail to reach the top of the well?", "answer": "To solve this problem, let's analyze the snail's daily progress. The snail effectively climbs 1 foot per day, since it climbs 3 feet during the day and slips back 2 feet at night. \n\nHowever, on the day the snail reaches or surpasses the top of the well, it won't slip back down, as it will have already escaped the well. This means we need to consider the final climb separately.\n\nTo figure out how many days the snail needs to climb 18 feet (leaving 2 feet for the final day's climb), we divide 18 by 1 foot, which equals 18 days. \n\nOn the 19th day, the snail will climb 3 feet and reach a total height of 21 feet, which is more than the well's depth, but it won't slip back because it has already escaped. However, if we consider the well's depth of 20 feet, we realize that the snail will actually reach the top on the 18th day's climb (18 feet) plus the final 2 feet it needs to climb on the 19th day to reach 20 feet.\n\nSo, the snail will reach the top of the 20-foot well in 18 days of climbing 1 foot per day, and then on the 19th day, it climbs the final 2 feet, making it a total of 19 days, but counting the final climb as a full day, which includes climbing the last 3 feet to surpass the well, is a bit misleading. It actually reaches 20 feet, the top, after 18 days and the final 2 feet of the climb on the 19th day. Nonetheless, it is customary to count that final climb as the last day, so the answer is 18+1 or 19, the last being partial, but mostly referenced as 18 days to climb 18 feet and a final day for the last 2 feet."}
