{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_744789", "question": "Can someone explain the differences between a Rails Engine and a Mountable app? In Rails 3.1, you can create either one with the \"rails new plugin _ _\" command. When would you want to use one versus the other? Is it possible to package a Mountable App as a gem? What are the other differences between them?", "answer": "Certainly! Here are the main differences between a Rails Engine and a Mountable app:\n\n**Full Engine:**\n\nWith a full engine, the parent application automatically inherits the routes from the engine. You don't need to make any changes to the `parent_app/config/routes.rb` file. Simply specifying the engine gem in the `Gemfile` of the parent app is enough for it to inherit the models, routes, etc. The engine's routes are specified in the `my_engine/config/routes.rb` file:\n\n```ruby\nRails.application.routes.draw do \n  # whatever \nend\n```\n\nIn a full engine, there is no namespacing of models, controllers, etc. They are immediately accessible to the parent application.\n\n**Mountable Engine:**\n\nWith a mountable engine, the engine's namespace is isolated by default. This means that the engine's routes are namespaced, and the parent app can bundle this functionality under a single route. To define the routes for a mountable engine, you need to modify the `my_engine/config/routes.rb` file as follows:\n\n```ruby\nMyEngine::Engine.routes.draw do \n  # whatever \nend\n```\n\nThen, in the `parent_app/config/routes.rb` file, you can mount the engine and specify the route under which it should be accessible:\n\n```ruby\nParentApp::Application.routes.draw do \n  mount MyEngine::Engine => \"/engine\", :as => \"namespaced\"\nend\n```\n\nIn a mountable engine, models, controllers, etc. are isolated from the parent application. However, helpers can be easily shared between the engine and the parent app.\n\nIn summary, a full engine is best used as a standalone application adjacent to the parent app, as it does not isolate itself from the parent application. Name clashes between the engine and the parent app could occur in this case. On the other hand, a mountable engine is useful when you want to avoid name conflicts and bundle the engine's functionality under a specific route in the parent application.\n\nI hope this helps clarify the differences between a Rails Engine and a Mountable app! If you have any further questions, please let me know."}
