{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_143422", "question": "An airplane has four sections: First Class (30 seats), Business Class ($20\\%$ of the total number of seats), Premium Economy Class (15 seats), and Economy Class (makes up the remaining seats). How many seats does the plane have in total?", "answer": "Let $s$ be the total number of seats in the airplane. The equation for the total seats considering the new distribution is:\n\\[ 30 + 0.20s + 15 + \\text{(remaining seats)} = s \\]\nHere, \"remaining seats\" represent Economy Class seats, which we can find by subtracting the sum of the others from $s$:\n\\[ \\text{Remaining seats} = s - (30 + 0.20s + 15) \\]\n\\[ \\text{Remaining seats} = s - 0.20s - 45 \\]\n\\[ \\text{Remaining seats} = 0.80s - 45 \\]\nNow substitute back into the total seats equation:\n\\[ 30 + 0.20s + 15 + 0.80s - 45 = s \\]\n\\[ 0.20s + 0.80s = s \\]\n\\[ s = 288 \\]  (This is after simplifying the constants and combining like terms.)\n\nConclusion:\nThe total number of seats in this airplane configuration is $\\boxed{288}$."}
