{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_677643", "question": "You are given an integer array nums and an integer k. Find the number of unique k-diff pairs in the array. A k-diff pair is a pair of numbers in the array where the absolute difference between them is k. Notice that (1, 3) and (3, 1) are considered the same pair.\n\nExamples\nInput: nums = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5], k = 2\nOutput: 2\n\nExplanation: There are two 2-diff pairs in the array, (1, 3) and (3, 5). Although we have two 1s in the input, we should only return 2.\n\nInput: nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5], k = 1\nOutput: 4\n\nExplanation: There are four 1-diff pairs in the array, (1, 2), (2, 3), (3, 4) and (4, 5).\nInput: nums = [1, 3, 1, 5, 4], k = 0\nOutput: 1\n\nExplanation: There is one 0-diff pair in the array, (1, 1).\nInput: nums = [1,2,4,4,3,3,0,9,2,3], k = 3\nOutput: 2\n\nExplanation: There are two 3-diff pairs in the array, (0, 3) and ( (3, 6) N/A  however we do have (4,1).\nInput: nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5], k = 10\nOutput: 0\n\nConstraints:\n\n*   1 <= nums.length <= 104\n*   -107 <= nums[i] <= 107\n*   0 <= k <= 107\n\n\nHere is the starting point of the code.\n\nclass Solution:\n    def findPairs(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        if k < 0:\n            return 0\n\n        seen = set()\n\n        count = 0\n\n        nums.sort()\n        for i, v in enumerate(nums):\n\n            # Check the case that k equals 0\n            if k == 0:\n                if v in seen:\n                    count += 1\n                    nums = [x for x in nums if x != v]\n                seen.add(v)\n            else:\n\n                if v - k in seen:\n                    count += 1\n\n                seen.add(v)\n        return count\n\nThis isn't correct though. If k is not 0, this can double count pairs. Come up with a way that correctly counts the unique k-diff pairs.", "answer": "To avoid double counting, we can modify the code to only count the pairs when the smaller number in the pair is encountered. Here's the updated code:\n\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def findPairs(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:\n        if k < 0:\n            return 0\n\n        seen = set()\n        pairs = set()\n\n        nums.sort()\n        for v in nums:\n            if k == 0:\n                if v in seen:\n                    pairs.add(v)\n            else:\n                if v - k in seen:\n                    pairs.add((v - k, v))\n            seen.add(v)\n        return len(pairs)\n```\n\nIn this updated code, we use a set `pairs` to store the unique pairs. When `k` is 0, we directly add the number to the `pairs` set. When `k` is not 0, we add the pair `(v - k, v)` to the `pairs` set. Since sets automatically eliminate duplicates, this ensures that we only count each pair once. Finally, we return the length of the `pairs` set, which represents the number of unique k-diff pairs."}
