{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_965775", "question": "A snail is at the bottom of a 20-foot well. Each day, it climbs up 3 feet, but at night, it slips back 2 feet. How many days will it take for the snail to reach the top of the well?", "answer": "To solve this problem, let's analyze the snail's movement pattern. The snail climbs 3 feet during the day and slips back 2 feet at night, making a net progress of 1 foot each day.\n\nHowever, when the snail reaches the top of the well, it won't slip back at night because it will already be out of the well. This means that on the day the snail reaches the top, its progress won't be reduced by the nighttime slip.\n\nSince the well is 20 feet deep, the snail will need 18 days to climb 18 feet, making 18 feet of net progress. On the 18th day, the snail will climb 3 feet, reaching 21 feet, but this exceeds the well's depth. \n\nSo, on the 18th day, the snail is already at 18 feet. On the 19th day, the snail will climb the final 2 feet to reach 20 feet and get out of the well. Thus, it will take the snail 18 days to climb to 18 feet and the 19th day to climb out of the well, resulting in 18 + 1 = 19 days for the snail to reach the top of the well and escape."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_502477", "question": "Ten vectors are such that the length of the sum of any nine of them is less than the length of the sum of all ten vectors. Prove that there exists an axis such that the projection of each of the ten vectors onto this axis is positive.", "answer": "1. **Define the Given Vectors:**\n\n   Let the given vectors be \\(\\boldsymbol{e}_1, \\boldsymbol{e}_2, \\ldots, \\boldsymbol{e}_{10}\\). \n\n2. **Sum of All Vectors:**\n\n   We denote the sum of all 10 vectors by \\(\\overrightarrow{AB} = \\boldsymbol{e}_1 + \\boldsymbol{e}_2 + \\cdots + \\boldsymbol{e}_{10}\\).\n\n3. **Vector Subtraction and Squaring:**\n\n   Consider any vector \\(\\boldsymbol{e}_i\\). The squared length of \\(\\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i\\) is given by:\n\n   \\[\n   \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2 = \\left(\\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i\\right) \\cdot \\left(\\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i\\right)\n   \\]\n\n4. **Expanding the Dot Product:**\n\n   We expand the dot product using the distributive property:\n\n   \\[\n   \\left(\\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i\\right) \\cdot \\left(\\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i\\right) = (\\overrightarrow{AB} \\cdot \\overrightarrow{AB}) - 2 (\\overrightarrow{AB} \\cdot \\boldsymbol{e}_i) + (\\boldsymbol{e}_i \\cdot \\boldsymbol{e}_i)\n   \\]\n\n   This simplifies to:\n\n   \\[\n   \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2 = AB^2 - 2 (\\overrightarrow{AB} \\cdot \\boldsymbol{e}_i) + \\left| \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2\n   \\]\n\n   where \\(AB = \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} \\right|\\).\n\n5. **Isolating the Dot Product:**\n\n   Rearrange the above equation to isolate the dot product \\((\\overrightarrow{AB}, \\boldsymbol{e}_i)\\):\n\n   \\[\n   2 (\\overrightarrow{AB} \\cdot \\boldsymbol{e}_i) = AB^2 + \\left| \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2 - \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2\n   \\]\n\n   Thus:\n\n   \\[\n   (\\overrightarrow{AB} \\cdot \\boldsymbol{e}_i) = \\frac{AB^2 + \\left| \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2 - \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2}{2}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Condition from Problem Statement:**\n\n   Given that the length of the sum of any 9 vectors is less than the sum of the lengths of all 10 vectors, we have:\n\n   \\[\n   AB > \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|\n   \\]\n\n   From this, it follows that:\n\n   \\[\n   AB^2 > \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2\n   \\]\n\n   Therefore:\n\n   \\[\n   AB^2 + \\left| \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2 > \\left| \\overrightarrow{AB} - \\boldsymbol{e}_i \\right|^2\n   \\]\n\n7. **Conclusively Positive Dot Product:**\n\n   Hence, the expression for \\((\\overrightarrow{AB}, \\boldsymbol{e}_i)\\) will be strictly positive:\n\n   \\[\n   (\\overrightarrow{AB} \\cdot \\boldsymbol{e}_i) > 0\n   \\]\n\n8. **Positive Projection Conclusion:**\n\n   Since the dot product \\((\\overrightarrow{AB}, \\boldsymbol{e}_i)\\) is positive, it follows that the projection of each vector \\(\\boldsymbol{e}_i\\) onto the direction of \\(\\overrightarrow{AB}\\) (the axis defined by \\(A\\) and \\(B\\)) is positive.\n\n### Conclusion:\n   Therefore, there exists an axis (the direction of \\(\\overrightarrow{AB}\\)) such that the projection of each of the ten vectors onto this axis is positive.\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{}\n\\]"}
