{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_158157", "question": "What is the remainder when the polynomial P(x) = x^4 - 6x^3 + 16x^2 - 25x + 10 is divided by x - 2?", "answer": "This problem can be solved using the Remainder Theorem, which states that if a polynomial P(x) is divided by x - a, then the remainder is given by P(a). In our case, we need to find P(2).\n\nSubstituting x = 2 into the polynomial, we get:\nP(2) = (2)^4 - 6(2)^3 + 16(2)^2 - 25(2) + 10\nP(2) can be calculated as 16 - 48 + 64 - 50 + 10.\n\nCombining like terms and simplifying this expression, we find that P(2) is equal to -8.\n\nThus, the remainder when P(x) is divided by x - 2 is -8."}
