{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_310163", "question": "The slope of the line $y=\\sqrt{3}x$ is ( ).\n\nA: $30^{\\circ}$\n\nB: $60^{\\circ}$\n\nC: $90^{\\circ}$\n\nD: Does not exist", "answer": "To find the slope of the line given by $y=\\sqrt{3}x$, we observe that the coefficient of $x$ is directly the slope. Thus, the slope of this line is $\\sqrt{3}$. \n\nThe slope of a line is also related to its angle of inclination $\\theta$ with the positive direction of the x-axis through the formula $\\tan(\\theta) = \\text{slope}$. Therefore, we have $\\tan(\\theta) = \\sqrt{3}$. \n\nRecalling our trigonometric identities, we know that $\\tan(60^{\\circ}) = \\sqrt{3}$. This means that the angle of inclination $\\theta$ of our line is $60^{\\circ}$.\n\nTherefore, the correct answer is $\\boxed{\\text{B}}$."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_641209", "question": "Write a Python function that accepts an integer `n` and returns an integer with the first `n` bits set to 1. Use bit shifts to achieve this without using loops or recursion.\n\nYour code should pass the following assertions:\n```python\nassert set_first_n_bits(8) == 255\nassert set_first_n_bits(10) == 1023\nassert set_first_n_bits(3) == 7\nassert set_first_n_bits(6) == 63\n```", "answer": "To set the first `n` bits to 1, we can use bit shifts to shift the number 1 `n` times to the left, and then subtract 1 to make all the bits to the left of the first `n` ones 1 as well.\n\nFor example, if `n` is 3, we want to shift 1 to the left 3 times to get 1000. Then we subtract 1 to get 111.\n\nHere is how you could implement this function:\n\n```python\ndef set_first_n_bits(n: int) -> int:\n    return (1 << n) - 1\n```\n\nThis function uses bit shifts to shift the number 1 `n` times to the left. Then it subtracts 1 to make all the bits to the left of the first `n` ones 1 as well."}
