{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_717830", "question": "By . Paul Donnelley . PUBLISHED: . 06:57 EST, 19 March 2014 . | . UPDATED: . 11:01 EST, 19 March 2014 . A hopeless romantic is suing a dating site after a man he met online conned him out of $70,000. Michael Picciano, 65, from Little Neck, an upper middle-class neighbourhood of Queens, New York, where a one-bedroom flat can cost up to $200,000, signed up to OkCupid in the hope of meeting Mr Right. Picciano says in his Manhattan lawsuit that OkCupid and its parent company, IAC, did not carry out ‘even minimal screening of its subscribers and therefore deceptively creating the impression that their dating service was safe. . . when in fact . . . [it] was a trap for the unwary’. OkCupid bills itself as 'the best free dating site on Earth' and so Michael Picciano was not wary when he received a message from 'genuineguy62' The New Yorker was excited when on February 11, 2013 he received a message from ‘genuineguy62’. Picciano said that he ‘felt safe’ and ‘trusted’ his online match, supposedly a man named Bruce Thompson, simply because ‘Thompson’ had a profile on OkCupid, which bills itself as ‘the best free dating site on Earth’, reports the New York Post. The following month, Picciano and ‘Thompson’ were in contact via phone, Skype and email. ‘Thompson’ said that since ‘they had found each other’ there was no need for them to continue on the site and they should delete their accounts – Picciano agreed. Picciano was ‘comfortable’ enough with his new love to send him $24,000 ‘for unexpected fees he incurred in his dealings setting up a new computer-parts business’. He was not suspicious when ‘Thompson’ asked for the money to be sent to ‘Dennis E. Racer’ in Addison, Texas, and ‘Edmond Thebeau’ in Canada. In April, when asked by ‘Thompson’, Picciano sent a further $46,420 to ‘MacBenson and Associates’ in Britain through his Capital One bank account. Silver surfer: More older people are looking for love online laying them open to scams (File photo) That month, the penny finally dropped and after a friend helped Picciano track 'Thompson' down on a site called malesscammers.com, he went to the police.at the 111th Precinct in Queens. ‘It was apparent that Mr Thompson had used the same Cleveland, Ohio-based phone number and the same email address. . . with Mr Picciano that he had used to perpetrate other frauds,’ the lawsuit says. The police told to stay in touch with ‘Thompson’ who then sent him a forged cheque and a loan note but no fingerprints could be found and the authorities could not . trace the software used to create the phony cheque. Picciano is also suing his bank, Capital One, for failing 'to comply with proper procedures for the transmission of wire funds'. Picciano claims that ‘Thompson’ is still conning people on the site, using the name ‘bigheartedbt’. Both Picciano and OkCupid refused to comment.", "answer": "Michael Picciano, a 65-year-old man from Little Neck, Queens, New York, is suing the dating site OkCupid and its parent company, IAC, after being conned out of $70,000 by a man he met online. Picciano, who signed up to OkCupid in search of a romantic partner, received a message from a user named 'genuineguy62,' who claimed to be Bruce Thompson. Picciano trusted Thompson because of his profile on the site, which bills itself as \"the best free dating site on Earth.\" Over the following months, Thompson convinced Picciano to send him a total of $70,420, purportedly for business expenses and other fees. The money was sent to various individuals in different countries, including Texas, Canada, and Britain.\n\nPicciano eventually realized he had been scammed after a friend helped him identify Thompson on a website listing known scammers. He reported the fraud to the police, but the authorities were unable to trace the scammer or find any usable evidence. Picciano is also suing his bank, Capital One, for failing to follow proper procedures for wire transfers. The lawsuit alleges that OkCupid did not adequately"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_917680", "question": "Consider a square with side length 1.  Let P be a point within the square, such that the distances from point P to the top and left sides of the square are both x.  Thus, the distance from point P to the bottom and right sides of the square are both 1 - x.  Now consider a line segment drawn from the bottom right corner of the square to point P, and another line segment from the top left corner to point P.  If the lengths of the two line segments are equal, what is the value of x?", "answer": "This problem can be solved by using the Pythagorean theorem. We can start by drawing the square and labeling the relevant distances. Let's denote the distance from the bottom right corner to point P as d. Since the line segments from the bottom right corner and top left corner to point P are equal, we have two right-angled triangles with legs of length x and 1 - x, and hypotenuse d.\n\nUsing the Pythagorean theorem, we can express the length d in terms of x for the bottom right triangle: d² = x² + (1 - x)². Similarly, for the top left triangle, d² = (1 - x)² + x².\n\nSince the lengths of the line segments are equal, we can equate the two expressions: x² + (1 - x)² = (1 - x)² + x². However, this equation is an identity, meaning it holds true for all values of x. This result is expected because the equation simply confirms that the distances are equal.\n\nTo find the value of x, we need to take a closer look at the problem. Let's simplify the equation d² = x² + (1 - x)² by expanding it: d² = 2x² - 2x + 1.\n\nNow, for the top left triangle, we can express d² as: d² = (1 - x)² + x² = 1 - 2x + x² + x² = 2x² - 2x + 1.\n\nNotice that we have a symmetry between x and (1 - x) in these expressions. This suggests that a specific value of x might provide a simple solution. To explore this, let's try to find a value of x that makes the two expressions for d² simplify further.\n\nFrom the symmetry of the expressions, we can infer that x might be equal to (1 - x), which would lead to x = 1/2. Let's verify this solution by plugging x = 1/2 into the equation d² = 2x² - 2x + 1: d² = 2(1/2)² - 2(1/2) + 1 = 1/2.\n\nSince this value of x satisfies the equation and the given conditions of the problem, we can conclude that x = 1/2 is indeed the solution."}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_668098", "question": "I am writing an essay about parenting. I'd like to convey that the way most parents discipline their children is not the best way and offer an alternative. Here is my first paragraph:\n\n\"Raising children can be one of the most challenging jobs imaginable, yet most parents aren't formally trained for the task. As a result, they often default to practices they learned from their own childhood. This can lead to improper discipline methods, including yelling, physical punishment, or using rewards and punishments to control behavior. Not only can these methods be ineffective, but they can also cause long-term damage to a child's self-esteem and emotional intelligence.\"\n\nHow can I improve this paragraph?", "answer": "Your paragraph effectively introduces the challenges of parenting and highlights the potential pitfalls of traditional discipline methods. To further enhance it, consider a few minor adjustments to improve clarity and flow:\n\nYou might rephrase the opening sentence to make it more engaging and specific. For instance, \"Parenting is a profoundly demanding role, yet one that often comes without formal guidance or support.\" This modification helps set the stage for the discussion of inadequate training.\n\nThe phrase \"improper discipline methods\" could be reworded for more precision. Consider replacing it with \"outdated or punitive approaches\" to better convey the idea that these methods are not only ineffective but also potentially damaging.\n\nThe last sentence effectively raises the stakes by mentioning long-term consequences. However, to make it even more impactful, you could specify what you mean by \"ineffective\" in the context of these methods. This might become: \"Not only can these approaches fail to address underlying issues and encourage positive behavior, but they can also cause long-term damage to a child's self-esteem and emotional intelligence.\"\n\nHere's the revised paragraph:\n\n\"