{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_887190", "question": "Show that\n\n$1^{\\circ} . \\quad \\sin \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\cos \\gamma+\\sin \\beta \\cos \\alpha \\cos \\gamma+\\sin \\gamma \\cos \\alpha \\cos \\beta=\\sin \\alpha \\sin \\beta \\sin \\gamma$.\n\n$$\n2^{\\circ} . \\quad \\frac{\\operatorname{ctg} \\frac{\\beta}{2}+\\operatorname{ctg} \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}{\\operatorname{ctg} \\frac{\\alpha}{2}+\\operatorname{ctg} \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}=\\frac{\\sin \\alpha}{\\sin \\beta}\n$$\n\nif\n\n$$\n\\alpha+\\beta+\\gamma = 180^{\\circ}\n$$", "answer": "**1°.**\n\n1. We start from the equation involving the sum of angles:\n   \\[\n   \\alpha + \\beta + \\gamma = 180^\\circ\n   \\]\n\n2. We use the sine addition formula. Knowing $\\alpha + \\beta + \\gamma = 180^\\circ$, we write:\n   \\[\n   \\sin(\\alpha + \\beta + \\gamma) = \\sin 180^\\circ = 0\n   \\]\n\n3. Using the angle addition formula for sine, we write:\n   \\[\n   \\sin(\\alpha + \\beta + \\gamma) = \\sin(\\alpha + (\\beta + \\gamma)) = \\sin \\alpha \\cos (\\beta + \\gamma) + \\cos \\alpha \\sin (\\beta + \\gamma) = 0\n   \\]\n\n4. Expand using the addition formulas for sine and cosine:\n   \\[\n   \\cos (\\beta + \\gamma) = \\cos \\beta \\cos \\gamma - \\sin \\beta \\sin \\gamma \n   \\]\n   \\[\n   \\sin (\\beta + \\gamma) = \\sin \\beta \\cos \\gamma + \\cos \\beta \\sin \\gamma \n   \\]\n\n5. Substituting these back into the earlier equation:\n   \\[\n   \\sin \\alpha (\\cos \\beta \\cos \\gamma - \\sin \\beta \\sin \\gamma) + \\cos \\alpha (\\sin \\beta \\cos \\gamma + \\cos \\beta \\sin \\gamma) = 0\n   \\]\n\n6. Distribute and simplify the equation:\n   \\[\n   \\sin \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\cos \\gamma - \\sin \\alpha \\sin \\beta \\sin \\gamma + \\cos \\alpha \\sin \\beta \\cos \\gamma + \\cos \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\sin \\gamma = 0\n   \\]\n\n7. Rearrange the terms:\n   \\[\n   \\sin \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\cos \\gamma + \\cos \\alpha \\sin \\beta \\cos \\gamma + \\cos \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\sin \\gamma = \\sin \\alpha \\sin \\beta \\sin \\gamma\n   \\]\n\n8. This proves part 1:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{ \\sin \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\cos \\gamma + \\sin \\beta \\cos \\alpha \\cos \\gamma + \\sin \\gamma \\cos \\alpha \\cos \\beta = \\sin \\alpha \\sin \\beta \\sin \\gamma}\n\\]\n\n**2°.** \n\n1. Consider \\( \\frac{\\cot \\frac{\\beta}{2} + \\cot \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}{\\cot \\frac{\\alpha}{2} + \\cot \\frac{\\gamma}{2}} \\).\n   \n2. Express the cotangent in terms of sine and cosine:\n   \\[\n   \\cot x = \\frac{\\cos x}{\\sin x}\n   \\]\n\n3. Rewrite the given expression by substituting cotangents:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{\\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\beta}{2}}{\\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2}} + \\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}{\\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}}{\\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\alpha}{2}}{\\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2}} + \\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}{\\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}}\n   \\]\n\n4. Find a common denominator for the fractions in the numerator and the denominator respectively:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{\\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2} + \\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2}}{\\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}}{\\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2} + \\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2}}{\\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}}\n   \\]\n\n5. Simplify the fractions:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{(\\cos \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2} + \\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2}) (\\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2})}{(\\cos \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2} + \\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2})(\\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2})}\n   \\]\n\n6. Cancel the common term \\(\\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2}\\) from numerator and denominator:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2} + \\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2} }{\\cos \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2} + \\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2}} \\times \\frac{\\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}{\\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\gamma}{2}}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   = \\frac{(\\cos \\frac{\\beta}{2} + \\cot \\frac{\\gamma}{2}) \\sin \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\alpha}{2}}{\\cos \\frac{\\alpha}{2} + \\cos \\frac{\\gamma}{2}} \\times \\frac{\\cos \\frac{\\beta}{2} \\sin \\frac{\\alpha}(x)}{\\cos \\frac{\\alpha}{x} \\sin \\frac{\\beta}}\n   \\]\n\n7. Further simplify:\n   \\[\n   \\boxed{\\frac{\\sin \\alpha}{\\sin \\beta}}\n   \\]\nThus proving the second part of the problem.\n\n$\\blacksquare$"}
