{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_622779", "question": "By . Sarah Griffiths . It is said that there are plenty more fish in the sea, but the popular maxim no longer holds true as fish are said to be on the road to extinction. Reports in 2010 found that over-fishing and pollution is depleting the world's fish stocks, and now a team of scientists claims to have discovered how. They state that 90 per cent of fish larvae are biologically doomed to die just days . after hatching, because of the viscosity, or 'stickiness' of the water in which they are born. On the verge of extinction? A team of scientists have found that 90 per cent of fish larvae (pictured) are biologically doomed to die just days after hatching because pollution makes the water they're born into viscous, and this slows them down when looking for food . Around 90 per cent of fish larvae are biologically doomed to die just days after hatching. The study found that ‘hydrodynamic starvation,’ or the physical inability to feed due to environmental incompatibility, is the reason so many fish larvae perish. The ‘stickiness’ or the viscosity of ocean water hampers the larvae’s attempts to feed. ‘All that determines the larvae's feeding ability is viscosity - not age, not development – only their interaction with the surrounding water, Dr Holzman explained. ‘Because the water molecules around you have weak electrical bonds, only a thin layer sticks to your skin - a mere millimetre thick. If you're a large organism, you hardly feel it. ‘But if you're a three-millimetre-sized larva, dragging a millimetre of water across your body will prevent you from propelling forward to feed. ‘So really, it’s all about larval size and its ability to grow fast and escape the size where it feels the water as viscous fluid.’ The researchers found that in less viscous water, the larvae improved their feeding ability and in theory, this water would increase their survival rate. And this stickiness is increased by pollution. A scarcity of fish spells disaster for . over a billion people around the world who are dependent on fish for . their main source of protein. The study, by Roi Holzman and Victor China of the Department of Zoology at Tel Aviv University, follows the 2010 report by the United Nations Environment Program. The research, which was conducted at the Inter-University Institute for Marine Sciences in Eilat, and published in PNAS, suggests that ‘hydrodynamic starvation,’ or the physical inability to feed due to environmental incompatibility, is the reason so many fish larvae perish. Nearly all fish species reproduce externally – releasing and abandoning their sperm and eggs into the water. The fertilised eggs hatch within a couple of days and the larvae must feed themselves. They had previously fed on a yolk sac – a membrane joined to an embryo to provide early nourishment in the form of yolk – but once hatched, the vast majority die. ‘We . thought, something is going on during this period, in which the . proportional number of larvae dying is greatest,’ Dr Holzman said. ‘Our goal was to pinpoint the mechanism causing them to die. Disaster looming: A scarcity of fish spells disaster for over a billion people around the world who are dependent on fish for their main source of protein. A major report in 2010 blamed pollution levels and overfishing for the state of affairs. A fisherman casting his net in a lake in southern India is pictured . 'We saw that even under the best controlled conditions, 70 per cent of fish larvae were dying within the two weeks known as the 'critical period,' when the larvae detach from the yolk sac and open their mouths to feed,’ said Dr. Holzman. Dr Holzman said that using their understanding of the mechanism that kills off fish larvae, could help 'find a solution to the looming fish crisis in the world'. A school of larval fish is pictured . Over two years, the researchers observed fish larvae at three significant points in their development - at eight, 13 and 23-days-old, or the beginning, middle, and end of that ‘critical period’. They found that the ‘stickiness’ or the viscosity of the surrounding ocean water was hampering the larvae’s attempts to feed. Polluted seawater is typically more viscous than clean water, and cooler water is slightly gloopier than warmer bodies of water. ‘All that determines the larvae's feeding ability is viscosity - not age, not development – only their interaction with the surrounding water, Dr Holzman explained. ‘Because the water molecules around you have weak electrical bonds, only a thin layer sticks to your skin - a mere millimetre thick. If you're a large organism, you hardly feel it. ‘But if you're a three-millimetre-sized larva, dragging a millimetre of water across your body will prevent you from propelling forward to feed. ‘So really, it’s all about larval size and its ability to grow fast and escape the size where it feels the water as viscous fluid.’ The researchers found that in less viscous water, the larvae improved their feeding ability and in theory, this water would increase their survival rate. ‘We conclude that hydrodynamic starvation is the reason for their dying,’ Dr. Holzman said. ‘Imagine eating soup with a fork – that's what it's like for these larvae. They're not developed enough at the critical point to adopt the constrained feeding strategy of adult-sized, better-developed fish.’ Dr Holzman said that by using their . understanding of the mechanism that kills off the majority of the . world’s fish larvae, it could help ‘find a solution to the looming fish . crisis in the world.’ Armed with . this knowledge of the larvae's biological flaw, the researchers are . currently patenting a solution to maintain higher survival rates among . fish larvae populations.", "answer": "Scientists from Tel Aviv University have discovered that 90 percent of fish larvae are biologically doomed to die shortly after hatching due to a phenomenon called \"hydrodynamic starvation.\" This occurs because the viscosity, or \"stickiness,\" of the water hampers the larvae's ability to feed. The study, conducted by Dr. Roi Holzman and Victor China, found that the thin layer of water that adheres to the larvae's skin due to weak electrical bonds significantly impedes their movement and feeding capabilities. This issue is exacerbated by pollution, which increases water viscosity, and cooler water, which is more viscous than warmer water.\n\nThe researchers observed fish larvae at three key developmental stages and found that the larvae's feeding ability is solely determined by the viscosity of the surrounding water, not their age or development stage. In less viscous water, the larvae's feeding ability improved, potentially increasing their survival rate. The study suggests that this mechanism, known as hydrodynamic starvation, is the primary reason for the high mortality rate among fish larvae.\n\nThis finding is particularly concerning as over a billion people worldwide rely on fish as their main source of protein. The 2010 United Nations Environment Program report had already highlighted the depletion of fish stocks due to overfishing and pollution"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_696906", "question": "You are a creative writing assistant. The following is an idea for a science fiction novel: contact with a distant planet reveals an ancient alien city on the once-thought uninhabited planet, frozen in time, yet there are no signs of struggle with or disappearance of the aliens. In this scenario the crew of the spaceship is from Earth in the year 2254. A robot has been sent to explore the alien city.", "answer": "What an intriguing concept. The mysterious abandonment of an entire alien city is a compelling puzzle for your crew to unravel. As the robot ventures into the city, it could stumble upon eerie yet fascinating sights: towering spires that hum with a gentle, residual energy; perfectly preserved marketplaces with strange, exotic goods still on display; and grand, sweeping architecture that seems to defy gravity.\n\nThe robot's initial findings could spark a flurry of questions among the crew. Were the aliens wiped out by some catastrophic event, or did they simply vanish into thin air? Was the city abandoned in a state of panic, or was it a deliberate, calculated departure? Perhaps the aliens had reached a point of technological advancement where they could simply transcend their physical forms, leaving behind their sprawling metropolis as a relic of a bygone era.\n\nAs the crew begins to analyze the robot's discoveries, they may start to notice subtle inconsistencies in the city's frozen-in-time state. A faint, almost imperceptible vibration emanating from the city's central square, or a series of strange, hieroglyphic-like symbols etched into the walls, could hint at a more complex, mysterious narrative. The crew's investigation could lead them to uncover clues that challenge their initial assumptions and force them to reevaluate the nature of the alien city and its long-lost inhabitants.\n\nThe robot, as it navigates the city, may encounter strange, surreal landscapes that blur the lines between technology and nature. It could stumble upon vast gardens filled with strange, bioluminescent plants, or massive, crystalline structures that seem to be imbued with an otherworldly essence. These discoveries could raise questions about the aliens' relationship with the natural world and whether their disappearance was somehow tied to the planet's unique properties.\n\nWhat would you like to explore next? The crew's reaction to the robot's findings, the alien city's mysterious energy signature, or perhaps the implications of the aliens' disappearance on a universal scale?"}
{"id": "general_smoltalk_2300_837079", "question": "Tell me how to write an essay.", "answer": "Writing an essay typically begins with a clear understanding of the topic, purpose, and audience. Here's a general guide to get you started:\n\nStart by defining the topic and understanding what's being asked of you. Identify the key questions you need to address. Develop a thesis statement that encapsulates your main argument or point. This statement should be specific, concise, and argue a specific claim.\n\nNext, organize your ideas into a logical structure. Typically, this includes an introduction, body paragraphs, and a conclusion. The introduction sets the stage for your argument, providing background information and context. The thesis statement usually appears at the end of the introduction.\n\nBody paragraphs should each have a clear topic sentence and supporting evidence or analysis. Ensure that each paragraph flows logically from one to the next, using transitional phrases to connect your ideas. Aim for a clear and concise writing style, avoiding unnecessary jargon and overly complex language.\n\nWhen supporting your argument, use a variety of evidence, such as academic sources, statistics, and real-life examples. Make sure to properly cite any sources you use to avoid plagiarism.\n\nYour conclusion should summarize your main points and reiterate your thesis statement. It should also leave the reader with something to think about, whether it's a call to action or a final thought on the topic.\n\nOnce you've written your first draft, revise and edit your work. Check for clarity, grammar, and punctuation errors. Ask someone to review your work and provide feedback.\n\nFinally, proofread your essay carefully before submitting it. This will help you catch any final errors and ensure your work is polished and professional.\n\nRemember, writing an essay takes time and practice. Don't be discouraged if it doesn't come easily at first. With patience and persistence, you can develop the skills to write clear and effective essays."}
